WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:03.740
- We're talking about a society
that was right in the middle

00:00:04.260 --> 00:00:08.240
of one of the main corridors of
empire building and new religions

00:00:08.300 --> 00:00:13.500
in the world. This is the most dangerous
neighborhood that you can possibly live in.

00:00:13.680 --> 00:00:18.880
- 26 emperors were murdered
in a period of 50 years.

00:00:18.940 --> 00:00:20.860
- Yes. It's tremendous instability.

00:00:21.020 --> 00:00:24.880
- Almost all were of these emperors
were generals, and almost all were

00:00:24.920 --> 00:00:31.200
murdered by their men. So civil war was
the norm, hyperinflation, economic crash,

00:00:31.580 --> 00:00:34.540
plus there's a plague.
There's just a lot of chaos.

00:00:34.760 --> 00:00:38.340
- Here's why I don't think the
Eastern Roman Empire is a military

00:00:38.360 --> 00:00:42.120
dictatorship. Even though, again,
the emperors control the armies,

00:00:43.120 --> 00:00:47.560
and the armies themselves
will often have a say in,

00:00:48.500 --> 00:00:52.370
Who becomes emperor, like through the
civil wars that we mentioned. The reason

00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:55.890
why I don't think it's a
military dictatorship is because

00:00:55.960 --> 00:01:03.410
they almost never, very, very, very rarely
use the army as an instrument of social

00:01:03.500 --> 00:01:07.200
control. Sometimes these eunuchs
were extremely competent

00:01:07.280 --> 00:01:11.120
like Narses, Justinian's general, who
defeated the Goths in Italy in this

00:01:11.200 --> 00:01:15.060
massive battle. Like, this guy was a
total hardass. And he's this little

00:01:15.140 --> 00:01:19.020
old man. He was- he was very old, and he was
tiny, and he was a eunuch, and the Goths

00:01:19.060 --> 00:01:22.440
laughed at him, but he had the last laugh.

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:28.500
- The following is a conversation
with Anthony Kaldellis, a

00:01:28.540 --> 00:01:34.700
historian of the Eastern Roman Empire,
also known as the Byzantine Empire.

00:01:35.600 --> 00:01:39.560
This is a Lex Fridman podcast. To support
it, please check out our sponsors in the

00:01:39.600 --> 00:01:43.170
description, where you can
also find links to contact me,

00:01:43.540 --> 00:01:46.970
ask questions, give
feedback, and so on. And

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:50.680
now, dear friends, here's
Anthony Kaldellis.

00:01:52.120 --> 00:01:55.860
You've described that the
Byzantine Empire is the Roman

00:01:56.040 --> 00:01:59.870
Empire, that calling it the
Byzantine Empire is an invention of

00:01:59.880 --> 00:02:03.560
historians writing long after
the empire has collapsed,

00:02:04.060 --> 00:02:07.940
that the people of that time
considered themselves Romans, and that

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:11.620
the so-called Byzantine Empire never
actually existed, that it was,

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:15.460
in every legal and cultural
sense, the Roman Empire

00:02:15.880 --> 00:02:23.520
continuing unbroken. So let's get our terms
right in the grand historical context.

00:02:24.020 --> 00:02:28.300
What is the Byzantine Empire, and why
should we just call it the Roman Empire?

00:02:28.640 --> 00:02:32.560
- So Lex, the burden of proof is on those
who would assert that what we've been

00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:35.140
calling the Byzantine
Empire is something other-

00:02:35.150 --> 00:02:39.109
... than the Roman Empire, because all of our sources
are very clear about this. And we've known about

00:02:39.120 --> 00:02:42.700
this. We've always known about it. It's
almost a form of cognitive dissonance, right?

00:02:42.740 --> 00:02:46.790
It's like when you know something is the
case, but you carry on as if it's not.

00:02:47.120 --> 00:02:51.080
So the Eastern Roman Empire,
this is the direct continuation

00:02:51.120 --> 00:02:54.660
of the ancient Roman Empire in the East,
right? Everybody knows the Western Empire

00:02:54.700 --> 00:02:56.109
fell in the fifth century.

00:02:57.340 --> 00:03:01.300
And for many conceptions of Western history,
that was sufficient. Like, that's when

00:03:01.340 --> 00:03:04.240
we just called it. The Roman
Empire fell in the fifth century.

00:03:05.100 --> 00:03:09.080
And we kinda, yeah, we kinda know that the
eastern half survived, but we don't wanna include

00:03:09.140 --> 00:03:12.920
that in our cultural genealogy. And
so we kinda pretend that it became

00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:16.860
something else. But in fact, it called
itself the Roman Empire. Its subjects were

00:03:16.900 --> 00:03:20.600
Roman citizens. They called themselves Romans
all the way down through to the end and

00:03:20.680 --> 00:03:25.900
beyond. So there are a number of
reasons why Western Europeans wanted to

00:03:25.960 --> 00:03:29.950
think that the Eastern Empire is something
different, and those reasons have

00:03:30.040 --> 00:03:31.420
created these models where

00:03:32.560 --> 00:03:36.320
They were, they called it Empire of the Greeks
for 1,000 years, then they switched to Byzantine

00:03:36.380 --> 00:03:39.990
Empire for very political
reasons. Now that's collapsing.

00:03:40.440 --> 00:03:44.300
So we're now moving into a phase where
we have the long Roman Empire. We,

00:03:44.340 --> 00:03:47.650
we recognize that the history of
the Roman state, the Roman polity,

00:03:48.490 --> 00:03:51.070
is something that lasts an
extraordinarily long time.

00:03:51.400 --> 00:03:55.049
Very unique almost in
history, from antiquity,

00:03:55.360 --> 00:03:58.440
like the archaic period,
down to the 15th century.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:00.560
- I think it would be really
nice to actually look

00:04:01.400 --> 00:04:05.180
just for a brief moment at
the grand scale of the,

00:04:05.280 --> 00:04:11.100
the full Roman state as it
lasted for over 2,200 years.

00:04:11.440 --> 00:04:11.700
- Yeah.

00:04:11.980 --> 00:04:20.560
- So its founding, 753 BC, to let's say
the fall of Constantinople in 1453 AD.

00:04:21.399 --> 00:04:25.260
So can we try to give a big picture
overview of everything that happened?

00:04:25.820 --> 00:04:29.740
- Okay, so first we have a period of the
kings. This is almost legendary, from

00:04:29.780 --> 00:04:33.710
like the eighth century
BC down to around 510 BC.

00:04:34.120 --> 00:04:36.680
So this is when Rome is ruled
by a series of local kings.

00:04:37.560 --> 00:04:41.240
The kings are expelled, and the
republic, or what we call the republic,

00:04:41.480 --> 00:04:45.440
is instituted, and this is a
regime that's governed by mostly

00:04:45.620 --> 00:04:49.520
an aristocracy, but with
cooperation from the

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:53.300
people of Rome. In various ways,
the arrangements change over the

00:04:53.360 --> 00:04:55.840
centuries. So that lasts
for about five centuries.

00:04:56.920 --> 00:05:00.520
And then we have the end of the republic
in the era of Julius Caesar and

00:05:00.560 --> 00:05:05.750
Augustus Caesar, when the civil wars lead
to the creation of an imperial monarchy...

00:05:05.880 --> 00:05:09.730
...right, under Augustus. So that's,
we date that roughly either,

00:05:10.180 --> 00:05:14.160
yeah, 27 BC, something like
that. And thereafter, it is an

00:05:14.200 --> 00:05:16.920
imperial monarchy for the
next millennium and a half.

00:05:17.940 --> 00:05:21.920
Very broadly, we can divide that
into two phases, one where the

00:05:21.940 --> 00:05:26.340
center of power is in Rome, and
one where it's in Constantinople.

00:05:26.469 --> 00:05:30.180
And, you know, we can debate the dates
of when that transition takes place.

00:05:30.780 --> 00:05:34.600
These big transitions usually take place over
long periods of time. They're not, like,

00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:41.580
very sudden. So that's the big picture.
Kings, republic, imperial monarchy.

00:05:42.220 --> 00:05:46.000
- The Roman Kingdom, the Roman
Republic, the Roman Empire.

00:05:46.200 --> 00:05:46.340
- Yes.

00:05:46.620 --> 00:05:49.080
- And then the West and East Roman Empire.

00:05:49.280 --> 00:05:50.000
- Yes.

00:05:50.120 --> 00:05:53.180
- Uh, and then maybe what are the
different terms that we could be

00:05:53.280 --> 00:05:58.300
using for the Byzantine
Empire, including Byzantium?

00:05:59.660 --> 00:06:03.120
Is it also fair to say
the Late Roman Empire?

00:06:03.460 --> 00:06:07.180
- So Late Roman Empire we use for
both east and west, starting

00:06:07.260 --> 00:06:10.960
around the reign of Diocletian maybe,
even a bit earlier, so during the third

00:06:11.020 --> 00:06:16.840
century AD. And that goes down to maybe
the early seventh century. So that

00:06:16.880 --> 00:06:19.040
period we call Late Roman Empire. And

00:06:20.050 --> 00:06:23.710
if you ask me to define its principal
characteristics, it would probably

00:06:23.790 --> 00:06:27.020
be the tax system and the
administration, the bureaucracy...

00:06:27.050 --> 00:06:30.550
...of the later Roman Empire
is that that comes from mostly

00:06:30.570 --> 00:06:32.690
Diocletian and Constantine's reforms.

00:06:32.710 --> 00:06:35.329
- And Diocletian was in the 3rd century.

00:06:35.450 --> 00:06:39.330
- Yes, 284 to 305 AD. Yes. A
very important reformer.

00:06:39.910 --> 00:06:43.330
- And we'll talk about it, but let's just do
this whirlwind, and hopefully there'll be

00:06:43.370 --> 00:06:46.270
automagical images
somewhere overlaid, but-

00:06:46.470 --> 00:06:46.850
- Okay.

00:06:46.910 --> 00:06:54.730
- So in 753 BC, Rome, a small city state,
is founded, and in 509 BC, the kings are

00:06:54.770 --> 00:07:02.340
overthrown, and the Roman Republic is born.
390 BC, the Gauls sack Rome, and this, I

00:07:02.410 --> 00:07:06.119
believe, among other events throughout
its history, is a formative

00:07:06.230 --> 00:07:09.820
trauma that hardens Rome's
security obsession.

00:07:10.970 --> 00:07:14.910
It turns out, throughout
its history, people want to

00:07:14.930 --> 00:07:18.690
attack from different directions,
and so you have to defend. So

00:07:19.150 --> 00:07:22.860
there's two wars, as we're actually
saying off mic. There's two kinds

00:07:22.930 --> 00:07:31.120
of military operations. One is wars
of conquest and expansion, and one is

00:07:31.170 --> 00:07:34.810
more defensive. And we'll
talk about how the military

00:07:34.850 --> 00:07:39.930
changes throughout its history to allocate
more effort to one versus the other.

00:07:40.790 --> 00:07:44.550
In 264 to 146 BC, the Punic

00:07:44.630 --> 00:07:48.410
Wars and the survival against Hannibal
transform Rome into a Mediterranean

00:07:48.450 --> 00:07:55.570
superpower. Then like you
mentioned, Caesar in 49 to 31 BC,

00:07:55.590 --> 00:07:59.490
Caesar's crossing of the Rubicon
to assassination of Caesar to

00:07:59.530 --> 00:08:03.430
the Battle of Actium, and
then the Civil War dismantles

00:08:03.450 --> 00:08:10.670
the Republic and concentrates power in a
single ruler, Octavian, AKA Augustus, the

00:08:10.750 --> 00:08:17.150
first Roman emperor, let's say. Then
27 BC, Augustus founds the Principate,

00:08:17.870 --> 00:08:21.530
really low-key monarchy. And
so officially, that ends the

00:08:21.570 --> 00:08:28.150
Republic, and then that begins, 27 BC
to 180 AD, the Pax Romana, which is a

00:08:28.170 --> 00:08:32.059
period of relative peace and stability.
And a lot of the emperors we know of,

00:08:32.370 --> 00:08:36.010
the sexy, popular emperors
all come from that period.

00:08:36.070 --> 00:08:40.050
Marcus Aurelius, who I'm a big fan
of, from that period. Then that

00:08:40.090 --> 00:08:43.250
takes us to 284 AD, the guy we mentioned,

00:08:43.290 --> 00:08:48.030
Diocletian, who rebuilds the state.
Emperors drop the first citizen mask,

00:08:49.150 --> 00:08:52.790
this perception of the way, and we'll
talk about this, the persona that's

00:08:52.810 --> 00:09:00.570
presented by the state. 312 AD,
Constantine defeats Maxentius at the

00:09:00.630 --> 00:09:04.619
Milvian Bridge to become the sole ruler of
the western half of the empire, and then

00:09:04.670 --> 00:09:12.500
founds Constantinople in 330 AD. East
and West are split in 395 AD. Visigoths

00:09:12.650 --> 00:09:20.390
sack Rome in 410 AD. The West falls
at 476 AD as the last Western

00:09:20.490 --> 00:09:27.330
emperor is deposed. And then we sort of
focus more on the East Roman Empire with

00:09:27.570 --> 00:09:31.010
527. In the 6th century,
Justinian's reign.

00:09:31.810 --> 00:09:35.770
In the 7th century, Heraclius defeats
Persia and then loses against

00:09:35.790 --> 00:09:39.470
the Arabs. There's the Arab
conquest continuing in the 7th

00:09:39.530 --> 00:09:45.310
century. In the 8th the Arab
siege of Constantinople fails.

00:09:46.430 --> 00:09:50.290
There's the Macedonian dynasty in that you

00:09:50.330 --> 00:09:54.260
have an excellent book about.
And then the Crusades,

00:09:54.730 --> 00:10:01.870
and then eventually leading to
Constantinople falling in 1453 AD.

00:10:02.710 --> 00:10:06.650
As a person who understands
the full journey of it with

00:10:06.710 --> 00:10:10.650
a focus on East Roman history,
is there obvious glaring

00:10:10.770 --> 00:10:14.830
holes or incorrect things
in what I just said?

00:10:14.990 --> 00:10:19.790
- No, nothing incorrect. I would say
if you wanted to produce a sort of

00:10:20.930 --> 00:10:28.770
very swift timeline of its history, it's
obviously important to focus on the

00:10:28.850 --> 00:10:32.520
moments when lots of territory was

00:10:32.550 --> 00:10:36.090
lost to foreign invaders, and
these are actually three main

00:10:36.130 --> 00:10:39.690
moments. There's the Arab conquests in the

00:10:39.990 --> 00:10:46.950
630s. This is a decade. In a decade,
that war was lost. It is the Seljuk Turk

00:10:47.250 --> 00:10:52.180
conquest of Asia Minor,
modern Turkey, in the 1070s,

00:10:53.210 --> 00:10:58.850
and that was very swift and partly
reversed afterwards, but only partly.

00:10:59.700 --> 00:11:03.550
And then there's the Fourth
Crusade, 1204, when the armies from

00:11:03.590 --> 00:11:07.490
mostly France sack, conquer Constantinople,
and dismember the empire as

00:11:07.530 --> 00:11:11.430
much as they could. It didn't last
that long. The Romans managed to

00:11:11.470 --> 00:11:17.690
regroup and recover but those are the three
main crisis points. They are very swift,

00:11:18.550 --> 00:11:20.530
but they cause incredible damage.

00:11:22.110 --> 00:11:25.870
For all the rest of its
history, it is a state and

00:11:25.930 --> 00:11:33.070
society that is generally sort of
consolidating, you know, regrouping,

00:11:33.590 --> 00:11:41.380
and generally engaged in slow but steady
economic growth, territorial expansion on a

00:11:41.470 --> 00:11:42.940
small scale, but steady.

00:11:43.550 --> 00:11:47.490
Uh, so we can talk about this. It's...
I think it's an important thing

00:11:47.550 --> 00:11:51.850
to keep in mind about the big
picture, that the defeats were swift

00:11:52.870 --> 00:12:00.010
and kind of, you know, terrible. But most
of its history is one of slow growth.

00:12:00.510 --> 00:12:04.350
- There's some traumatic events
that have a big impact, but a

00:12:04.410 --> 00:12:08.010
lot of the developments
we'll talk about it might

00:12:08.510 --> 00:12:11.130
seem or feel like there's
a particular moment

00:12:12.070 --> 00:12:15.870
when those developments or changes in the
way the government or the military is

00:12:15.930 --> 00:12:18.710
structured arise, but really
it's a gradual process.

00:12:18.850 --> 00:12:19.330
- Exactly.

00:12:19.350 --> 00:12:21.770
- And so that's the tension we have
to be constantly dancing with.

00:12:21.850 --> 00:12:25.730
- Yeah, so as historians, this is a point
of method, and it's very important. There

00:12:25.790 --> 00:12:29.540
are moments when, like, individuals
with a great deal of power

00:12:30.130 --> 00:12:33.800
make choices that impact everybody
else and have, you know, long-term

00:12:33.870 --> 00:12:35.090
consequences downstream.

00:12:36.170 --> 00:12:39.050
Constantine's conversion to
Christianity, for example, right?

00:12:39.890 --> 00:12:43.490
Not something that anybody could
have or did predict. Okay.

00:12:44.810 --> 00:12:48.390
Otherwise, most of the
developments that we identify by

00:12:48.410 --> 00:12:52.330
specific dates, like you mentioned 395, the
division of the eastern and the western

00:12:52.390 --> 00:12:57.710
empires, those are conventional dates that
we use to actually capture what is in

00:12:57.750 --> 00:13:01.010
fact a much longer process. There
was no split between the two

00:13:01.050 --> 00:13:04.910
halves. It was one among many

00:13:04.970 --> 00:13:08.689
allocations of jurisdiction to, like, one
son and another son in the east and the

00:13:08.750 --> 00:13:13.830
west. The two halves were subsequently
reunited, then they kind of

00:13:13.870 --> 00:13:17.640
divided again among different
emperors. It's just a process,

00:13:17.810 --> 00:13:21.470
and so we sometimes use fixed dates
for what is in fact a process. Or for

00:13:22.030 --> 00:13:25.930
76, the fall of the Western Empire,
that's just the last date. It's

00:13:25.990 --> 00:13:28.659
actually a very long
process that took decades.

00:13:29.170 --> 00:13:32.910
Right? So that's just something to keep in mind,
that sometimes we're talking about processes,

00:13:32.930 --> 00:13:36.790
sometimes we're talking about very discrete
events with long-term consequences. Yeah.

00:13:37.550 --> 00:13:41.530
- Maybe an impossible question
for a Roman state that lasted

00:13:41.670 --> 00:13:45.410
over 2,200 years, but is
there a kind of through

00:13:45.470 --> 00:13:49.130
line, a thread, a soul that runs
through the entire history of the Roman

00:13:49.190 --> 00:13:52.530
Empire? As you said, it's a slow

00:13:52.610 --> 00:13:56.590
transformation and evolution.
But if we dare call the whole

00:13:56.670 --> 00:13:59.770
thing Roman, Rome, the Roman state-

00:14:00.090 --> 00:14:00.250
- Yes

00:14:00.350 --> 00:14:05.130
- ... is there some aspect, some characteristics
that run through the whole thing?

00:14:05.930 --> 00:14:10.430
- I think so, yes. By the way, you know
the metaphor of the Ship of Theseus?

00:14:10.650 --> 00:14:14.470
Okay. So in case the audience doesn't know it,
this is when there's a ship, and it's, you know,

00:14:14.670 --> 00:14:18.510
at sea, and over time, like,
every component of that ship

00:14:18.610 --> 00:14:22.390
is replaced with some other component,
so that by the end of the story, it

00:14:22.450 --> 00:14:26.190
has none of the original
parts. But it's, like, in a

00:14:26.250 --> 00:14:30.030
certain sense still that ship because
of the story, right? The... Okay.

00:14:30.570 --> 00:14:34.340
So Roman history is different
from, let's say, Greek history

00:14:34.630 --> 00:14:38.570
or Christian history, right? Christian
history is the story of a religion. It can be

00:14:38.610 --> 00:14:42.520
in any country, among any ethnic group.
It's here, there, right? It's everywhere.

00:14:43.130 --> 00:14:44.890
But you still have
histories of Christianity.

00:14:45.910 --> 00:14:48.930
It's the same with, like
say, Greek culture-

00:14:48.970 --> 00:14:52.670
... or your Greek literature, right?
It's not a function of a particular

00:14:52.770 --> 00:14:55.970
state. Ancient Greeks were
famously never united in a state.

00:14:56.630 --> 00:15:00.490
But it's people who culturally accept that

00:15:00.530 --> 00:15:04.390
tradition as their kind of elite
prestige culture and engage

00:15:04.430 --> 00:15:08.110
with Homer and Plato and so
forth. And they can be anywhere.

00:15:08.890 --> 00:15:12.870
Roman history is not like that. Roman history
is very specifically the history of a

00:15:13.330 --> 00:15:16.930
state or a political
community. And so this is the

00:15:16.970 --> 00:15:20.950
community of the Roman people,
the Roman citizens. And it

00:15:21.030 --> 00:15:24.890
is in gradual evolution, but at no
point is there a rupture in that

00:15:24.930 --> 00:15:28.760
history such that its members
would ever think that something

00:15:28.830 --> 00:15:32.550
dramatic had changed, and that
they're no longer part of that

00:15:32.650 --> 00:15:36.510
story. So in the same way as
the ship I just mentioned,

00:15:36.670 --> 00:15:40.490
in other words, it's the narrative that
you tell about it where the changes that

00:15:40.530 --> 00:15:45.520
take place to it make sense only when you
see them within the context of that story.

00:15:45.770 --> 00:15:49.370
It's the same with Roman history. Yes,
there are changes. Like, eventually

00:15:49.450 --> 00:15:53.350
everything changes. But it happens
so gradually that it doesn't

00:15:53.450 --> 00:15:55.190
seem that way to anyone living in it.

00:15:56.110 --> 00:15:59.650
And so the narrative of
the history of the Roman

00:15:59.690 --> 00:16:02.530
people is what holds all of this together.

00:16:02.610 --> 00:16:06.590
- How important is it that, so you
mentioned Greek culture. So a lot

00:16:06.610 --> 00:16:09.610
of my friends who are Greek are
extremely proud of being Greek.

00:16:10.730 --> 00:16:12.550
There's certain cultures that are proud.

00:16:12.670 --> 00:16:12.970
- Sure.

00:16:13.270 --> 00:16:17.200
- And it's not a momentary
ephemeral thing. It feels

00:16:17.230 --> 00:16:19.970
like a thing that has lasted
for many generations.

00:16:20.010 --> 00:16:20.280
- Oh, yeah.

00:16:20.350 --> 00:16:23.850
- And so that is an engine
that propagates through

00:16:23.910 --> 00:16:27.870
time that carries that
culture forward. And so does

00:16:27.890 --> 00:16:31.830
a similar thing apply for the Roman
Empire in a different way? Maybe

00:16:31.910 --> 00:16:36.030
because you say it's a political kind of
community, that means a set of ideals.

00:16:36.870 --> 00:16:40.630
And we'll talk about, because
those ideals become even more

00:16:40.690 --> 00:16:44.610
concretized and explicit, I
think, through the East Roman

00:16:44.670 --> 00:16:48.030
Empire, because one of the things
you talk about is that the

00:16:48.130 --> 00:16:53.760
citizens of the empire are kind
of all connected, that they are—

00:16:53.760 --> 00:16:57.730
... engaged in this whole sort of
machinery. Anyway, that's a complicated way

00:16:57.770 --> 00:17:01.490
of asking, is there some
elements that Greek

00:17:01.550 --> 00:17:06.400
pride, dare I speak, is there some kind
of Roman pride that propagates the thing?

00:17:06.450 --> 00:17:13.690
- Oh, there totally is. You can find authors
and historical agents who definitely

00:17:13.730 --> 00:17:16.920
display this or talk about it.
But we don't want to make that

00:17:17.610 --> 00:17:21.170
the center of the story or the basis for
any analysis because... So what you're

00:17:21.210 --> 00:17:25.150
observing in your Greek friends is also
the result of modern nation building,

00:17:25.350 --> 00:17:29.320
is it's the result of modern systems of
education, and sort of national identities,

00:17:29.370 --> 00:17:32.729
and these are fostered and created
through all kinds of media and

00:17:32.770 --> 00:17:36.390
institutions. It's just a different
situation altogether. What you

00:17:36.430 --> 00:17:44.290
find in ancient republics or medieval
states is more something like a consensus

00:17:45.010 --> 00:17:49.790
to be ruled, to be, to rule and to be ruled
in this particular political community.

00:17:50.670 --> 00:17:54.650
Now, some members of it may definitely, and
in fact did have this kind of pride. I'll

00:17:54.690 --> 00:17:58.650
give you an example. So there's an ambassador
in the sixth century, and he's concluding

00:17:58.690 --> 00:18:02.440
a deal with the Persians. And you
know, the Persians are skeptical

00:18:02.470 --> 00:18:05.770
cause, you know, Romans can't always be
trusted. But this guy says to them, he says,

00:18:06.690 --> 00:18:10.570
and let me just tell you, you're
making a deal here with the Romans.

00:18:10.790 --> 00:18:13.610
The Romans. The name should say it all."

00:18:13.690 --> 00:18:17.370
Like, you, okay, and you get a sense that this
is, he's expressing a certain pride in, like,

00:18:17.670 --> 00:18:21.430
being a bearer of the Roman tradition and
speaking for the emperors and the Roman Empire.

00:18:21.470 --> 00:18:25.290
I mean, that's, for him, this was something
very, very momentous. You find these kinds of

00:18:25.330 --> 00:18:28.790
examples, so these people exist. But I
wouldn't want to make that the basis

00:18:28.830 --> 00:18:34.530
for like an analysis of how
the society works as a whole.

00:18:34.550 --> 00:18:38.490
For the most part, it was something
like a consensus where, you

00:18:38.530 --> 00:18:43.550
know, subjects or citizens, however
you want to call them, they agree to—

00:18:44.434 --> 00:18:48.414
let's say be taxed and be ruled by
political authorities because of what

00:18:48.454 --> 00:18:52.034
they get in return, and there's
this kind of understanding of a

00:18:52.154 --> 00:18:55.434
mutual set of responsibilities. And

00:18:55.774 --> 00:18:59.364
my concern, among other things,
is to try to explain how this

00:18:59.454 --> 00:19:06.294
society held together for so long. Pride,
yes, among some people, definitely. You

00:19:06.334 --> 00:19:09.824
find it in the sources. But
sources are, texts are written by

00:19:09.894 --> 00:19:13.884
literate, you know, usually
elites. So this is a small part

00:19:13.914 --> 00:19:18.754
of the population. We can't automatically
extend their attitudes to everybody else.

00:19:18.854 --> 00:19:22.794
So in dealing with everyone else, we have to work
with different kinds of materials, different kinds of

00:19:22.834 --> 00:19:26.274
assumptions. We can't just posit that
they're just proud of being Roman.

00:19:26.724 --> 00:19:30.504
They could have been. We don't know that,
though. We can see other sorts of things

00:19:30.574 --> 00:19:34.404
about them. Like, for example, did they
pay their taxes? Did they try to rebel and

00:19:34.514 --> 00:19:37.554
leave the empire? So those are the
kinds of things that I look for.

00:19:37.954 --> 00:19:42.703
- Pride is one component, but there could
be other explanations and factors

00:19:43.934 --> 00:19:48.933
that explain what motivates a soldier
to defend the capital, for example.

00:19:49.534 --> 00:19:53.114
Like, what motivates a

00:19:53.134 --> 00:19:57.034
particular person to pay the taxes.
And then this is something that we'll

00:19:57.054 --> 00:20:00.394
definitely talk about. But just
to linger at the big picture,

00:20:01.574 --> 00:20:04.634
if the Romans from the
different periods met,

00:20:06.174 --> 00:20:10.154
how different would they be
from each other? Like, if I

00:20:10.254 --> 00:20:12.024
brought to you... This is one of
those, you know, there's like-

00:20:12.074 --> 00:20:12.284
- Yes, yes,

00:20:12.284 --> 00:20:14.374
- ... blind taste tests
you can do with food.

00:20:14.674 --> 00:20:16.514
- Yes. Pepsi and Coke.

00:20:16.614 --> 00:20:17.274
- Pepsi and Coke.

00:20:17.454 --> 00:20:17.574
- Yes.

00:20:17.874 --> 00:20:21.754
- If I brought you a Roman
from the kingdom period,

00:20:22.114 --> 00:20:26.754
the republic period, the
early imperial period-

00:20:27.254 --> 00:20:31.214
- I mean, I get asked this in a much more radical
form, which is like if you take someone

00:20:31.234 --> 00:20:35.214
from, like, around 1453 who's a
Roman and a subject of this Roman,

00:20:35.314 --> 00:20:39.254
and compare, and, and, you know,
compare him or have him meet, you know,

00:20:39.294 --> 00:20:42.404
in your imagination with someone from
the ancient republic. Like, how-

00:20:42.474 --> 00:20:42.544
- Yeah,

00:20:42.554 --> 00:20:46.514
- ... could they find any kind of
agreement on what it means to

00:20:46.534 --> 00:20:50.454
be Roman and recognize each other as
belonging to that polity? This, this

00:20:50.494 --> 00:20:54.394
is a very difficult thing to...
Like, now, I can point to a

00:20:54.434 --> 00:20:58.354
number of things that they would
find eventually. And, you know,

00:20:58.394 --> 00:21:02.364
if you told them, "Yo, you're both Romans,
you're both from this long history, now you have

00:21:02.374 --> 00:21:06.144
to find, you know, what you have in common,"
I think they could find things. But

00:21:06.194 --> 00:21:08.674
before we talk about those,
if you wanna get into it,

00:21:09.634 --> 00:21:13.354
let's just say that the
question can even be posed

00:21:13.394 --> 00:21:17.314
about Romans who live at the
same time. I mean, if you take a

00:21:17.574 --> 00:21:21.214
senator from the age of
Cicero and someone from the

00:21:21.654 --> 00:21:25.514
slums of Rome, who's
maybe the son of a slave

00:21:25.554 --> 00:21:29.474
who was brought from the East by
some general a generation ago,

00:21:30.254 --> 00:21:34.194
and put them in a room and
say, "Now, you discuss. You're

00:21:34.234 --> 00:21:37.914
both Romans. What do you have in common?" They
might have trouble in coming up with something.

00:21:38.334 --> 00:21:41.734
Right? So let's not minimize the sheer

00:21:41.814 --> 00:21:45.534
diversity of experiences and
sort of life experiences

00:21:45.714 --> 00:21:48.134
of Romans who are living at the same time.

00:21:49.654 --> 00:21:52.914
The important thing is that a
change is always happening, and

00:21:53.734 --> 00:21:57.274
from my standpoint this change is sort of

00:21:57.354 --> 00:22:00.754
cumulative, so it results
in Greek-speaking Orthodox

00:22:00.834 --> 00:22:04.814
Christian Romans in
Constantinople who at first

00:22:04.854 --> 00:22:08.814
sight might have little to
do with Latin-speaking, you

00:22:08.854 --> 00:22:12.354
know, non-Christians or worshiping
the ancient gods, Romans from a

00:22:12.434 --> 00:22:16.234
republic in Rome. And those are very,
very different situations, and no

00:22:16.254 --> 00:22:20.154
doubt they would look and seem
foreign to each other, right? The

00:22:20.194 --> 00:22:25.354
question is, why do we assume that someone
like Hadrian, right, an emperor from the

00:22:25.374 --> 00:22:29.154
second century sort of a
very cosmopolitan figure

00:22:29.234 --> 00:22:32.654
who travels around the empire
with his Greek lover and,

00:22:33.394 --> 00:22:39.534
you know, writes poems and has a Greek beard
and, you know, loves Greek culture and

00:22:40.834 --> 00:22:44.354
has much to do with someone from
the Middle Republic who's, you

00:22:44.394 --> 00:22:48.354
know some warrior who's chasing
down cattle from the Samnites. I

00:22:48.414 --> 00:22:53.934
mean, and yet the way we understand history
is that, oh no, those belong together.

00:22:53.994 --> 00:22:57.174
Hadrian and this ancient Roman
from the fourth century BC.

00:22:58.254 --> 00:23:02.114
But not Hadrian and someone,
you know, an emperor a few

00:23:02.193 --> 00:23:06.414
centuries later who's just like him,
bilingual in Greek and Latin, who's

00:23:06.424 --> 00:23:09.794
... kinda cosmopolitan, who,
you know, reads the same stuff,

00:23:10.774 --> 00:23:14.574
because we posit this rupture
between Roman and Byzantine.

00:23:15.034 --> 00:23:18.864
- One of the ways we can try to analyze
this is, for example, looking at

00:23:18.974 --> 00:23:25.384
a very specific role in society across
time. So we can look at soldiers,

00:23:26.574 --> 00:23:29.794
how they solve violence, for
example. That's one way.

00:23:29.854 --> 00:23:33.694
So you're making me realize
that we can just take 1,000

00:23:33.734 --> 00:23:36.554
different professions and
positions in society and really

00:23:36.634 --> 00:23:41.654
specifically look at what the
experience of the world was like.

00:23:41.684 --> 00:23:46.524
And so one of them is
the view on violence,

00:23:47.614 --> 00:23:53.254
Across time. And, and then the other
is the view on the role of the,

00:23:54.154 --> 00:23:57.274
the government- ... across time.

00:23:57.694 --> 00:24:01.724
- That's an excellent way of putting it. So take
soldiers, for example. They swear an oath.

00:24:01.994 --> 00:24:05.114
Right? Now, we don't have the
oath for every given period.

00:24:05.994 --> 00:24:09.814
We have some approximations of it, some hints
of what it contained, but we know that Roman

00:24:09.854 --> 00:24:13.574
soldiers swore an oath like,
throughout all of the centuries of the

00:24:13.674 --> 00:24:17.554
empire. Sometimes they might
add, like, a Christian formula

00:24:17.614 --> 00:24:25.114
to it. Sometime before that, not. But
they swore basically to protect the

00:24:25.154 --> 00:24:28.874
republic or depending on
what term they used or the

00:24:28.884 --> 00:24:32.544
empire or the emperor. And this
is something that they would have

00:24:32.574 --> 00:24:36.374
recognized very quickly. Like,
if, if they met each other over

00:24:36.434 --> 00:24:40.294
time and said, "Hey, what was your oath like?" And
they recited it this would have made much sense

00:24:40.374 --> 00:24:41.484
to them, right?

00:24:41.514 --> 00:24:47.164
Or take, for example, a woman who runs a
business, right? From any century of the

00:24:47.234 --> 00:24:52.338
empire. It, it would have been, especially
the later you go, the, the more so,

00:24:53.118 --> 00:24:56.798
that this woman is enabled
to do this by virtue

00:24:56.858 --> 00:25:00.468
of Roman law. Of certain,
you know, Roman law of

00:25:00.478 --> 00:25:03.538
property and inheritance
and, and marriage, but

00:25:03.638 --> 00:25:07.428
also regulations regarding
who can do what and what

00:25:07.478 --> 00:25:11.098
kinds of properties women can handle
and under what circumstances.

00:25:11.678 --> 00:25:16.458
This is something that Roman women had in
common that many other cultures did not.

00:25:16.698 --> 00:25:20.678
So I'll give you an example.
So for example, in the 10th,

00:25:20.738 --> 00:25:26.138
11th century, there are Jewish women
who live in the Eastern Roman Empire-

00:25:26.148 --> 00:25:31.798
... who realize that they have more
rights in Roman courts than in

00:25:31.838 --> 00:25:36.178
rabbinical ones, and they take
their disputes to the Roman courts.

00:25:37.138 --> 00:25:40.618
Now, the thing is that for the
Romans, these are property matters-

00:25:40.738 --> 00:25:44.478
... not religious matters. But for the
rabbis, these are religious matters. But the

00:25:44.518 --> 00:25:46.938
Roman courts trump the Jewish courts-

00:25:47.038 --> 00:25:50.698
... in the empire, right? And so you end up
with a situation where Jewish women have more

00:25:50.718 --> 00:25:51.678
rights-

00:25:52.198 --> 00:25:56.038
... than Jewish women do elsewhere,
because where Roman law is not operative.

00:25:56.858 --> 00:26:00.818
And there you go. Right? Like, these
things matter, right? And that's a

00:26:00.878 --> 00:26:02.078
function of imperial law.

00:26:02.538 --> 00:26:06.498
- And this, this would be an interesting
actually interplay between the law

00:26:07.198 --> 00:26:12.578
and religious institutions- ... Throughout
the East- ... uh, Roman Empire.

00:26:13.458 --> 00:26:17.168
So you argue that even though the
personality of the various emperors varied,

00:26:17.438 --> 00:26:20.938
as we'll talk about, and as
they're often venerated,

00:26:21.018 --> 00:26:22.878
celebrated, criticized, talked about,

00:26:24.118 --> 00:26:27.718
the late Roman Empire was
projecting a persona to its

00:26:27.778 --> 00:26:30.738
citizens that was consistent
throughout its history.

00:26:31.618 --> 00:26:35.318
Can you describe what you mean by this
and describe the different detailed

00:26:35.358 --> 00:26:36.958
characteristics of this persona?

00:26:36.998 --> 00:26:44.508
- Yes. So this persona, it's what the
governments or the emperor, the court, and the

00:26:44.618 --> 00:26:48.168
spokesman, the bureaucracy
want their subjects to think,

00:26:49.238 --> 00:26:55.228
This whole thing is about. Like, how is
power being used, why, and for whom, right?

00:26:56.218 --> 00:27:00.078
And they do so in laws that

00:27:00.138 --> 00:27:04.038
they promulgate throughout the empire.
Sometimes they have these laws read in

00:27:04.118 --> 00:27:07.958
church, for example, or posted
publicly. They're definitely eager to

00:27:07.998 --> 00:27:10.398
have them communicated to
as many people as possible.

00:27:11.298 --> 00:27:15.178
But they're also a function of
imperial rhetoric so the way

00:27:15.218 --> 00:27:18.907
you praise an emperor, the way you
talk about an emperor. You find this

00:27:18.938 --> 00:27:22.558
language in petitions, so
this is a hugely important

00:27:22.618 --> 00:27:26.378
glue for this society,
is that anyone could

00:27:26.418 --> 00:27:30.008
basically petition the authorities for
let's just say just about anything.

00:27:30.078 --> 00:27:33.548
That's not technically true, but
there's a lot of petitioning going

00:27:33.598 --> 00:27:37.498
on. So, you know, if you think
something's wrong or you've been

00:27:37.538 --> 00:27:41.378
treated unjustly, you can
petition local officials, even

00:27:41.398 --> 00:27:45.198
imperial officials. You can petition
the emperor, you can... Right? And the

00:27:45.238 --> 00:27:49.148
expectation is that that petition will be
read, addressed, and answered. It might not

00:27:49.158 --> 00:27:52.288
be answered in the way that you
want, but it will be answered.

00:27:52.978 --> 00:27:56.948
And those responses contain this
language also, right? So these are

00:27:56.978 --> 00:28:00.728
the different media through which
the emperors are broadcasting this

00:28:00.738 --> 00:28:04.118
persona, and that persona is
what? Basically, that the

00:28:04.138 --> 00:28:07.958
authorities are responsive to
the needs of their subjects,

00:28:08.798 --> 00:28:12.738
that they are often accountable.
In other words, they understand

00:28:12.778 --> 00:28:15.128
that they are exercising public power,

00:28:16.018 --> 00:28:19.858
and that their mandate is to
exercise it solely for the

00:28:19.878 --> 00:28:23.278
benefit of their subjects.
They keep saying this. Um,

00:28:23.318 --> 00:28:26.608
so renouncing any kind of
private interest. In other

00:28:26.658 --> 00:28:30.398
words, "We're not doing this
for our benefit," say the

00:28:30.438 --> 00:28:32.628
authorities. "We're doing
this for your benefit."

00:28:33.118 --> 00:28:36.528
Also that they're proactive.
So the emperors are constantly

00:28:36.558 --> 00:28:39.668
saying that, "We're planning ahead.

00:28:40.518 --> 00:28:44.378
We're trying to foresee what problems
you might have, and we are solving

00:28:44.418 --> 00:28:46.568
them at, before you experience them."

00:28:46.998 --> 00:28:50.898
And that they are also working very
hard. So hardworking. In fact,

00:28:51.018 --> 00:28:54.838
the one of the cliches that they keep
using is sleepless. The emperors

00:28:54.938 --> 00:28:58.828
keep saying that, "I'm losing sleep over
this. I'm not sleeping at night because

00:28:58.898 --> 00:29:02.818
I'm just worrying so much about your
problems and how to solve them." Justinian,

00:29:02.838 --> 00:29:06.828
for example, was publicly known
as the sleepless emperor, and not

00:29:06.858 --> 00:29:10.178
because he was a demon whose head
floated around in the palace on its own,

00:29:10.958 --> 00:29:11.518
which some people

00:29:12.238 --> 00:29:12.758
- That's the thing?

00:29:12.898 --> 00:29:13.838
- It was a thing, yes.

00:29:14.018 --> 00:29:14.298
- Okay.

00:29:14.558 --> 00:29:15.178
- That's a whole thing.

00:29:15.258 --> 00:29:16.988
- But sleepless in terms of worked so hard-

00:29:17.018 --> 00:29:17.158
- Yes.

00:29:17.168 --> 00:29:19.298
- ... there's no time to sleep.

00:29:19.418 --> 00:29:23.938
- He was a workaholic. That is
conceded by even his enemies.

00:29:24.018 --> 00:29:27.938
All night he was up just hauling
officials in at any old hour to

00:29:27.978 --> 00:29:31.918
talk about whatever, you know, wars
and architecture and laws and the

00:29:31.978 --> 00:29:35.878
religion and theology and whatever. So the
emperors are projecting this image, right?

00:29:36.118 --> 00:29:37.998
So that's what I call the persona.

00:29:38.318 --> 00:29:44.178
Tireless effort to work on behalf
of subjects, to do so responsibly,

00:29:45.098 --> 00:29:48.718
to be responsive and
accountable. In other words,

00:29:49.318 --> 00:29:53.058
if some of my officials
breaks the law or oppresses

00:29:53.218 --> 00:29:56.738
you, I'm giving you
instruments, like legal

00:29:56.798 --> 00:29:59.228
instruments, by which to
hold them to account.

00:29:59.798 --> 00:30:02.518
So that's the persona.
It's very consistent,

00:30:03.378 --> 00:30:07.298
And I think it's part of the
mechanism of tying the society

00:30:07.358 --> 00:30:11.058
together. In other words, if subjects
think that their emperors are like this,

00:30:11.778 --> 00:30:17.008
right, they're more likely to agree to the
consensus of essentially paying taxes.

00:30:17.578 --> 00:30:20.548
- And you draw this distinction
between rhetoric and action,

00:30:21.438 --> 00:30:25.018
what the authorities say and what
they actually do. So when you say

00:30:25.038 --> 00:30:30.598
persona in the modern times, some of
that could be reframed as propaganda-

00:30:30.778 --> 00:30:30.808
- Yeah.

00:30:30.808 --> 00:30:36.178
- ... for example. And propaganda
implies that the rhetoric,

00:30:36.278 --> 00:30:39.898
that there's a big gap
between the rhetoric and the

00:30:40.018 --> 00:30:43.808
action. And one of the things you said you
took away from reading Machiavelli is that

00:30:43.898 --> 00:30:47.738
we should judge people not by what
they say, but by what they do.

00:30:48.458 --> 00:30:52.338
So how much of the Roman Empire's
government of what they espoused

00:30:52.378 --> 00:30:56.358
was merely rhetoric, and how
much was true in how they acted?

00:30:56.558 --> 00:31:00.378
- Yes. This is a key lesson I took
from reading Machiavelli, and

00:31:00.798 --> 00:31:04.478
I found this a very insightful way
of thinking about politics, and

00:31:05.038 --> 00:31:08.910
I would recommend that anybody kind of
practice this way of looking at the world,

00:31:09.110 --> 00:31:12.930
right? People and states and, you
know, powerful people can say

00:31:12.990 --> 00:31:17.310
anything they want to. At the end of the
day, what matters is what they actually do.

00:31:18.250 --> 00:31:21.330
And this doesn't mean
that what they say is

00:31:21.390 --> 00:31:26.990
irrelevant, even if it's discordant
with what they do. But nevertheless,

00:31:27.810 --> 00:31:31.700
In the case of the East Roman state,

00:31:31.730 --> 00:31:35.440
so my research suggests that the
emperors and the authorities

00:31:35.470 --> 00:31:39.109
were generally sincere in what
they said. In other words,

00:31:39.710 --> 00:31:45.390
I have found that they generally did what
they said they were going to do overall.

00:31:46.210 --> 00:31:50.170
Not perfectly, obviously. And of course,
these are human beings we're talking

00:31:50.230 --> 00:31:54.150
about. The, right, the human societies,
there was a lot of, you know,

00:31:54.190 --> 00:31:56.340
corruption, and you name it. Abuse-

00:31:56.340 --> 00:32:00.100
... of course. Of course there is.
But overall, I think that there was

00:32:00.770 --> 00:32:04.750
a sufficient level of
understanding that the emperors

00:32:04.830 --> 00:32:08.750
are in fact doing this, and they were
actually incentivized to do this. We can talk

00:32:08.830 --> 00:32:14.030
about how. Because they were also in a
pretty vulnerable situation too, so they

00:32:14.130 --> 00:32:18.390
needed their subjects to be
relatively content on this front.

00:32:18.930 --> 00:32:22.550
- Isn't this surprising to
you? So, you know, from the

00:32:22.770 --> 00:32:27.870
outsider point of view, Roman emperors,
even in the East Roman Empire,

00:32:29.190 --> 00:32:32.950
technically have a lot of power.

00:32:33.010 --> 00:32:36.800
You can even say in some
cases absolute power, and yet

00:32:37.610 --> 00:32:44.040
they seem to be awfully worried ... to
make everybody in the empire happy.

00:32:44.650 --> 00:32:48.390
What explains that? Like
what, what explains the small

00:32:48.400 --> 00:32:51.820
gap between rhetoric and action
in the East Roman Empire?

00:32:52.180 --> 00:32:56.950
- A number of things, but ultimately it is
that there is no right to the throne.

00:32:57.950 --> 00:33:02.630
And this is a function of the Roman
matrix of politics here. In other words,

00:33:03.850 --> 00:33:05.990
So here's a bit of a paradox.

00:33:06.990 --> 00:33:10.730
What we call the Roman Republic
was the most imperialistic

00:33:10.790 --> 00:33:14.410
phase of Roman history. Like this is when
the Romans did most of their conquering.

00:33:15.130 --> 00:33:18.950
What we call the empire is much
less imperialistic in this way.

00:33:19.010 --> 00:33:22.770
That's much more defensive in
its approach, right? And yet our

00:33:22.810 --> 00:33:30.330
terms are a little mismatched in that way.
The empire is more a function of the,

00:33:30.630 --> 00:33:36.270
That it has an emperor rather than
it is engaged in imperialism.

00:33:36.310 --> 00:33:40.190
And that emperor emerged
out of the republic.

00:33:40.230 --> 00:33:43.460
But emerged out of the republic in
a very strange way. In other words,

00:33:44.210 --> 00:33:47.930
not as a dynasty that created the

00:33:48.050 --> 00:33:51.650
state. So for example, if you think of
the Ottoman Empire, many other empires,

00:33:52.670 --> 00:33:57.740
they... The whole thing existed because
this dynasty engaged in conquest and-

00:33:57.740 --> 00:34:01.630
... was successful in creating the state, and
so the dynasty was like at the heart of the

00:34:01.650 --> 00:34:05.450
state. But that's not at
all the case in the Roman

00:34:05.510 --> 00:34:09.210
Empire. The emperor is a
figure who emerged within a

00:34:09.250 --> 00:34:12.990
republic, and in order to
create peace after the

00:34:13.010 --> 00:34:16.950
civil wars, those emperors had
to, for a long time, kind of

00:34:16.990 --> 00:34:23.350
pretend that they were not what they
really were. Um, basically, you know,

00:34:23.430 --> 00:34:27.270
continuing to flatter the idea of a
republic that is, you know, that has a

00:34:27.310 --> 00:34:31.130
first citizen maybe. "Oh, no,
no, I'm not a king. I'm just, I

00:34:31.190 --> 00:34:33.340
have this office and that
office and that office."

00:34:33.340 --> 00:34:37.290
"Whatever the Senate has given me." Now,
we understand that's a facade, but the

00:34:37.330 --> 00:34:40.130
fact that they had to create this
facade at all is very important.

00:34:40.290 --> 00:34:41.730
- Can we actually just linger on that?

00:34:41.770 --> 00:34:45.170
I mean, how much of this... 'Cause you
said they had to create this facade.

00:34:45.270 --> 00:34:45.810
- Yeah.

00:34:46.890 --> 00:34:52.250
- Did Augustus, who started the whole
thing, the first emperor of Rome,

00:34:53.070 --> 00:34:58.970
did he have to act that way? 'Cause he
kept acting like he's not an absolute-

00:34:59.330 --> 00:34:59.450
- Yes

00:34:59.490 --> 00:35:07.250
- ... monarch, and he could have gone
hardcore, destroy the Senate, just full

00:35:07.990 --> 00:35:09.730
hardcore rule, dictatorship.

00:35:09.740 --> 00:35:10.660
- Well, then how does he govern then?

00:35:11.210 --> 00:35:13.510
- Uh, so he wants to be
an effective governor.

00:35:13.530 --> 00:35:13.620
- Oh, yeah.

00:35:13.650 --> 00:35:16.050
- And he also wants to not be overthrown.

00:35:16.090 --> 00:35:20.050
- Exactly. Because, you know, just
because you ended one civil war

00:35:20.070 --> 00:35:22.070
doesn't mean that there's
not going to be another.

00:35:22.130 --> 00:35:25.810
You have to create a consensus such that
people don't want to have another civil war.

00:35:26.230 --> 00:35:30.110
If he did what you said, which
he in theory could have done,

00:35:30.470 --> 00:35:34.130
but that would've just led
to more wars, right? So the

00:35:34.190 --> 00:35:37.650
problem is that the emperors, even those
who come to power through violence, they

00:35:37.710 --> 00:35:41.590
can't prevent other people from trying
to come to power through violence

00:35:41.670 --> 00:35:45.150
because like I said, no one
has a right to the throne.

00:35:45.170 --> 00:35:47.670
- We should also say one more thing where,

00:35:49.450 --> 00:35:55.870
dare I carefully say this, but it
seems like riots and civil wars

00:35:56.790 --> 00:35:58.890
is a feature, not a bug of the system.

00:35:59.070 --> 00:35:59.650
- Yes.

00:35:59.710 --> 00:36:02.560
- This is a different thing that
we have to the modern day,

00:36:03.650 --> 00:36:07.390
is because the threat of a civil
war, a violent civil war where you

00:36:07.470 --> 00:36:11.550
overthrow the government
and there's just a lot of-

00:36:11.560 --> 00:36:15.310
... death and struggle for
power is always a threat.

00:36:15.410 --> 00:36:19.350
That's another incentive that, I
guess the stick, not the carrot, but

00:36:19.390 --> 00:36:21.910
the stick for the emperor to behave.

00:36:22.150 --> 00:36:26.020
- Yes. It's the main one. In
other words, just take the,

00:36:26.050 --> 00:36:31.390
the thousand years that I study.
There's something like 120 civil wars.

00:36:31.670 --> 00:36:34.850
Now, these are usually very
swift. They're over quickly,

00:36:35.610 --> 00:36:40.270
and they're never about ideology. So
they're not like modern civil wars.

00:36:40.430 --> 00:36:44.350
Right? It's about slavery or the rights
of kings or whatever. No, no, no. They're

00:36:44.610 --> 00:36:47.250
solely about who has the power.

00:36:47.330 --> 00:36:50.850
All sides have the same ideology.
They talk about, you know, the

00:36:50.870 --> 00:36:54.670
responsibility of government in the same
way, right? They're just competing over

00:36:54.730 --> 00:36:56.710
who's the best man to do the job.

00:36:57.050 --> 00:37:00.940
Right? And so once you have that
situation... And it might not be a

00:37:00.950 --> 00:37:04.470
civil war, it could be a palace
coup, it could be a kind

00:37:04.490 --> 00:37:06.620
of fighting in the capital-

00:37:06.620 --> 00:37:10.195
... something like that. Once everyone's
taken their side and you have a winner,

00:37:10.946 --> 00:37:16.246
that's the emperor, And you often overthrow
the previous regime. I'll give you some

00:37:16.306 --> 00:37:20.266
statistics. Something like
46% of the emperors of

00:37:20.306 --> 00:37:25.625
Constantinople are overthrown through
violence. 46%. And that's almost half.

00:37:25.866 --> 00:37:29.806
Right? So that's a huge, that's a huge
number, which means that every emperor

00:37:29.846 --> 00:37:31.696
is vulnerable and insecure,
and they know it,

00:37:32.506 --> 00:37:35.616
right? So what they have to do is make
sure that that doesn't happen to them,

00:37:36.626 --> 00:37:40.586
and the way to do that is not by arresting

00:37:40.606 --> 00:37:44.546
and executing everybody you think might
be a threat or just generally behaving

00:37:44.646 --> 00:37:48.506
like a, you know, a Caligula or a
Nero. That will just get you killed.

00:37:48.546 --> 00:37:52.306
Like, they know this. So
the best way to avoid that

00:37:52.386 --> 00:37:56.166
fate is to actually do
the things that will make

00:37:56.186 --> 00:38:00.066
people happy so that they don't
support a rebel if a rebel

00:38:00.086 --> 00:38:02.366
decides to appear. And
sometimes rebels would appear.

00:38:03.166 --> 00:38:06.966
There's a kind of convention in
Constantinople, like if you... Sometimes you

00:38:07.186 --> 00:38:11.146
you think, "Hmm, that emperor's pretty unpopular
and I think I can overthrow him." What you would

00:38:11.206 --> 00:38:15.286
do is you would march down
the center boulevard-

00:38:15.866 --> 00:38:19.766
... And, you know, you'd have
your people just call the

00:38:19.806 --> 00:38:23.666
populace of Constantinople out to
rally, to you know, maybe go to

00:38:23.706 --> 00:38:27.436
Hagia Sophia, the, the church, and just
create a big crowd and call for the

00:38:27.526 --> 00:38:31.246
deposition of the emperor and, you know,
maybe that would hap- And sometimes it did,

00:38:31.746 --> 00:38:35.686
and sometimes it didn't, and the
rebel or wannabe rebel would sort of

00:38:35.726 --> 00:38:39.266
proceed down the Mese, the
boulevard, and people would just

00:38:39.286 --> 00:38:42.966
gradually just disappear,
and then he'd be left alone-

00:38:43.066 --> 00:38:49.226
... and go up to Hagia Sophia as
seeking asylum. Right? So that's a bid.

00:38:49.296 --> 00:38:53.146
That's someone making a bid for the
throne, and it just goes disastrously bad.

00:38:53.226 --> 00:38:57.066
Other times, the people come out 'cause they hate the emperor,
and they drag the emperor out and cut his nose off or

00:38:57.396 --> 00:39:01.166
whatever. So emperors are

00:39:01.246 --> 00:39:05.006
constantly trying to prevent that from
happening, and the best way to do

00:39:05.086 --> 00:39:06.506
that is through goodwill.

00:39:07.416 --> 00:39:11.406
- I'm trying to load in that kind
of world 'cause it's a different

00:39:11.446 --> 00:39:13.666
world than we live in today.

00:39:13.706 --> 00:39:14.086
- Yes.

00:39:14.126 --> 00:39:20.606
- There's a constant inner workings of
policy development inside government.

00:39:20.846 --> 00:39:21.046
- Yes.

00:39:21.746 --> 00:39:26.526
- But the check on power is, like,
literal, like, we will murder you.

00:39:27.306 --> 00:39:30.926
- Yes, it depends on the period. Sometimes
murder you, sometimes blind you,

00:39:31.006 --> 00:39:32.926
sometimes cut your nose off,
but there were periods-

00:39:33.946 --> 00:39:35.206
- Thank you for the nuance

00:39:35.226 --> 00:39:38.786
- ... No, there were periods that were more civilized.
We'll just basically, you'll get retired to a

00:39:38.826 --> 00:39:39.366
monastery.

00:39:39.766 --> 00:39:40.066
- Right.

00:39:40.146 --> 00:39:43.686
- Okay. You're right. So
here's what elections do.

00:39:43.786 --> 00:39:47.766
Elections give a government a mandate
for, I don't know, four or five years,

00:39:48.606 --> 00:39:52.406
and during that period, you may be
unpopular, but you're legitimate,

00:39:53.046 --> 00:39:54.966
right, because of the institutions.

00:39:55.946 --> 00:39:59.626
Whereas in Constantinople, we don't
have those kinds of institutions.

00:40:00.586 --> 00:40:04.246
We have instead an ongoing referendum.

00:40:04.826 --> 00:40:06.915
We just call it a perpetual
referendum, right?

00:40:07.426 --> 00:40:11.146
And in fact, the emperors are, they're
conducting opinion polls in a sense

00:40:11.186 --> 00:40:14.975
because they appear in public. When
they appear in public, everyone is

00:40:15.006 --> 00:40:19.006
expected to cheer and chant
acclamations, right, like,

00:40:19.866 --> 00:40:23.726
Slogans. Right? So you have
100,000 people in the Hippodrome

00:40:23.806 --> 00:40:27.656
all chanting, you know, "Worthy" or "Many
years for you, Augustus" or something

00:40:27.666 --> 00:40:31.646
like this. And if that happens, it's great. But
if you appear in the Hippodrome and people are,

00:40:31.746 --> 00:40:36.566
like, sullen or if the chanting is
a bit tepid or if they're booing,

00:40:37.406 --> 00:40:39.056
then you know something's wrong, right?

00:40:39.056 --> 00:40:42.666
So you gotta find out what's wrong.
It could be something like the grain

00:40:42.746 --> 00:40:45.975
supply is, you know, not working or

00:40:46.266 --> 00:40:49.276
whatever. And so emperors are
desperate to fix those problems.

00:40:49.986 --> 00:40:53.306
- And the Hippodrome is this
big gathering place in

00:40:53.346 --> 00:40:57.016
Constantinople, which I guess
a lot of people gathered

00:40:57.086 --> 00:41:01.626
at and did this kind of cheering or
not cheering based on policy and-

00:41:01.646 --> 00:41:06.216
... and whether the emperor is
popular or not. This was democracy.

00:41:07.106 --> 00:41:09.236
Uh, I apologize to use that term, but-

00:41:09.306 --> 00:41:13.126
... in our conception of what that
means, because what do we mean by

00:41:13.146 --> 00:41:16.616
democracy in the modern day is
that the people somehow have a

00:41:16.646 --> 00:41:20.266
connection to who leads and how they lead,

00:41:20.826 --> 00:41:26.606
and this is, the Hippodrome was that
connection between the people and the leaders.

00:41:26.866 --> 00:41:30.786
- Yes. Now, we can talk about modern democracy
if you, if you want. That's a, that's a,

00:41:30.946 --> 00:41:32.676
I have, I have my own views about-

00:41:32.676 --> 00:41:36.636
... modern democracy, and, and,
you know, how it works and how

00:41:36.686 --> 00:41:40.646
it doesn't and, anyway, whether it is democracy,
in fact, 'cause there are other models of

00:41:40.666 --> 00:41:41.436
democracy, like-

00:41:41.436 --> 00:41:45.366
... ancient Athenian democracy, which is
a whole other thing. But you're right.

00:41:45.386 --> 00:41:49.146
So it's not just in the Hippodrome.
It's wherever people assemble in large

00:41:49.226 --> 00:41:52.816
numbers. So this could be
military mustering grounds,

00:41:53.466 --> 00:41:57.316
right? So the army. The army is also
the Roman people in a way, and the-

00:41:57.566 --> 00:42:01.226
in some cases, the most decisive
part of it, right? So if an

00:42:01.306 --> 00:42:04.666
army gathers together and they decide
they want a different emperor,

00:42:04.886 --> 00:42:08.746
that's serious, and that can happen
out in the provinces too. That doesn't

00:42:08.786 --> 00:42:12.646
necessarily have to happen in
Constantinople. There's also Hagia

00:42:12.666 --> 00:42:16.446
Sophia, so the people gather in
the church, or they gather in

00:42:16.466 --> 00:42:18.806
public spaces like the
Forum of Constantine.

00:42:19.266 --> 00:42:23.446
So this can happen anywhere where a
large number of people can gather,

00:42:24.386 --> 00:42:28.146
and it's, I don't know if you
wanna call it a democracy as such

00:42:28.606 --> 00:42:32.086
but it is definitely a form
of popular, mm, let's say

00:42:32.186 --> 00:42:36.006
consultation and a testing of consensus.

00:42:36.606 --> 00:42:41.816
I'll give you another example. So in the
1190s, the emperor, and it's Alexius III,

00:42:42.886 --> 00:42:46.846
he's being threatened by the German emperor. German emperor's
basically, "You, you, you pay me a bunch of money or

00:42:46.886 --> 00:42:49.456
I'll invade." Just straight up extortion.

00:42:49.946 --> 00:42:50.146
- Yeah.

00:42:50.226 --> 00:42:54.076
- Um, and Alexius decides, "Okay, I'm
gonna gather this money. I'm gonna

00:42:54.106 --> 00:42:55.066
impose these taxes."

00:42:55.926 --> 00:42:59.726
And he gathers the people in the Hippodrome, and
he says, "You know, we're gonna have the German

00:42:59.766 --> 00:43:04.066
tax." He called it the German
tax. And there's such an uproar

00:43:04.986 --> 00:43:08.946
in the Hippodrome against this
that he was like, "Uh, that

00:43:08.986 --> 00:43:12.606
wasn't my idea. I don't know where that came from.
No, never mind. We're not gonna have the German

00:43:12.646 --> 00:43:16.446
tax." Fortunately, the German emperor
died and, and nothing ever happened,

00:43:17.046 --> 00:43:20.926
but it gives you a sense of how emperors, like,
literally can backtrack when they see that the

00:43:20.946 --> 00:43:23.946
people are against something in a matter
of policy, right- ... like tax policy.

00:43:24.970 --> 00:43:27.550
So yeah, there was this give and take.

00:43:28.270 --> 00:43:32.190
So institutionally, the emperor
might look absolute, as

00:43:32.270 --> 00:43:39.680
you called him earlier. In practice, no.
No. The ones that did that didn't end well.

00:43:40.540 --> 00:43:44.390
- And we should say, going to Perplexity
here, the Hippodrome of Constantinople

00:43:44.430 --> 00:43:48.610
was the main stadium and social
center of the Byzantine capital,

00:43:49.570 --> 00:43:53.470
used primarily for chariot
racing and imperial ceremony,

00:43:53.570 --> 00:43:57.210
and today survives in Istanbul's
Sultanahmet district.

00:43:57.510 --> 00:44:01.490
And the reason I looked this up, I
wanted to see how many people. Shaped as

00:44:01.550 --> 00:44:05.390
a long U-shaped race course
with a central barrier

00:44:05.910 --> 00:44:09.470
and tiered seating, it may
have held from roughly thirty

00:44:09.590 --> 00:44:13.080
thousand up to a hundred
thousand spectators,

00:44:13.450 --> 00:44:18.350
though exact capacity is debated because
archaeological remains are limited.

00:44:18.390 --> 00:44:19.170
That's a lot of people.

00:44:19.350 --> 00:44:22.710
- Thirty thousand is definitely
a pretty un- underestimate.

00:44:22.930 --> 00:44:25.830
The Hippodrome is still there. I mean, you
can see it from, it's like satellite photos.

00:44:26.070 --> 00:44:27.750
The shape of it is still there.

00:44:28.010 --> 00:44:31.990
And actually some parts of the built,
the, the Sphendone, the, the sling

00:44:32.090 --> 00:44:35.990
around the southern side is still there.
You can walk around it. And it's right

00:44:36.030 --> 00:44:40.450
next to the palace. In other words,
emperors didn't have to go far. Now,

00:44:41.250 --> 00:44:45.230
sometimes there are events for replacing
an emperor. So say the emperor dies in

00:44:45.250 --> 00:44:50.010
his sleep, and there's no heir.
This happens in 491, for example.

00:44:51.110 --> 00:44:54.640
And so the people gather in the
Hippodrome in order to have a

00:44:54.640 --> 00:44:58.620
discussion with the court about whom to
appoint. Now, in those kinds of contexts, it's

00:44:58.650 --> 00:45:02.530
entirely possible that there are
people also in the, the arena,

00:45:03.590 --> 00:45:07.530
like not just in the stands. I
think some military units might

00:45:07.570 --> 00:45:11.470
have just been arrayed there rather than
in the stands. So you can get more people

00:45:11.530 --> 00:45:15.510
than what we project might fit in the
stands, because they're not having the races

00:45:15.570 --> 00:45:16.090
on that day.

00:45:16.430 --> 00:45:20.210
- We should say, so like, I think the thing that
was emphasized in the first paragraph is the,

00:45:20.830 --> 00:45:24.610
the athletic events and the
entertainment events, right? Like the

00:45:24.830 --> 00:45:28.210
imperial ceremony. But there is
a sort of a political gathering

00:45:28.850 --> 00:45:32.790
was also popular. The Hippodrome
was not just for sport. It

00:45:32.830 --> 00:45:36.819
was where emperors appeared before
the people, where acclamations,

00:45:36.950 --> 00:45:40.590
public punishments, and political
demonstrations took place, and where the

00:45:40.610 --> 00:45:44.240
rival circus factions,
blues, greens, reds, whites,

00:45:44.390 --> 00:45:48.360
became powerful social and
sometimes paramilitary forces.

00:45:48.810 --> 00:45:51.379
And this goes on and on and
on. So this was a place-

00:45:51.970 --> 00:45:52.540
- Oh, it's a very important place. Yeah,

00:45:52.540 --> 00:45:55.110
- ... for people to speak to the leader.

00:45:55.410 --> 00:45:58.250
- Yeah. Vent sometimes. Even insult them.

00:45:58.870 --> 00:46:02.830
- Yeah. This is fascinating. I mean, it's
human civilization. It's converged

00:46:02.850 --> 00:46:06.730
towards a mechanism that
has clearly worked, because

00:46:06.810 --> 00:46:10.790
for the empire in the East, stood

00:46:10.830 --> 00:46:15.210
for a thousand years. So it's,
it's fascinating. We as humans,

00:46:16.130 --> 00:46:21.030
throughout our history, we try
to figure out, okay, how do we,

00:46:22.050 --> 00:46:24.930
figure out how to govern

00:46:25.850 --> 00:46:29.790
large collections of humans in a way
that they're represented, in the

00:46:29.830 --> 00:46:33.270
way that they don't
riot, they don't rebel.

00:46:33.430 --> 00:46:37.000
Um, in the way that we
flourish together as a

00:46:37.150 --> 00:46:39.250
people, all this, all this kind of stuff.

00:46:39.290 --> 00:46:42.659
So this is a real... The
East Roman Empire is a real

00:46:42.810 --> 00:46:46.550
study of something that seemed
to have worked. There are

00:46:46.610 --> 00:46:50.140
lessons there even for the modern
times, I think. And modern times,

00:46:50.170 --> 00:46:54.070
again, is very early human civilization.

00:46:54.770 --> 00:46:57.670
- From a certain standpoint,
yes, we are still early in-

00:46:57.950 --> 00:46:58.590
- Trying to figure it out

00:46:58.610 --> 00:46:59.620
- ... trying to figure it out.

00:46:59.670 --> 00:47:03.090
Yes. Now, mind you, I'm not
advocating for this type of social

00:47:03.140 --> 00:47:06.170
organization and government. What
I'm trying to do as a historian

00:47:07.070 --> 00:47:10.930
is understand how and why it survived

00:47:11.090 --> 00:47:14.830
and also to find the ways
that it worked, because it

00:47:15.010 --> 00:47:18.930
did work. We know that much. We have
to start from that. It survived. It

00:47:18.970 --> 00:47:20.870
was resilient. There was a lot of,

00:47:21.670 --> 00:47:25.450
you know, give and take in the exercise
of power, and I want to understand the

00:47:25.490 --> 00:47:26.450
mechanisms of that.

00:47:27.630 --> 00:47:31.540
- So if we can, before we go
to Emperor Constantine the

00:47:31.690 --> 00:47:35.630
First and the founding of
Constantinople, can we look at some

00:47:36.550 --> 00:47:40.290
maybe seminal events that
led up to some of the

00:47:40.350 --> 00:47:44.030
topics we'll be talking about? So
one of them maybe tell me if this is

00:47:44.050 --> 00:47:51.910
not as interesting as I think it is, but
the Edict of Caracalla, in 212 AD. So this

00:47:52.010 --> 00:47:53.490
is where,

00:47:54.470 --> 00:47:58.390
You described that starting with Augustus
in the early imperial period, government

00:47:58.470 --> 00:48:01.390
saw itself as a protector
of the Roman citizens,

00:48:02.470 --> 00:48:06.150
which is a minority of the people
living in the, in the Roman

00:48:06.210 --> 00:48:10.050
Empire. It doesn't consider
the, the provincials.

00:48:11.210 --> 00:48:14.530
And then you described that
the Edict of Caracalla, that

00:48:14.570 --> 00:48:19.450
extended full Roman
citizenships to basically all,

00:48:20.350 --> 00:48:23.870
free inhabitants of the Roman Empire. So

00:48:24.230 --> 00:48:27.390
what is it? Why was it
done? Why is it important?

00:48:28.330 --> 00:48:30.390
And how did it change the Roman Empire?

00:48:30.990 --> 00:48:34.890
- Right. I agree with you that this is,
in fact, a very important... It's

00:48:34.990 --> 00:48:38.890
a, it's a real turning point in a sense,
but it also is part of a process.

00:48:40.690 --> 00:48:48.970
So for various reasons, the Roman polity
tended to bestow its metropolitan

00:48:49.070 --> 00:48:54.060
citizenship, that is, Roman
citizenship, on its allies,

00:48:54.890 --> 00:48:58.320
and eventually in time, on many
people that it had conquered.

00:48:59.130 --> 00:49:02.830
And it had various mechanisms for doing
so. It could bestow block grants.

00:49:03.450 --> 00:49:07.200
Sometimes it allowed its generals
to bestow citizenship on people

00:49:07.250 --> 00:49:11.050
they thought would, you
know, would be necessary

00:49:11.090 --> 00:49:14.500
players for controlling local
societies. Sometimes they even

00:49:14.530 --> 00:49:18.210
allowed foreign cities to,
like non-Roman cities, to

00:49:18.230 --> 00:49:21.920
decide who would get Roman citizenship by

00:49:22.010 --> 00:49:25.710
basically electing them to certain kinds of
offices. Like they, they outsourced a lot of this.

00:49:26.838 --> 00:49:30.578
And so you have over time
the steady growth of a

00:49:30.618 --> 00:49:34.538
Roman community of citizens
who are not all in Rome, and

00:49:34.578 --> 00:49:38.368
who are not all of Roman origin, whatever that
means, but they, they were not descended from

00:49:38.378 --> 00:49:39.258
people who were from Rome.

00:49:40.198 --> 00:49:43.898
And this proceeds, you know, it
expands, it expands, it expands.

00:49:44.258 --> 00:49:47.398
By Caracalla's time, so
early third century AD,

00:49:48.298 --> 00:49:51.978
we can estimate that maybe at, at most, a

00:49:52.318 --> 00:49:56.018
third of the free citizens
of the empire are

00:49:56.058 --> 00:49:59.878
Roman citizens. Everyone else has
local citizenship, like you're

00:50:00.178 --> 00:50:05.098
Alexandrian or Athenian or, or whatever.
And with... You're subject to those laws.

00:50:05.898 --> 00:50:09.758
This emperor, Caracalla, now that's his
nickname. His reigning name is Marcus

00:50:09.778 --> 00:50:10.778
Aurelius Antoninus.

00:50:12.258 --> 00:50:15.558
So just like Marcus Aurelius, it's
sa- same name two generations later.

00:50:15.618 --> 00:50:19.518
- Some badass names for emperors, by the
way. I don't know if it's the chicken or

00:50:19.558 --> 00:50:22.337
the egg, but just... some epic names.

00:50:22.398 --> 00:50:25.328
- They've been remembered that way, and
so we read that back into the name—

00:50:25.638 --> 00:50:25.808
- Yes, that's true.

00:50:25.808 --> 00:50:26.918
- ... and absolutely, yes.

00:50:26.958 --> 00:50:28.238
- But anyway, Caracalla. Yeah.

00:50:28.268 --> 00:50:31.678
- Yeah, so he issues this
edict in 212 called the

00:50:31.718 --> 00:50:35.558
Constitutio Antoniniana, named
after him. Some people at the

00:50:35.638 --> 00:50:37.138
time called it the Divine Decree,

00:50:37.978 --> 00:50:41.778
which basically extended citizenship to
everybody. Now, we don't know exactly why

00:50:41.838 --> 00:50:43.678
he did so. We can guess

00:50:44.658 --> 00:50:48.528
the reasons that he said he did
so, and this was for religious

00:50:48.598 --> 00:50:54.758
reasons. In other words, he wanted
people to go to the temples and pray and

00:50:54.878 --> 00:51:01.378
give thanks to the gods for him,
for his survival out of a coup.

00:51:01.718 --> 00:51:05.388
Which is whatever. And it's

00:51:05.478 --> 00:51:09.358
possible that there was some kind of
religious motivation here, and he wanted

00:51:09.378 --> 00:51:13.298
everybody to do so as Roman citizens to
honor the Roman gods and something like

00:51:13.338 --> 00:51:17.078
that. Other historians at the time
said he did it for tax reasons.

00:51:17.818 --> 00:51:21.618
We don't know exactly.
There might even have been

00:51:21.698 --> 00:51:25.678
a kind of ideology of a
unified community across

00:51:25.718 --> 00:51:29.618
the empire playing in his, if
not in his mind, in that of

00:51:29.778 --> 00:51:34.938
the jurists, that is the legal advisors
that he had. So that's possible. But

00:51:35.818 --> 00:51:42.818
less interesting than his
motivations, more interesting are the

00:51:42.998 --> 00:51:46.438
consequences of this— ... and what it
tells us about the Roman community. So

00:51:47.338 --> 00:51:54.328
imagine a situation where, like, no modern
empire has ever done this really, right?

00:51:55.538 --> 00:51:58.938
When what's significant about the Roman
case is that not only did they extend

00:51:59.038 --> 00:52:02.878
citizenship to everybody, but they meant
it. This is something that had teeth. In

00:52:02.938 --> 00:52:06.738
other words, it meant that the rights
and opportunities that were available to

00:52:06.758 --> 00:52:10.478
Roman citizens, say, in
the Roman Senate at Rome—

00:52:10.598 --> 00:52:17.148
... are now available to everybody. And
within a generation, you have a situation

00:52:17.178 --> 00:52:20.358
where, like, all of the
emperors are provincials,

00:52:21.578 --> 00:52:24.898
right? All the most powerful people
in the empire are from the provinces.

00:52:25.138 --> 00:52:28.558
- This is, like, mind-breaking,
mind-blowing. This is incredible.

00:52:29.018 --> 00:52:33.318
The fact that the Roman Empire was
able to do this, and it stuck.

00:52:33.598 --> 00:52:34.678
- They did it, and they meant it.

00:52:34.798 --> 00:52:37.818
- And they meant it. They
implemented it. It was real.

00:52:37.828 --> 00:52:41.598
That's, that tells you, that's an
important thing that tells you a

00:52:41.718 --> 00:52:45.828
lot of information about the
populace of the Roman Empire.

00:52:45.898 --> 00:52:49.438
That the, the fact that it stuck,
that the government meant it,

00:52:49.818 --> 00:52:54.018
that the system encouraged,
incentivized the government to mean it.

00:52:54.038 --> 00:52:54.598
It's incredible.

00:52:54.918 --> 00:52:58.618
- Yeah, and there's a law of citizenship,
and it, basically it says something like,

00:52:58.778 --> 00:53:01.418
"Anyone born within the Roman
Empire is a Roman citizen."

00:53:01.998 --> 00:53:05.938
And the Roman jurists and
policymakers who were behind,

00:53:06.018 --> 00:53:09.638
This had some very interesting ideas
about, you know, creating this kind of

00:53:09.678 --> 00:53:13.518
community. Look, like, imagine
if, I mean, it's almost

00:53:13.658 --> 00:53:17.558
impossible to, to imagine,
but the, the British at the

00:53:17.618 --> 00:53:21.478
time of the peak of the empire
bestowed British citizenship on

00:53:21.558 --> 00:53:25.138
everyone, including in India, and, like,

00:53:25.178 --> 00:53:29.118
suddenly made positions of
power in London available to

00:53:29.138 --> 00:53:33.608
people from India, like, including the
throne. Like, it's just unthinkable.

00:53:34.138 --> 00:53:37.208
And that has to do, you know, with race and
colonialism and all kinds of things, right?

00:53:38.048 --> 00:53:41.988
But not in the Roman Empire.
So we have a situation where

00:53:42.018 --> 00:53:45.967
the emperors are all from the provinces.
The most powerful officials are

00:53:46.018 --> 00:53:49.838
all from the provinces.
And so a century later,

00:53:50.238 --> 00:53:53.868
when Constantinople is created,
this is, it's created,

00:53:54.258 --> 00:53:58.018
right, like, in, in the Bosporus,
so, like, where modern Istanbul is,

00:53:58.898 --> 00:54:02.758
in the Eastern Roman Empire. It's
created within the preexisting Roman

00:54:02.798 --> 00:54:06.878
context, right? It doesn't bring Romanness
to the East. It's already there.

00:54:07.738 --> 00:54:11.728
And so it's not such a leap to
create a center of Roman power

00:54:11.838 --> 00:54:13.498
in the East because of that.

00:54:13.858 --> 00:54:17.598
- And you've helped put together a book on the history
of intellectual thought in the East Roman Empire.

00:54:17.658 --> 00:54:21.338
But this is the interesting thing
here, and I can ask that many

00:54:21.398 --> 00:54:25.238
times, but let me ask it here
also, is the great man, the

00:54:25.318 --> 00:54:27.518
great woman view of history.

00:54:28.378 --> 00:54:33.638
Were there, like, Thomas Jefferson or
those types of characters in the meetings

00:54:34.658 --> 00:54:38.538
as they're executing on
the edict or developing

00:54:38.558 --> 00:54:42.358
the edict? Is that important, or is it
more about the system and the culture and

00:54:42.458 --> 00:54:43.938
just, uh—

00:54:44.158 --> 00:54:48.058
... is it, how important was it? 'Cause this
seems like a revolutionary idea, and when

00:54:48.138 --> 00:54:52.078
we think about the American Revolution
and the, the founding documents, it seems

00:54:52.098 --> 00:54:55.138
like a few individuals—

00:54:55.148 --> 00:54:59.138
... were really critical about the
wording of things, and then words matter

00:54:59.538 --> 00:55:03.038
because those words create the reality,
and then it propagates through time.

00:55:03.518 --> 00:55:07.358
- Yeah. For the edict, I suspect that yes,
there were a few people who were behind

00:55:07.398 --> 00:55:11.138
it, and quite possibly jurists,
that is Roman legal scholars.

00:55:11.198 --> 00:55:14.898
And, and 212 is in an
age of very important

00:55:15.598 --> 00:55:19.598
Roman legal scholars Ulpian,
for example, and others.

00:55:20.438 --> 00:55:24.438
But we just don't have those... We, we
have- ... minutes of the meetings for the-

00:55:24.448 --> 00:55:25.838
... American Revolution.

00:55:25.958 --> 00:55:29.698
Not only do we not know who was in the
room, we don't actually even have the whole

00:55:29.778 --> 00:55:33.838
edict. We have a papyrus fragment,
this is a piece of ancient paper—

00:55:33.878 --> 00:55:37.488
... that's mostly torn and mutilated,
and we have, like, a bit of a

00:55:37.518 --> 00:55:38.948
paragraph from it.

00:55:39.438 --> 00:55:43.298
Um, in Greek, not even the Latin
original. And it's kind of torn,

00:55:43.358 --> 00:55:47.220
but it actually preserves the
key clause. Right? And that's,

00:55:48.450 --> 00:55:52.340
that's all we have of the original.
We have contemporary sources that

00:55:52.370 --> 00:55:55.630
mention it, we have legal
documents, but nothing like a,

00:55:56.670 --> 00:56:00.650
Like we can talk about the
people involved in it. Or even

00:56:00.750 --> 00:56:04.620
how it was immediately implemented.
Like, suddenly we know everyone in the

00:56:04.690 --> 00:56:08.250
provinces, like, there's this explosion
in the number of people called

00:56:08.310 --> 00:56:12.390
Aurelius, because that was
his Roman family name.

00:56:13.030 --> 00:56:18.170
Um, and so when you acquired citizenship
from that edict, you became an Aurelius.

00:56:18.350 --> 00:56:21.790
Right? And there are lots of Aurelii suddenly
all over the place. Like, we can see it

00:56:21.850 --> 00:56:26.390
immediately. Uh, but we can't
actually see the implementation.

00:56:26.460 --> 00:56:30.750
- But your instinct says that
individuals were very important

00:56:31.570 --> 00:56:33.770
in the development of that
idea and execution of it.

00:56:33.790 --> 00:56:37.650
- Probably, yeah. Yeah. Even though
it's part of a long-term process

00:56:37.710 --> 00:56:42.810
of expanding Roman citizenship, this was
a, an explosion, not just an expansion.

00:56:43.310 --> 00:56:46.970
- And then you said that one of the
important aspects about this edict is

00:56:47.070 --> 00:56:50.990
that giving equal rights to provincials

00:56:51.070 --> 00:56:52.950
was one of the things
that helped deal with the

00:56:53.790 --> 00:56:57.420
crisis of the third century,
and was the thing that,

00:56:57.990 --> 00:57:01.550
I think you said, quote,
"sapped discontent from the

00:57:01.610 --> 00:57:07.070
relevant populations," which then
minimized the probability of uprisings.

00:57:07.090 --> 00:57:09.610
- Well, now that's a very long-term process.

00:57:09.650 --> 00:57:13.150
Now, the third century is chaos,
there's a crisis, it's a mess, right?

00:57:13.570 --> 00:57:19.930
So what follows the edict is
quite a few decades of unrest.

00:57:20.190 --> 00:57:21.560
- Okay, let's put it in mildly.

00:57:21.570 --> 00:57:25.490
Let's talk about the crisis
of the third century, where

00:57:25.730 --> 00:57:30.730
26 emperors were murdered
in a period of 50 years.

00:57:30.930 --> 00:57:32.910
- Yes. It's tremendous instability.

00:57:33.310 --> 00:57:37.040
- So there's civil wars
nonstop. Almost all were,

00:57:37.270 --> 00:57:41.390
of these emperors were generals, and
almost all were murdered by their men.

00:57:42.670 --> 00:57:48.730
So civil war was the norm, hyperinflation,
economic crash, plus there's a plague-

00:57:48.870 --> 00:57:56.810
... from 249 to 262 AD, which is a
pandemic, possibly smallpox or Ebola. It

00:57:56.850 --> 00:58:00.750
killed up to 5,000 people a day
in Rome alone, devastating the

00:58:00.790 --> 00:58:05.710
tax base and army recruitment
pool. And the empire

00:58:07.010 --> 00:58:10.660
fractured into three
pieces, but then Emperor,

00:58:10.910 --> 00:58:15.550
Aurelian miraculously reconquered
them in a period of five years.

00:58:16.370 --> 00:58:20.860
So just a lot of chaos. It deserves the
name, the Crisis of the Third Century.

00:58:20.870 --> 00:58:24.560
- Yeah, it's a perfect storm. Yeah, I mean,
you have a crisis of imperial legitimacy.

00:58:24.630 --> 00:58:29.390
Basically, the army's proclaiming
emperors left and right. In an odd sense,

00:58:30.220 --> 00:58:33.490
ironically, this is in part
because there are now a lot more

00:58:33.590 --> 00:58:37.160
stakeholders in the Roman tradition, right?
There's all of these provincial armies,

00:58:37.290 --> 00:58:40.630
and they're appointing their
generals as rival emperors.

00:58:41.490 --> 00:58:46.850
But you also have a serious
uptick in foreign invasions.

00:58:47.430 --> 00:58:51.150
In the north, you have the creation
of the Sasanian Persian or

00:58:51.190 --> 00:58:54.350
Iranian Empire in the east, and
this was very, very bellicose.

00:58:55.410 --> 00:58:59.390
So lots of foreign defeats.
Armies are defeated by

00:58:59.730 --> 00:59:03.350
you know, like, quote, "barbarian
enemies." You have eventually

00:59:03.390 --> 00:59:09.650
inflation, and you have plague. And so
under the pressure, right, of all of those

00:59:09.690 --> 00:59:14.800
forces, it almost fell apart.
Now, it didn't actually.

00:59:14.830 --> 00:59:18.390
Inevitably, there are also historians
who downplay the crisis. Of course,

00:59:18.610 --> 00:59:22.430
right, like, and legitimately so, right?
We must push back against every of these

00:59:22.470 --> 00:59:23.310
characterizations.

00:59:23.610 --> 00:59:25.670
- 26 emperors died, bro. What do you-

00:59:25.690 --> 00:59:29.670
- That's just the emperors. That's
just the emperors. We should be

00:59:29.680 --> 00:59:31.490
- I'm sorry. In 50 years.

00:59:31.650 --> 00:59:31.890
- Yeah.

00:59:31.950 --> 00:59:33.550
- Every other year, emperor dead.

00:59:33.770 --> 00:59:34.310
- Yeah, that's-

00:59:34.330 --> 00:59:34.890
- Civil war

00:59:34.990 --> 00:59:38.340
- ... that's political instability
at the top, right? But what-

00:59:38.370 --> 00:59:39.060
- Right, that's not-

00:59:39.180 --> 00:59:40.810
- ... what are the l- the
lives of most people?

00:59:40.890 --> 00:59:40.900
- Sure.

00:59:40.910 --> 00:59:44.490
- So if you go to Egypt, for example,
which is kind of out of the... Right?

00:59:45.210 --> 00:59:48.970
What's going on there? How are people living there?
And we can see how people are living in Egypt

00:59:49.090 --> 00:59:51.790
because we have all these
papyrus documents from Egypt.

00:59:52.650 --> 00:59:53.370
- That's true.

00:59:53.400 --> 00:59:55.830
- And for the most part, they don't
seem to be experiencing a crisis.

00:59:56.270 --> 00:59:59.150
- I mean, this is something you talk
about. Constantine, as we'll get to him,

00:59:59.770 --> 01:00:03.570
is one of the most murderous
leaders in all of human

01:00:03.610 --> 01:00:07.579
history, if you consider
his own family. But

01:00:07.650 --> 01:00:13.730
if you're living in the provinces,
you know, there's... He's not-

01:00:13.750 --> 01:00:14.220
- Oh, yeah, yeah.

01:00:14.250 --> 01:00:15.230
- ... he's not that murderous.

01:00:15.290 --> 01:00:16.720
- No, no, no, he's perfectly
fine. Yeah, yeah.

01:00:16.730 --> 01:00:20.570
- So it's very important to actually remember
about what the actual experience of

01:00:20.630 --> 01:00:27.740
the average citizen of the empire is like.
Fair. Okay, so but how... Maybe there's

01:00:27.850 --> 01:00:31.710
more we could say about the crisis.
And then of course, the, the

01:00:31.750 --> 01:00:35.730
crisis is in part
resolved by Diocletian as

01:00:35.770 --> 01:00:38.830
he does a hard reset on the
structure on the Roman system of

01:00:38.870 --> 01:00:42.570
government. So maybe you could speak a
little bit more to the crisis that's

01:00:42.610 --> 01:00:48.010
important for us to understand, and how
Diocletian solves the crisis in 284 AD.

01:00:48.710 --> 01:00:52.410
- Right. So again, these are processes
rather than specific events.

01:00:52.530 --> 01:00:52.770
- Sure.

01:00:53.110 --> 01:00:56.950
- So for example, you mentioned that the
empire kind of breaks into pieces.

01:00:57.170 --> 01:00:57.670
- Yes.

01:00:57.710 --> 01:01:01.550
- And we have what's called
sometime the Empire of the Gauls.

01:01:02.170 --> 01:01:06.030
Gaul are modern France and sort
of Britain, for a while are, for

01:01:06.290 --> 01:01:09.810
a decade and a half or so, are kind
of like this little separatist-

01:01:09.820 --> 01:01:13.710
empire. So what's interesting
about that is that this was

01:01:13.790 --> 01:01:17.780
not an attempt to break away
from the empire. In other words,

01:01:17.810 --> 01:01:21.450
it's not some discontent provincials
who are just tired of Roman

01:01:21.530 --> 01:01:25.390
rule and wanna break away
and do their own thing. No.

01:01:26.650 --> 01:01:29.990
This is actually just
a, it's an attempt by,

01:01:30.280 --> 01:01:34.210
provincial generals to take the
throne, and do so to rule the entire

01:01:34.270 --> 01:01:38.460
empire. It doesn't work. They get only
as far as the provinces that they take.

01:01:38.930 --> 01:01:42.970
And the only way that they know to set
up a state is to make it a Roman state.

01:01:43.290 --> 01:01:47.170
Right? Like, that's the total of their
political imaginary is like, "Well,

01:01:47.390 --> 01:01:49.190
we're just gonna do a Roman thing here."

01:01:50.182 --> 01:01:53.882
And maybe we'll get, you
know, we'll reunite the

01:01:53.922 --> 01:01:57.882
empire ourselves, or as happened,
Aurelian, that is someone from the other

01:01:57.922 --> 01:02:01.842
side, will reunite the empire. But it's
always a Roman model. Like, there's,

01:02:01.942 --> 01:02:06.181
it's almost like there's no alternatives
by this point. So that's interesting.

01:02:07.042 --> 01:02:09.842
What Diocletian does essentially is,

01:02:11.502 --> 01:02:15.282
The, the way I characterize
it sometimes is that he

01:02:15.342 --> 01:02:17.182
turns the problem into its own solution.

01:02:18.082 --> 01:02:21.282
In other words, the problem is too
many emperors or wanna-be emperors.

01:02:21.882 --> 01:02:25.872
Because there's just more going on. Like, one
emperor can't deal with all these problems

01:02:25.902 --> 01:02:28.442
along the frontiers, with
all the political problems.

01:02:29.502 --> 01:02:33.442
So what he does is he deputizes some
of his colleagues, people he was on

01:02:33.462 --> 01:02:37.312
very good terms with from the army. These are
all Illyrians. They're from... By the way,

01:02:37.722 --> 01:02:41.122
for a few centuries, the emperors are
all from this region of the former

01:02:41.162 --> 01:02:44.622
Yugoslavia that's the size of Scotland.
Like, that's where they all come from.

01:02:44.842 --> 01:02:45.762
- Well, what explains that?

01:02:46.042 --> 01:02:46.522
- Uh, the army.

01:02:47.042 --> 01:02:47.142
- Ah.

01:02:47.362 --> 01:02:50.962
- These are military men. Sometimes
hard-drinking military men.

01:02:51.182 --> 01:02:55.002
Very good at their job like Aurelian, you
mentioned, right? So there's a series of

01:02:55.041 --> 01:02:58.622
Illyrian emperors who

01:02:58.702 --> 01:03:02.522
restore stability. And the reason
why there's so many Illyrian

01:03:02.562 --> 01:03:06.332
emperors is because they worked their way
up through the ranks of the army. And,

01:03:06.622 --> 01:03:10.782
you know, the regions of Yugoslavia
in, at that time are sufficiently,

01:03:11.622 --> 01:03:15.742
you know, economically underdeveloped
that there's a strong incentive for,

01:03:16.682 --> 01:03:21.252
for young men to go join the army
because, you know, it's a living.

01:03:21.462 --> 01:03:25.202
Um, and so Illyrians become,
like, kind of the backbone of the

01:03:25.222 --> 01:03:29.182
Roman army, and they're described as
these, you know, tough Roman conservative

01:03:29.262 --> 01:03:33.022
types. I mean, these are, you
know, these are, these are tough

01:03:33.062 --> 01:03:37.042
military guys. I say that to
draw a contrast between, say,

01:03:37.082 --> 01:03:39.212
Hadrian, whom I mentioned earlier-

01:03:39.212 --> 01:03:42.922
... you know, who was a much more
sophisticated, artsy, poetic,

01:03:43.042 --> 01:03:44.262
cosmopolitan emperor.

01:03:44.862 --> 01:03:44.872
- Sure.

01:03:44.942 --> 01:03:48.522
- Also a hard-ass. You did not
wanna mess with Hadrian. But,

01:03:49.042 --> 01:03:52.762
These guys from the third century are military
men through and through. Like, their whole

01:03:52.802 --> 01:03:57.582
careers are in the army. And they
have, like, the military stubble.

01:03:57.622 --> 01:03:59.602
They've got these thick necks.

01:03:59.662 --> 01:04:03.122
They look angry. They've got their hands
on their swords. Like, they're not

01:04:03.162 --> 01:04:04.562
projecting an image of sort of-

01:04:04.622 --> 01:04:04.752
- Yeah.

01:04:04.752 --> 01:04:08.222
- ... calm and sophisticated,
you know, bum-bum, you know.

01:04:08.562 --> 01:04:09.782
- So, military men.

01:04:09.922 --> 01:04:10.422
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:04:10.431 --> 01:04:11.012
- ... military men from Aurelian.

01:04:11.142 --> 01:04:15.002
- Yep. So Diocletian gets a gang of them
together. They, eventually there are

01:04:15.042 --> 01:04:22.242
four. We call this the Tetrarchy. Um, and
he basically allocates them to various,

01:04:22.622 --> 01:04:26.172
um... This wasn't any kind of
hard division of the empire.

01:04:26.262 --> 01:04:30.122
Basically, it was a
collaborative project. They each

01:04:30.182 --> 01:04:31.522
went wherever they were needed.

01:04:31.782 --> 01:04:35.582
- Uh, was it, is it fair to say that
there was four administrative zones?

01:04:36.362 --> 01:04:38.222
He allocated each one to a zone?

01:04:38.302 --> 01:04:40.422
- Broadly. I'd say more military zones.

01:04:40.782 --> 01:04:40.922
- Okay.

01:04:41.042 --> 01:04:44.942
- Um, so the administration tends to
operate, it kind of humming along in the

01:04:45.002 --> 01:04:48.642
background wherever these emperors
happen to be, right? This is a,

01:04:49.242 --> 01:04:53.122
We're talking about a period of big
government now. So Diocletian creates a

01:04:53.162 --> 01:04:57.102
larger government, possibly a larger army,
and in order to pay for that, you need more

01:04:57.142 --> 01:04:58.752
systematic and effective taxation-

01:04:58.792 --> 01:04:58.832
- Mm-hmm.

01:04:58.832 --> 01:05:02.442
- ... which means you need more census, you need
more bureaucracy, you need more collect...

01:05:02.502 --> 01:05:05.722
You know? So it is an era
of bigger government.

01:05:05.782 --> 01:05:07.342
- So just to linger on that point-

01:05:07.442 --> 01:05:07.452
- Yeah.

01:05:07.452 --> 01:05:11.182
- ... is it fair to say that Diocletian
created the deep state? Quote, "deep state."

01:05:11.742 --> 01:05:14.392
So the tax collectors, the, the logistics,

01:05:15.202 --> 01:05:19.132
the thing that you've kinda hinted at, which
is the separation of the civil and the

01:05:19.202 --> 01:05:21.582
military layer of society.

01:05:21.962 --> 01:05:25.942
- So the concept of a deep state,
I've had discussions about that

01:05:26.082 --> 01:05:29.832
with experts who work on the
idea of the deep state, and I'm

01:05:29.902 --> 01:05:33.752
not sure that I would characterize
the Roman Empire that

01:05:33.782 --> 01:05:37.642
way, in part because while you do have big
government, you do have bureaucracy, you

01:05:37.722 --> 01:05:41.622
have, you have bureaucrats who are
buried in various echelons, and you

01:05:41.662 --> 01:05:43.962
know, nobody knows exactly what
they're doing and things like that,

01:05:44.922 --> 01:05:48.732
you know, I have not come
across the idea of some sort of

01:05:48.822 --> 01:05:54.822
sinister elements, you know, who are working
within the administrative apparatus to

01:05:54.882 --> 01:05:57.622
undermine the emperor.

01:05:58.082 --> 01:06:02.362
Like, from a distance occasionally, you
might get glimpses of this kind of thing.

01:06:02.392 --> 01:06:06.242
Diocletian, for example, once complained that, "Nobody
ever tells me anything." In other words, like,

01:06:06.282 --> 01:06:07.292
he's so removed-

01:06:07.482 --> 01:06:11.362
... in part from the realities of
what's going on on the ground that he,

01:06:11.482 --> 01:06:17.792
felt sometimes he'd lost touch. But
I don't find this kind of idea of of

01:06:17.822 --> 01:06:21.082
undermining imperial power
from within the bureaucracy.

01:06:21.242 --> 01:06:25.212
- Yeah, I think the, one of the ways
to explain that is because, so, you

01:06:25.242 --> 01:06:26.342
know, in the modern day,

01:06:27.282 --> 01:06:32.442
democracy in quotes, there's a kind of
temporary nature to the leader at the top.

01:06:32.492 --> 01:06:35.002
So it's incentivized
the deep state to form.

01:06:35.082 --> 01:06:38.082
That, so the deep state thinks
of themselves as a thing that

01:06:38.122 --> 01:06:41.842
propagates long-term periods
of time, and then the

01:06:41.922 --> 01:06:44.402
leader is a very ephemeral
short, short-term thing.

01:06:45.182 --> 01:06:45.452
- Yeah.

01:06:45.482 --> 01:06:47.072
- With a, with an emperor, technically-

01:06:47.072 --> 01:06:50.982
... you can go for a long time, so
it's best to be integrated deeply.

01:06:51.502 --> 01:06:55.402
With, the bureaucracy should be integrated
with the leader. It makes sense.

01:06:55.702 --> 01:06:56.942
- Yeah. But also,

01:06:56.992 --> 01:06:57.052
- Fair enough

01:06:57.052 --> 01:07:03.322
- ... also in, in, in modern social thought
or, or fear is that the deep state might

01:07:03.362 --> 01:07:04.722
be undermining, say...

01:07:04.802 --> 01:07:05.482
- Undermining, yeah

01:07:05.582 --> 01:07:09.512
- ... the democracy itself rather than,
right, rather than... It can cut both ways.

01:07:09.822 --> 01:07:13.462
- But there is a bureaucracy.
There is a big government.

01:07:13.582 --> 01:07:14.272
- Absolutely. Yeah.

01:07:14.302 --> 01:07:15.432
- There's a big machinery.

01:07:15.622 --> 01:07:17.342
- Yeah, compared to before.

01:07:17.411 --> 01:07:17.822
- Before.

01:07:17.852 --> 01:07:18.062
- Yes.

01:07:18.922 --> 01:07:22.882
So Diocletian creates these larger bureaucratic
structures, and these are the ones that define

01:07:22.902 --> 01:07:26.872
the society that I study. So
as a specialist, I focus on

01:07:26.902 --> 01:07:29.052
the period after him mostly.

01:07:29.202 --> 01:07:33.082
But he implemented those to
solve a lot of these problems.

01:07:33.522 --> 01:07:37.402
He was mostly successful. So in
terms of generating revenue from

01:07:37.482 --> 01:07:43.482
a much more troubled and kind of
precarious situation in sustaining large

01:07:43.562 --> 01:07:50.722
armies and putting down these
rebellions and usurpations. And he was

01:07:50.822 --> 01:07:52.382
generally successful at doing that.

01:07:53.222 --> 01:07:59.142
So he created the model that they kept for
the next, Well, three centuries or more.

01:08:00.332 --> 01:08:04.672
- But a lot of the elements of that
model lasted even beyond that, right?

01:08:04.832 --> 01:08:08.592
- Yeah, like universal taxation. I'll
give you an example. Up until then,

01:08:09.592 --> 01:08:13.492
Italy was exempt from taxes. Italy was the land
of the conquerors. The conquerors don't pay

01:08:13.532 --> 01:08:16.952
taxes to themselves. The conquerors
live off the taxes that others pay,

01:08:17.492 --> 01:08:21.332
right? So Italy was this
big tax haven, right?

01:08:22.152 --> 01:08:25.612
Diocletian, Galerius, you know,
his guys, these guys are from

01:08:25.852 --> 01:08:27.592
Illyria. They're from the Balkans.

01:08:27.632 --> 01:08:31.612
Like why is Italy tax-free exactly, you
know? That doesn't make any sense. It's a

01:08:31.792 --> 01:08:35.592
very, very wealthy, prosperous part
of the world, and so, no, they

01:08:35.652 --> 01:08:39.622
tax Italy. So now, like, not only do all
Romans have the same citizenship and

01:08:39.622 --> 01:08:42.912
the same law, they all
have the same tax system,

01:08:43.532 --> 01:08:47.512
and the Diocletianic tax code, as it
were, it's not a code, it sounds like

01:08:47.572 --> 01:08:50.652
a flat tax, which for
us sounds regressive.

01:08:51.412 --> 01:08:55.012
But by those stand- by the standards
of that time, it's actually kind of

01:08:55.072 --> 01:08:56.132
progressive in a way.

01:08:56.632 --> 01:08:57.112
- Right.

01:08:57.132 --> 01:08:58.132
- It means that, like, even-

01:08:58.272 --> 01:08:58.282
- Right.

01:08:58.282 --> 01:09:00.952
- ... elites paid, like,
the same, right? Yeah.

01:09:01.992 --> 01:09:05.972
- So how much of all of this, everything
we'll talk about in the, in

01:09:06.012 --> 01:09:08.212
the coming centuries
is all about taxation?

01:09:08.652 --> 01:09:10.782
- I think it's huge. Taxation
is the heart of it.

01:09:12.392 --> 01:09:16.662
- So I mean, the functioning, the
success, the flourishing of a society,

01:09:17.532 --> 01:09:21.492
the way the government works, the way the
people are represented, all of it has to do,

01:09:21.522 --> 01:09:25.032
all the civil wars and everything, it
feels like taxation is at the core.

01:09:25.292 --> 01:09:30.052
- Yes. Yeah. If you asked me to put my
finger on one factor, it would be that.

01:09:30.592 --> 01:09:34.562
- So the taxation system,
that feels like the early

01:09:34.592 --> 01:09:36.972
framework for the East Roman Empire.

01:09:37.012 --> 01:09:40.892
- It did create a more sort of
homogeneous framework, for sure.

01:09:40.992 --> 01:09:44.432
By the end of the third century,
it's pretty much in place. What

01:09:44.452 --> 01:09:47.792
Diocletian does is a universal census,

01:09:48.492 --> 01:09:51.682
and this is continued by
his successors. So every

01:09:52.392 --> 01:09:58.552
taxable asset in the empire is censused.
And so you can now start to have a budget.

01:09:59.392 --> 01:10:02.502
- Now, there is some element, and
then you push back against that,

01:10:03.312 --> 01:10:10.152
some element of Diocletian where he legally
limited social and class mobility in

01:10:10.192 --> 01:10:14.052
part for the taxation
system, and made it, in many

01:10:14.132 --> 01:10:17.862
cases, illegal to move and
illegal to quit your job. For

01:10:17.912 --> 01:10:21.752
example, as I read to guarantee the food

01:10:21.792 --> 01:10:25.592
supply and land tax, farmers
were legally forbidden from

01:10:25.652 --> 01:10:29.452
moving away from the land they worked,
so the state always knew who to

01:10:29.472 --> 01:10:32.872
tax. And then for soldiers,
sons of veterans were

01:10:32.912 --> 01:10:37.632
legally obligated to serve in the
army to maintain troop numbers.

01:10:38.572 --> 01:10:42.052
You argue that these were tax enforcement

01:10:42.172 --> 01:10:46.052
mechanisms, not a rigid caste
system, and so in practice, the

01:10:46.112 --> 01:10:49.232
empire remained a society
of high mobility.

01:10:50.032 --> 01:10:51.772
- This is a complicated matter.

01:10:51.832 --> 01:10:55.812
So let's talk, for example,
about soldiers. It's probably

01:10:55.872 --> 01:11:02.832
the case that most soldiers' sons were
expected to succeed them. Like most

01:11:02.872 --> 01:11:06.492
professions where you have an
apprenticeship, the son will usually

01:11:06.532 --> 01:11:09.912
succeed, right? There
are a number of other

01:11:10.072 --> 01:11:15.132
professions that were kind of guild-like
in nature like for example, shipping.

01:11:15.472 --> 01:11:21.092
Uh, where there were considerable
assets involved in order to

01:11:21.112 --> 01:11:25.032
secure contracts for insurance
purposes for the ships and so forth,

01:11:25.232 --> 01:11:29.132
and it made sense for those assets to be, you
know, passed from father to son. In other

01:11:29.152 --> 01:11:32.892
words, and with them
comes the obligation to

01:11:32.932 --> 01:11:39.962
continue in that line of work. Some of
these things are inherently, sort of

01:11:40.102 --> 01:11:43.932
hereditary, and I don't think most
people would have objected to it.

01:11:44.692 --> 01:11:48.032
The farmers is probably the only case

01:11:48.272 --> 01:11:52.212
where it might have actually
involved some coercion. There was

01:11:52.292 --> 01:11:55.932
a category of farmers, and we don't
know how many of them, who were,

01:11:56.852 --> 01:11:59.192
for fiscal purposes, bound to the land.

01:12:00.092 --> 01:12:03.591
This doesn't mean they couldn't leave the land, like
physically. No one's preventing them from leaving.

01:12:03.652 --> 01:12:07.401
But they were fiscally responsible
for providing the taxes or rents or

01:12:07.432 --> 01:12:11.172
whatever because the state
wanted to have a secure

01:12:11.232 --> 01:12:15.172
revenue stream from, say, those lands.
And if... Anyway, it's, it's one of these

01:12:15.212 --> 01:12:19.121
complicated situations. This
did create some limitations on,

01:12:19.172 --> 01:12:22.892
on those people. And it's a
topic of current research,

01:12:23.492 --> 01:12:25.192
these bound farmers, as it were,

01:12:25.992 --> 01:12:29.252
who are tied to the land. It's more of
a... You know, someone put it that,

01:12:29.352 --> 01:12:33.192
you know, most of the time it's
people who own the land, and in

01:12:33.252 --> 01:12:35.732
this arrangement, it's the
land that owns the people.

01:12:36.402 --> 01:12:39.712
- But you're saying the bigger picture
thing is that there was mobility.

01:12:39.752 --> 01:12:40.362
- Oh, there's considerable mobility.

01:12:40.362 --> 01:12:42.422
- So, so class mobility- ...
and physical mobility-

01:12:42.422 --> 01:12:46.112
... meaning people moved a... And we'll
see this as from the West into the

01:12:46.212 --> 01:12:48.242
East and Constantinople and
all this kind of stuff.

01:12:48.242 --> 01:12:50.412
- Oh, yeah. There's tons of mobility.

01:12:50.632 --> 01:12:53.472
No, no, this is not a society
where people are bound really,

01:12:54.392 --> 01:12:58.192
to... We, like, we don't find
anybody who's, who's like, "Ah, I

01:12:59.372 --> 01:13:03.252
I really don't want to be a soldier. But my
father was a soldier, and I'm obligated to be

01:13:03.292 --> 01:13:05.992
one." Like- ... like, we just don't
hear those kinds of complaints-

01:13:06.452 --> 01:13:09.932
of people who don't want to be a so- Why wouldn't
you want to be a soldier in the Roman Empire?

01:13:09.962 --> 01:13:11.292
I mean, it's got tremendous perks.

01:13:11.392 --> 01:13:16.332
- Right. Right. So can we just linger
on the why is it that Diocletian

01:13:17.152 --> 01:13:21.052
was able to stabilize the
empire? It's like, you

01:13:21.072 --> 01:13:24.692
know, the crisis of the third century
really threatened to tear apart everything.

01:13:25.512 --> 01:13:29.952
So why did some of these things
that we talked about stabilize?

01:13:30.272 --> 01:13:33.322
- Well, Aurelian had already
united the empire territorially.

01:13:33.492 --> 01:13:35.162
So this is right before Diocletian.

01:13:36.112 --> 01:13:39.662
And what Diocletian did was
put in place a system that

01:13:39.672 --> 01:13:43.582
reduced the number of rebellions.
Simply by having four big guys with

01:13:43.612 --> 01:13:47.802
four armies, they managed to put out
all of those fires, or most of them.

01:13:48.692 --> 01:13:52.572
And once you have stability, and
he also beat the Persians, I

01:13:52.612 --> 01:13:56.052
mean, Galerius did so
starting to beat back foreign

01:13:56.092 --> 01:14:01.692
invasions, that creates a framework
for economic stability. People need

01:14:02.544 --> 01:14:06.304
To, you know, if they're going to
invest in, like, land reclamation

01:14:06.404 --> 01:14:10.224
or expand production, they
need to know that, you know,

01:14:10.304 --> 01:14:14.114
foreigners aren't gonna come rampaging through,
marauding through the, you know, stealing their

01:14:14.164 --> 01:14:17.744
cattle and, you know, enslaving
them and taking them off to work on

01:14:17.804 --> 01:14:20.674
agricultural farms in Mesopotamia.
Like, they need to know this.

01:14:20.974 --> 01:14:24.444
And if you provide that context of
stability, the economic growth, the

01:14:24.464 --> 01:14:30.044
demographic growth will return. And Diocletian
created that kind of, that context.

01:14:30.604 --> 01:14:35.294
- So that takes us to Constantine but
first a quick bathroom break, if I can.

01:14:35.324 --> 01:14:35.424
- Sure.

01:14:36.364 --> 01:14:40.304
- Quick ten-second thank you to our sponsors.
Check them out in the description. It really

01:14:40.404 --> 01:14:42.844
is the best way to support
this podcast. Go to

01:14:42.854 --> 01:14:46.564
lexfridman.com/sponsors.
And now, dear friends,

01:14:47.104 --> 01:14:51.024
back to our conversation about
the Eastern Roman Empire.

01:14:52.224 --> 01:14:55.864
All right, we're back, and
let's talk about Constantine

01:14:56.284 --> 01:15:00.064
and Constantinople. Let's go
to the rise of the East Roman

01:15:00.144 --> 01:15:04.014
Empire. Who was Constantine?
Tell me about his rise

01:15:04.044 --> 01:15:08.404
to power and the founding of
Constantinople in 330 AD.

01:15:08.704 --> 01:15:12.544
- Sure. So Constantine was the son
of one of Diocletian's colleagues,

01:15:12.964 --> 01:15:14.684
so he comes from within the system.

01:15:15.704 --> 01:15:19.544
And the system was actually designed
to be non-hereditary. In other words,

01:15:20.424 --> 01:15:24.264
the senior emperors would retire, the
junior ones would move up to the senior

01:15:24.284 --> 01:15:27.164
position, and then they
would recruit two new ones.

01:15:27.684 --> 01:15:31.404
And they tried to skip
the dynastic element. So,

01:15:31.664 --> 01:15:35.364
so it would be kind of, let's
just say, kinda meritocratic, not

01:15:35.724 --> 01:15:39.364
whose son, you know, you were. Constantine
was a son. He was passed over,

01:15:39.884 --> 01:15:42.974
but the armies liked him. He
was actually quite competent.

01:15:43.184 --> 01:15:47.084
And so there's a series of
civil wars among all of these

01:15:47.124 --> 01:15:50.674
successors of Diocletian, and
Constantine emerges as the winner.

01:15:51.364 --> 01:15:55.024
There are periods when there are quite a few of
them. There are, like, six at a time, but they gra-

01:15:55.564 --> 01:15:59.204
they gradually dwindle down to one. So

01:15:59.544 --> 01:16:03.344
yeah, it's as long as you have the
quarterfinals, semifinals, and then the final

01:16:03.364 --> 01:16:06.744
war, and Constantine
emerges in 324 as the sole

01:16:07.124 --> 01:16:11.093
ruler of the entire Roman Empire.
So that's who he is. He's

01:16:11.364 --> 01:16:14.704
definitely an insider,
very, very competent

01:16:14.924 --> 01:16:19.304
general at civil war. And he
gradually moves eastward.

01:16:20.124 --> 01:16:23.764
So as he's conquering his
rivals, who are often

01:16:23.824 --> 01:16:27.193
his father-in-laws or his brother-in-laws,
because these people are all

01:16:27.244 --> 01:16:30.353
intermarried, and they have alliances, and
they fall out. It's one of those kinds of

01:16:30.364 --> 01:16:34.344
situations. He moves eastward,
and by the time he defeats his

01:16:34.384 --> 01:16:41.574
last rival, this uh, an emperor called
Licinius, in 324 he's in the East. And

01:16:42.184 --> 01:16:45.684
Licinius had his headquarters
or one of his headquarters at

01:16:45.984 --> 01:16:49.284
this town called Byzantium. Byzantium is a

01:16:49.824 --> 01:16:53.064
city right where
Constantinople was founded.

01:16:53.524 --> 01:16:58.284
And it is at exactly the point where
Europe meets Asia, so on the Bosporus.

01:16:59.124 --> 01:17:03.114
And it's a very strategic location. It always had
been, right? So whoever controls the straits of

01:17:03.144 --> 01:17:06.364
the Bosporus, yeah, we don't need
to explain how important that is.

01:17:07.184 --> 01:17:10.884
And Constantine decides to create
a city named after himself,

01:17:11.024 --> 01:17:14.894
Constantinople, on that spot,
Byzantium. So Byzantium

01:17:14.944 --> 01:17:19.704
essentially ceases to exist as a city
and is replaced by Constantinople,

01:17:20.724 --> 01:17:24.124
AKA New Rome. So it's pretty clear
that right from the beginning,

01:17:24.244 --> 01:17:28.084
Constantine intended this
to be a kind of branch

01:17:28.164 --> 01:17:32.204
office of Rome in the East, a
kind of copy and paste of Rome

01:17:33.264 --> 01:17:37.964
in the East, and it's a plan that his
successors continued, right? Now,

01:17:39.864 --> 01:17:43.724
there are a number of
other cities in this,

01:17:43.844 --> 01:17:46.404
Let's say in the generation
or two before this,

01:17:47.404 --> 01:17:51.184
that were also treated as sort
of quasi-Romes. Basically,

01:17:51.544 --> 01:17:54.564
there was this historian in the third century
who said, "Well, wherever the emperor

01:17:54.704 --> 01:17:58.633
is, that's Rome," right? 'Cause
emperors are now itinerant.

01:17:58.714 --> 01:18:02.394
They're no longer staying at Rome.
They're mostly on the frontier, and

01:18:02.404 --> 01:18:06.124
Constantine is one of these frontier emperors.
They will sometimes visit Rome, maybe once or

01:18:06.164 --> 01:18:09.264
twice, maybe once a decade,
you know, something like this.

01:18:10.124 --> 01:18:14.064
So Rome becomes something
that can be sort of copied

01:18:14.084 --> 01:18:17.624
and pasted in other parts of the
empire, and a bunch of other cities get

01:18:17.704 --> 01:18:21.284
called, you know, a New
Rome, an Other Rome, an

01:18:21.323 --> 01:18:25.244
Alternative Rome, My
Rome. And Constantinople

01:18:25.304 --> 01:18:28.024
is the last and most successful of those.

01:18:28.744 --> 01:18:32.624
- So maybe can you speak geographically the
importance of Constantinople? It's an interesting

01:18:32.644 --> 01:18:34.204
place 'cause it-

01:18:35.584 --> 01:18:39.524
... when you're talking about a land so
large as the West and the East, with

01:18:39.584 --> 01:18:43.404
enemies, with threats from all
kinds of different directions, the

01:18:43.524 --> 01:18:46.744
location where the emperor
sits is important.

01:18:46.964 --> 01:18:48.384
- Very. So look at Rome,

01:18:49.584 --> 01:18:52.524
right? So it's right in the middle of Italy,
right in the middle of the Mediterranean.

01:18:53.204 --> 01:18:56.644
Very safe location in a way, but
it's very far from the frontiers.

01:18:57.284 --> 01:19:01.434
And this is a period when emperors
need to be with the armies, right?

01:19:01.444 --> 01:19:05.104
They're not senatorial emperors who are
sitting in Rome having meetings with

01:19:05.164 --> 01:19:10.424
senators. They are military emperors
who are marching along the frontiers,

01:19:11.264 --> 01:19:14.824
mostly with generals rather
than civilian administration.

01:19:15.504 --> 01:19:19.084
So they're doing their job.
Like, this is the hard

01:19:19.224 --> 01:19:24.754
work. They're slogging through the
mud of winter campaigns, right?

01:19:24.754 --> 01:19:27.404
Uh, they're not just sitting in a palace
enjoying themselves when they could.

01:19:28.944 --> 01:19:32.884
But Rome just becomes inconvenient
because of that. And if you

01:19:32.924 --> 01:19:35.684
look at Constantinople, it is

01:19:36.664 --> 01:19:41.984
kind of halfway between the Danube
frontier and the Euphrates frontier.

01:19:42.824 --> 01:19:46.744
So if you want to prioritize the
East or treat it as an equal part of

01:19:46.784 --> 01:19:49.494
the Roman Empire, as these
emperors all did. In fact,

01:19:50.444 --> 01:19:54.264
almost all emperors who had a choice
about whether they would stay in the East

01:19:54.324 --> 01:19:58.164
or stay in the West chose the
East. There's only one who

01:19:58.204 --> 01:20:01.994
chooses the West, and that's Valentinian
later in the fourth century. All the others

01:20:02.024 --> 01:20:04.044
understand that the East is where it's at.

01:20:04.988 --> 01:20:08.757
And Constantinople is right between the Danube
and the Euphrates. These are two major frontiers.

01:20:09.368 --> 01:20:12.128
And so it allows emperors
to move between the two.

01:20:13.088 --> 01:20:16.888
And also look at its location
north, south, east, west, right? So

01:20:16.908 --> 01:20:21.488
north, south, it is the node between
the Black Sea and the Mediterranean,

01:20:22.308 --> 01:20:26.208
right? And east, west, it's
precisely where Europe meets Asia,

01:20:26.868 --> 01:20:30.808
right? And because there's a break
there, so there's a Bosporus, the

01:20:30.888 --> 01:20:34.468
Sea of Marmara, the Hellespont,
the Roman Empire during the civil

01:20:34.568 --> 01:20:37.698
wars, it would tend to break there.

01:20:38.008 --> 01:20:41.858
And you would have one emperor on one side in Asia,
and you would have another emperor on the other

01:20:41.888 --> 01:20:45.528
side. And this just kept happening. And

01:20:45.608 --> 01:20:52.628
Constantinople ultimately functions as a
kind of clamp that unifies this whole area,

01:20:53.168 --> 01:21:00.478
so basically the Balkans and Asia
Minor and Syria as a kind of unit,

01:21:00.968 --> 01:21:04.888
right? And, you know,
what is a new Rome? A new

01:21:04.908 --> 01:21:11.748
Rome is, among other things, a new senate,
right? And Constantine and his successors

01:21:11.808 --> 01:21:15.008
recruit this new senate for the new

01:21:15.048 --> 01:21:18.888
Rome. So we're talking about maybe
two and a half thousand, 3,000

01:21:19.108 --> 01:21:22.668
men, you know, at, at, at
its peak, and these are all

01:21:22.728 --> 01:21:25.508
recruited from all of these areas.
You know, some come from Rome,

01:21:26.368 --> 01:21:29.968
but others come from the Aegean
region, from Asia Minor,

01:21:30.688 --> 01:21:33.788
Eastern Mediterranean. So these
are the wealthiest people,

01:21:34.208 --> 01:21:37.768
usually most well-connected elites
from the whole Eastern Mediterranean,

01:21:38.268 --> 01:21:42.708
and they come together and form a new
purpose, common purpose in Constantinople.

01:21:43.508 --> 01:21:44.908
And the empire never breaks there again.

01:21:46.108 --> 01:21:49.828
Right? So it, it holds together
this part of the world. The

01:21:49.848 --> 01:21:52.388
breaking point now, interestingly,
moves to the Adriatic,

01:21:53.568 --> 01:21:57.698
right? So when, in 395, we talked
about East and West kind of splitting.

01:21:57.748 --> 01:22:01.428
It breaks at the Adriatic 'cause
Constantinople is now holding that whole

01:22:01.468 --> 01:22:05.208
Eastern world together. 'Cause all
of these elites, they now, they're

01:22:05.268 --> 01:22:09.168
invested in it. They're literally investing in
it. They have to invest in it in order to be

01:22:09.208 --> 01:22:10.358
senators in Constantinople.

01:22:11.308 --> 01:22:14.517
So that's kind of one of the functions that
it, that it performs, a strategic function.

01:22:15.428 --> 01:22:19.388
There's a political function. There's also
a cultural one, but you know, we can talk

01:22:19.428 --> 01:22:23.258
about that, too. But that's what you see
there on that map, the northwest, east,

01:22:23.308 --> 01:22:23.588
south.

01:22:24.408 --> 01:22:28.288
- So just to linger on it,
so you do a podcast,

01:22:28.368 --> 01:22:33.548
Byzantium and Friends, but you're also a
guest on podcasts, and I should mention

01:22:34.668 --> 01:22:38.248
you being a guest multiple
times on the excellent The

01:22:38.328 --> 01:22:42.268
History of Byzantium podcast
hosted by Robin Pierson. I

01:22:42.328 --> 01:22:45.848
highly recommend people listen to it, to all
of your appearances. You have a lot of really

01:22:45.928 --> 01:22:49.618
fascinating ones. But the reason I bring
all that up is one of the episodes,

01:22:50.268 --> 01:22:57.788
you do the fun thing of selecting the
top 10 emperors of Byzantium, and

01:22:58.108 --> 01:23:01.988
spoiler alert, everybody should go
listen to the full list 'cause you

01:23:02.048 --> 01:23:09.248
justify all the different options. But
Constantine ends up in the number one spot.

01:23:09.297 --> 01:23:13.208
And so can you just add a
little bit more depth why he

01:23:13.248 --> 01:23:15.588
would be in your number one spot-

01:23:15.748 --> 01:23:15.848
- Yes

01:23:15.868 --> 01:23:17.008
- ... now that we're talking about him?

01:23:17.408 --> 01:23:21.168
- Yes. It's not because I sort of like
him as a person, right? I mean-

01:23:21.718 --> 01:23:23.728
... as you said, he was pretty murderous.

01:23:23.888 --> 01:23:30.028
Right? All those wars, so clearly
ambitious, murderous, ruthless, basically.

01:23:30.268 --> 01:23:34.258
- Can you actually speak to the murderous
aspect? He seemed to have murdered a

01:23:34.308 --> 01:23:35.928
lot of people in his family.

01:23:36.528 --> 01:23:40.108
- Yes, that's because what we
call his family were also

01:23:40.228 --> 01:23:43.768
alliances of convenience that
he made on the way to the top.

01:23:44.568 --> 01:23:48.528
And when those alliances
or, you know, those, you

01:23:48.548 --> 01:23:52.168
know, those wives or those fathers-in-law
were no longer convenient or,

01:23:52.788 --> 01:23:56.768
or turned against him,
he had no hesitation in

01:23:56.808 --> 01:24:00.708
removing them. But he's also, you know, he

01:24:00.748 --> 01:24:05.348
gets a little extra bonus because he also
murdered his own son, Crispus, who was-

01:24:05.368 --> 01:24:10.668
... apparently a very competent and popular
kind of general, and we don't know why.

01:24:11.208 --> 01:24:14.928
He executes Crispus soon
after defeating Licinius,

01:24:15.828 --> 01:24:18.608
and then follows it up with
the murder of his wife-

01:24:18.688 --> 01:24:22.648
... not Crispus' mother, and we don't
know why. The funny thing is that when

01:24:22.688 --> 01:24:26.508
emperors do this sort of thing, if
there's any kind of remotely, like, a

01:24:26.548 --> 01:24:30.488
good reason, they'll blast it through
all of the media, right? Like, "Crispus

01:24:30.528 --> 01:24:34.568
was rebelling against me," or
whatever. There's nothing.

01:24:34.628 --> 01:24:38.088
He doesn't even try to justify it,
which means it must have been something

01:24:38.708 --> 01:24:41.048
unjustifiable- Like, I don't
know. I can't process it.

01:24:41.628 --> 01:24:45.518
- And also, I read that the
historians of the time would

01:24:45.548 --> 01:24:46.988
just ignore that that happened.

01:24:47.708 --> 01:24:50.568
- Yes. Well, sort of. So

01:24:51.508 --> 01:24:54.948
when Crispus is alive, it's all,
like, praising Crispus as, "Oh,

01:24:55.308 --> 01:24:58.488
Constantine, you great emperor, and your
wonderful son who will..." whatever.

01:24:58.548 --> 01:25:01.478
And then Crispus is executed, and
he just disappears from the, like-

01:25:01.478 --> 01:25:02.348
... they never talk about him.

01:25:02.388 --> 01:25:08.168
- Yeah. Actually, as another side
to a side, I think you mentioned,

01:25:09.288 --> 01:25:13.268
Whether it's on your podcast or
elsewhere, that if, if you had

01:25:13.328 --> 01:25:16.708
to have a beer with any of the
emperors, that you probably wouldn't.

01:25:17.488 --> 01:25:21.228
So it's not like some of the
most impactful, some of the

01:25:21.268 --> 01:25:24.777
most influential and great
emperors that we talk about,

01:25:25.508 --> 01:25:27.808
they might not be very pleasant people.

01:25:28.678 --> 01:25:32.588
- So let's set aside whether you'd like to have
a beer with these people. The reason I put

01:25:32.628 --> 01:25:36.128
Constantine at the top of the list is
because the decisions that he made were so

01:25:36.168 --> 01:25:39.418
consequential, just important, and

01:25:40.648 --> 01:25:49.328
for the most part, not bad decisions.
So I couldn't not put him at the

01:25:49.388 --> 01:25:52.448
top of the list. The,
you know, the creating

01:25:52.488 --> 01:25:56.408
Constantinople and converting to Christianity
and setting the empire on a path

01:25:56.448 --> 01:26:01.358
to conversion, these are major,
like, world history level decisions.

01:26:02.068 --> 01:26:05.908
Right? Now, not many emperors do
that. In fact, Constantine is in,

01:26:05.928 --> 01:26:08.668
like, his own league when it comes
to those kinds of decisions.

01:26:09.880 --> 01:26:15.060
My other criteria for top emperors were
basically those who did the job well,

01:26:16.280 --> 01:26:19.960
right? Not making, you know, these
kinds of earth, you know, shattering

01:26:20.030 --> 01:26:23.640
decisions or, you know, world
history changing decisions, but just

01:26:24.140 --> 01:26:28.020
who performed the role competently with

01:26:28.080 --> 01:26:33.180
results that impacted the lives
of their subjects for the better.

01:26:33.420 --> 01:26:35.080
So those are the other
criteria that I used.

01:26:35.920 --> 01:26:39.420
It's difficult to juggle these different
criteria, right, in order to create a

01:26:39.460 --> 01:26:42.990
systematic list. And by the way, we, historians
generally don't do these kinds of things.

01:26:43.200 --> 01:26:45.100
But you said it's fun. It is fun.

01:26:45.160 --> 01:26:45.610
- It was fun. It was fun.

01:26:45.720 --> 01:26:50.300
- And it allows you to talk about certain
things that you might not otherwise do.

01:26:50.820 --> 01:26:53.000
So yeah, that's why
Constantine was at the top.

01:26:53.520 --> 01:26:57.460
- So you mentioned Christianity. That
was one other big component of his

01:26:57.500 --> 01:27:01.300
rule. What was the role of Christianity
in, in Constantine's life,

01:27:02.020 --> 01:27:07.460
in the lives of the citizens
of the new Roman Empire?

01:27:08.180 --> 01:27:12.680
- At this stage, Christianity doesn't have
a role. It actually took the emperors...

01:27:13.520 --> 01:27:17.400
When the emperors took it on board,
that is, they made it a part

01:27:17.440 --> 01:27:21.300
of the imperial system, then
it began to acquire a role

01:27:21.340 --> 01:27:25.190
within the system. Previously, it
had imagined itself as having its

01:27:25.240 --> 01:27:28.600
own history, like not
necessarily part of the

01:27:28.660 --> 01:27:32.500
empire or affiliated
with imperial power. But

01:27:32.580 --> 01:27:34.520
after Constantine, it does acquire a role.

01:27:34.880 --> 01:27:38.700
- And so actually, one way to ask that question,
which is fascinating, 'cause you said that there's

01:27:38.740 --> 01:27:42.780
like, there's Rome, and then
there's like cultures like,

01:27:43.800 --> 01:27:50.380
or traditions like Christianity, or
being Greek, that kind of thing.

01:27:51.360 --> 01:27:55.020
So, one of the ways to ask this
question is does Christianity

01:27:55.140 --> 01:27:58.710
triumph over Rome, or did
Rome capture Christianity?

01:27:58.800 --> 01:28:00.180
- Right. Yes. That's a—

01:28:00.520 --> 01:28:03.060
- Which is the mechanism?

01:28:04.080 --> 01:28:07.460
- I would lean more toward the second.
In other words, that the religion was

01:28:07.540 --> 01:28:11.440
co-opted by the imperial system.
Now, there are many areas in which

01:28:11.800 --> 01:28:15.180
that's not the case and where the opposite
happens, so I'm not going to be absolute about it,

01:28:15.800 --> 01:28:18.080
but I think it's very important
to recognize that because

01:28:19.080 --> 01:28:22.680
Christianity generates
this narrative of triumph-

01:28:22.780 --> 01:28:25.480
...right, which modern
historians perpetuate,

01:28:26.340 --> 01:28:30.220
and it's framed in very particular ways. In
other words, that Christianity triumphs over the

01:28:30.260 --> 01:28:35.320
ancient religions. Right? So
displacing Zeus and Apollo and all of

01:28:35.440 --> 01:28:39.380
that, and animal sacrifice is gone,
and like, that's because Christianity

01:28:39.440 --> 01:28:43.180
triumphs, and that's a very narrow way of
looking at it. In other words, you pick your

01:28:43.220 --> 01:28:45.340
enemy, and then you can
defeat that enemy, right?

01:28:46.140 --> 01:28:50.020
But if you look in the other direction, there's,
like, the Roman imperial state, and you

01:28:50.060 --> 01:28:53.680
cannot say that Christianity
either triumphed over it or

01:28:53.840 --> 01:28:56.600
even tamed it or anything. It
actually became part of it.

01:28:56.980 --> 01:29:00.600
in many ways that, you know,
determined its history for

01:29:00.660 --> 01:29:02.440
centuries and, in fact, down to today.

01:29:03.240 --> 01:29:06.540
So this is very different, for
example, from the history of Islam.

01:29:07.320 --> 01:29:11.310
So Islam comes into existence without a

01:29:11.480 --> 01:29:15.420
preexisting state to receive
it and take it on board. It

01:29:15.500 --> 01:29:19.210
creates its own state,
right? So the Muslim armies,

01:29:19.609 --> 01:29:23.580
they conquer this empire, and then
they have to sort of govern it.

01:29:23.680 --> 01:29:27.490
They think according to whatever Islamic
principles. The Quran doesn't say anything about

01:29:27.500 --> 01:29:28.760
running an empire.

01:29:29.000 --> 01:29:32.600
So that creates a completely different
society, right, where, like,

01:29:32.640 --> 01:29:36.150
Islam is a, is really a
primary kind of identity and,

01:29:36.640 --> 01:29:40.300
like, drives a lot of developments.
But Christianity comes into

01:29:40.320 --> 01:29:43.980
existence within a very
well-developed society and, and

01:29:44.080 --> 01:29:45.620
political system. Now, here's the thing.

01:29:46.440 --> 01:29:50.190
We don't know exactly how many Christians
existed in the time of Constantine.

01:29:50.200 --> 01:29:54.100
Well, we speculate maybe 10% of
the empire. That might be very

01:29:54.140 --> 01:29:57.700
high, right? But even if it's 10%, it's

01:29:57.760 --> 01:30:01.580
not a lot, and these are not, like,
elites for the most part. Maybe

01:30:01.740 --> 01:30:05.440
middle, you know, what we
loosely call middle class,

01:30:06.420 --> 01:30:09.270
a few elites, a few slaves,
like this kind of thing.

01:30:10.060 --> 01:30:14.190
Mostly urban, and keeping in mind,
most of the population is rural.

01:30:14.420 --> 01:30:18.270
Right? So pockets of
concentrated, you know,

01:30:18.280 --> 01:30:21.820
Christian groups in cities. That's
what we're talking about. Not terribly

01:30:21.860 --> 01:30:22.820
politically powerful.

01:30:22.960 --> 01:30:26.730
- So Constantine's conversion to Christianity
and moving the empire towards Christianity is

01:30:26.820 --> 01:30:30.250
not something where it's a
gigantic majority of the people-

01:30:30.250 --> 01:30:34.240
... or it's a political convenience because
it's the elites. It's something else.

01:30:34.280 --> 01:30:38.480
I mean, it's, I mean, a pretty
revolutionary decision, I would say.

01:30:38.580 --> 01:30:42.100
- Exactly. Now, there used to be theories
that Constantine did this for, like,

01:30:42.180 --> 01:30:46.040
pragmatic, cynical reasons, that he, like,
wasn't a true Christian or anything, but there

01:30:46.080 --> 01:30:50.000
was some kind of political gain
to be had here. But I have never

01:30:50.540 --> 01:30:54.020
read a convincing account of what
exactly that political gain is.

01:30:54.900 --> 01:30:58.700
We now know that there are
fewer Christians. They were not

01:30:58.720 --> 01:31:02.300
that influential. You can make an
argument that bishops are a kind of

01:31:02.340 --> 01:31:06.219
convenient social influencers, you
might say. Like, you can use those.

01:31:06.440 --> 01:31:08.160
They're not a threat to your position.

01:31:08.460 --> 01:31:10.260
Right? So a bishop is not
gonna try to take the throne.

01:31:11.240 --> 01:31:15.120
So they're not dangerous political
operatives in that way. But they

01:31:15.140 --> 01:31:18.300
do have some influence over sectors
of society, and so that might be

01:31:18.380 --> 01:31:22.100
a... Okay, I see that,
but I don't quite see the

01:31:22.180 --> 01:31:24.390
argument for, like, going full Christian,

01:31:25.320 --> 01:31:28.940
Just to get the support of some bishops,
who actually pretty quickly turn out to be,

01:31:29.400 --> 01:31:30.839
some of them, more trouble
than they're worth.

01:31:31.660 --> 01:31:35.400
Anyway, so I have not
yet seen a convincing

01:31:35.660 --> 01:31:39.580
like, political argument for Constantine's
decision, which means that you then

01:31:39.680 --> 01:31:43.340
fall back on a personal
explanation that he did this

01:31:43.360 --> 01:31:47.080
because he was a believing
Christian, right? And he came out,

01:31:47.360 --> 01:31:51.240
You know, in support of the religion
that he held, and that's kind of

01:31:51.260 --> 01:31:54.340
where most scholars are today.
Though, I gotta tell you,

01:31:55.340 --> 01:31:59.100
historians are very uncomfortable
about personal choice, like explaining

01:31:59.120 --> 01:32:01.220
history in terms of these
kinds of personal choices.

01:32:02.260 --> 01:32:05.960
Because Constantine's conversion
is like, it's massive. It

01:32:06.060 --> 01:32:11.540
opens the door. It incentivizes
so many people to also convert.

01:32:11.730 --> 01:32:15.580
'Cause Romans will generally do
what their, you know, rulers

01:32:15.640 --> 01:32:19.480
will tell them. If we've
mentioned Hadrian a few times

01:32:19.520 --> 01:32:23.240
Hadrian's, he had this lover,
Antinous, Greek boy from Bithynia,

01:32:23.820 --> 01:32:26.770
who died in an accident in Egypt,
whatever, and Hadrian said

01:32:27.312 --> 01:32:30.932
Basically that Antinous should be
regarded as a god throughout the empire.

01:32:31.852 --> 01:32:35.772
And he was. We have, like, more statues
and busts of Antinous from all of

01:32:35.792 --> 01:32:39.051
these temples all over the empire than
I think of anyone else except Hadrian.

01:32:39.912 --> 01:32:43.622
So yeah, if, if the emperor says, like, "This
is a person who's a god now, you know, put

01:32:43.692 --> 01:32:45.402
statues of him everywhere," they will.

01:32:45.492 --> 01:32:49.452
And when Constantine comes out in favor of
Christianity, you know, suddenly people

01:32:49.472 --> 01:32:53.042
discover that, oh, this is an interesting
rite. It's got the support of the emperor.

01:32:53.732 --> 01:32:57.592
- So one of the things here, going to the Perplexity,
Constantine's conversion to Christianity is

01:32:57.652 --> 01:33:00.692
usually dated to 312 AD,

01:33:01.412 --> 01:33:04.892
Linked to a visionary experience
before the Battle of the Milvian

01:33:04.972 --> 01:33:12.012
Bridge. Do you believe that vision, that he
had this religious experience before the

01:33:12.032 --> 01:33:15.802
Battle of the Milvian Bridge? Here
it says, "But historians debate

01:33:15.832 --> 01:33:17.792
both its nature and its sincerity."

01:33:18.392 --> 01:33:18.542
- Well-

01:33:18.812 --> 01:33:20.222
- Do you believe the sincerity
of that experience?

01:33:20.312 --> 01:33:22.002
- Before we even get to the sincerity-

01:33:22.002 --> 01:33:25.192
... is the problem of the sources. This
is reported by authors writing later

01:33:25.992 --> 01:33:28.282
in the aftermath of a victory
when the emperor... Like,

01:33:29.092 --> 01:33:33.072
one of them had a dinner conversation with
the emperor a few decades later, and he

01:33:33.092 --> 01:33:36.412
said, "Well, let me tell you about the Milvian Bridge."
And it's like, okay, I'm not gonna believe that.

01:33:36.632 --> 01:33:38.372
I'm not gonna take that
at face value, rather.

01:33:38.472 --> 01:33:42.372
It's a much more complicated...
You know, this is how the emperor

01:33:42.412 --> 01:33:43.862
wants things to be remembered.

01:33:43.862 --> 01:33:47.572
That's different. Also, Constantine tended
to have a lot of religious visions.

01:33:47.612 --> 01:33:51.532
He had had religious visions of
Apollo before Christ, and we have

01:33:51.592 --> 01:33:55.492
sources that talk about that, too, that he went
to this temple in Gaul, and Apollo appeared to

01:33:55.512 --> 01:33:59.412
him in the form of light. Okay, Constantine
has a religious vision every time

01:33:59.432 --> 01:34:03.242
he kind of wants to shift
policies. And his, like,

01:34:03.502 --> 01:34:06.792
profile. Like, when he wanted to
break away from his other emperors

01:34:07.512 --> 01:34:10.992
who used to go for the, like, they went
for this kind of Jupiter/Hercules model.

01:34:11.002 --> 01:34:14.712
And he shifted to an Apollo model. This
is a branding. This is emperors doing

01:34:14.772 --> 01:34:15.292
branding.

01:34:15.752 --> 01:34:19.672
- So we should say that, as you've
described, Constantine is a

01:34:19.752 --> 01:34:21.512
pragmatist. He's very pragmatic.

01:34:22.372 --> 01:34:22.532
- Yeah.

01:34:22.802 --> 01:34:26.712
- But you're saying it's fair
to believe, based on the

01:34:26.792 --> 01:34:31.832
evidence, that he actually converged
towards being a Christian believer.

01:34:32.112 --> 01:34:36.072
- Yeah. It's very possible, in
fact plausible, that he thought

01:34:36.082 --> 01:34:39.312
the Christian God had
helped him in battle. And,

01:34:40.152 --> 01:34:43.592
you know, for someone like him, that's as
good a reason as any to support that god.

01:34:44.252 --> 01:34:48.012
- But he was not, like, a hardcore
Christian all the way through.

01:34:48.632 --> 01:34:52.532
He was a kind of a spiritual,
religious kind of person. He

01:34:52.592 --> 01:34:59.952
thought about religions more generally and
just converged towards Christianity as

01:35:00.092 --> 01:35:04.392
a good religion. He also had ideas
about what a good religion is-

01:35:04.442 --> 01:35:08.632
... and what a bad religion is, that kind
of stuff. So he's thinking in this space.

01:35:08.672 --> 01:35:11.412
- He's tending not to be too explicit.

01:35:11.532 --> 01:35:15.472
Depending on the audience. So
Constantine remains a pragmatist

01:35:15.532 --> 01:35:20.172
in the sense that he doesn't want to
alienate too many of his subjects, right?

01:35:20.192 --> 01:35:20.932
- Mm-hmm. Fair. Mm-hmm.

01:35:20.972 --> 01:35:25.892
- And so he's sometimes a bit
coy or elusive about what he's

01:35:25.932 --> 01:35:29.832
getting at. When he's talking to
Christians, he will talk about Christ. He

01:35:29.872 --> 01:35:33.472
will mention Christ. When he's talking to
everybody else in, like, a general law,

01:35:34.252 --> 01:35:38.232
he'll just refer to good
religion. And it's like, maybe

01:35:38.272 --> 01:35:43.352
you know what I mean, right? But he's not
gonna, like, you know, come to Jesus.

01:35:43.512 --> 01:35:43.671
- Yeah.

01:35:43.832 --> 01:35:43.862
- Right?

01:35:43.862 --> 01:35:44.072
- Yeah.

01:35:44.552 --> 01:35:49.892
- So even at the time when he's,
like, supporting the church, like,

01:35:50.672 --> 01:35:54.492
basically institutionalizing the
church as part of the imperial

01:35:54.532 --> 01:35:57.992
system, but he's also putting up
statues of himself that look like

01:35:58.032 --> 01:36:01.892
Apollo in Constantinople,
right? So the focal point of

01:36:01.932 --> 01:36:04.652
Constantine's Constantinople
is the Forum of Constantine.

01:36:04.882 --> 01:36:08.732
And in the middle is this very tall
column, and it has a colossal statue of

01:36:08.792 --> 01:36:12.542
Constantine on top, gilded, enormous

01:36:12.572 --> 01:36:16.552
thing. I don't know, like, eight
meters tall or whatever. But it's a

01:36:16.612 --> 01:36:20.392
repurposed Apollo. It's even, it,
like, visibly so. It's naked. It

01:36:20.452 --> 01:36:22.342
has the rays coming out of the-

01:36:22.342 --> 01:36:25.692
... head, right? Right. And everybody
knew it was an Apollo. So that's

01:36:25.932 --> 01:36:29.192
Constantine in the guise of
his old patron god, Apollo.

01:36:30.092 --> 01:36:33.822
Still, but he's still Christian
Constantine, so he's sending all of these

01:36:33.872 --> 01:36:34.652
different messages.

01:36:34.872 --> 01:36:38.492
- I mean, he likes being the god-like
figure. I mean, that whole

01:36:38.552 --> 01:36:40.732
statue just is like, "I am the god."

01:36:41.192 --> 01:36:43.892
- Yeah. It's assimilating yourself
to... Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:36:43.932 --> 01:36:47.912
- And I mean, a lot of the Romans, is it fair
to say, kinda saw the emperor a little

01:36:47.992 --> 01:36:48.222
bit in that light?

01:36:48.231 --> 01:36:50.632
- No, yeah. Oh, yeah. They
called him divine and-

01:36:50.712 --> 01:36:54.592
... yeah. There's not a hard theology there,
right? Like, if you pressed them on the actual

01:36:54.632 --> 01:36:55.561
theology, they wouldn't-

01:36:56.212 --> 01:37:00.072
... they wouldn't say the emperor
is a god. No. This is mushy.

01:37:00.132 --> 01:37:01.572
This gets very, very mushy.

01:37:01.692 --> 01:37:07.332
- But I mean, a lot of the Christians
have a kinda humility before God.

01:37:07.952 --> 01:37:11.752
I think when you have an emperor that's
god-like, it gets a little weird-

01:37:11.872 --> 01:37:12.992
- Yes. Yes

01:37:13.002 --> 01:37:15.412
- ... in the way you talk about God.

01:37:15.472 --> 01:37:19.402
- It depends on the context. Like, there are
contexts in which you are an emperor and

01:37:19.412 --> 01:37:23.272
you're proclaiming your majesty, and then
there are more personal contexts where you

01:37:23.372 --> 01:37:27.292
might be more humble because, I
don't know, you're being baptized or

01:37:27.332 --> 01:37:29.152
something. Like, those
are different contexts.

01:37:29.812 --> 01:37:33.652
- So can you speak to the whole process of
the conversion to Christianity, of the-

01:37:33.692 --> 01:37:37.612
... propagation of Christianity throughout
the empire and, and Constantine's role in

01:37:37.672 --> 01:37:37.802
that?

01:37:38.072 --> 01:37:41.992
- Constantine, or his successors
as well, because this was a

01:37:42.012 --> 01:37:45.752
gradual process, and it takes
a very long time. So let's,

01:37:46.412 --> 01:37:48.112
Let's put it into perspective.

01:37:49.432 --> 01:37:52.912
We probably can't talk about
a majority Christian society

01:37:53.112 --> 01:37:57.082
until maybe the 5th century, or early 5th-

01:37:57.082 --> 01:38:00.412
... mid-5th. We don't
have data, obviously.

01:38:01.332 --> 01:38:04.912
And we can't talk about,
like, a solidly Christian

01:38:05.012 --> 01:38:08.982
society until early 6th century.
And by solidly, I mean maybe

01:38:09.012 --> 01:38:15.322
where the non-Christians are 10,
15%, right? So that's a long time.

01:38:15.432 --> 01:38:18.632
That's, like, five centuries after
Jesus. That's half a millennium.

01:38:19.412 --> 01:38:24.752
So we're talking about a half a millennial
process here. It's, it's very long.

01:38:25.012 --> 01:38:29.642
- But it's only a couple of centuries
after Constantine. So it takes-

01:38:29.642 --> 01:38:34.454
... about two centuries to really
make the Roman Empire Christian

01:38:34.724 --> 01:38:38.654
- Yes. So very slow conversion,
maybe, maybe up to 10%

01:38:38.654 --> 01:38:42.364
tops under Constantine.
Then obviously larger and

01:38:42.404 --> 01:38:45.924
larger groups join the church,
even if only nominally, right?

01:38:46.804 --> 01:38:50.684
Until you get to the sixth century when
you're clearly talking about a, you

01:38:50.704 --> 01:38:53.204
know, mostly or overwhelmingly
Christian society.

01:38:54.164 --> 01:38:56.324
A lot of this is just
done through incentives

01:38:57.504 --> 01:39:01.344
and disincentives, right?
So bishops are given

01:39:01.424 --> 01:39:05.274
funds with which to
distribute, like, charity and

01:39:05.364 --> 01:39:09.044
help to communities in
distress. They have lists of

01:39:09.104 --> 01:39:13.064
widows and whatever they support. Land is

01:39:13.084 --> 01:39:16.804
given to the church by the
emperors or in wills so that they

01:39:16.844 --> 01:39:20.464
can engage in this kind of social policy.
And then there are disincentives. So

01:39:20.524 --> 01:39:25.414
emperors pass laws that increasingly restrict
the exercise of traditional religion.

01:39:25.584 --> 01:39:28.814
Like, you can't perform animal
sacrifices, then you can't start doing

01:39:28.844 --> 01:39:32.794
these like tying ribbons to make
wishes or, like, all of these

01:39:32.804 --> 01:39:35.954
things, like going out to sacred
trees and doing this or that,

01:39:36.084 --> 01:39:40.004
because they say, "Oh, this is kind of
nefarious business," or, like, magic or

01:39:40.044 --> 01:39:43.944
whatever it is. And then they just
gradually start outlawing it more

01:39:43.984 --> 01:39:47.944
and more, putting restrictions on, like,
if you're not a Christian, you can't hold

01:39:47.984 --> 01:39:51.624
these high offices or you can't...
Your... There's problems with your wills.

01:39:52.084 --> 01:39:53.744
So they gradually do it like that.

01:39:54.624 --> 01:39:58.484
And this is how you... Yeah, this
is... And it works. It works.

01:39:58.784 --> 01:40:02.604
- What explains the success of
Christianity after Constantine?

01:40:02.684 --> 01:40:08.064
Why was it, as a technology, so successful
at spreading throughout the empire?

01:40:08.884 --> 01:40:12.324
- Christianity developed in a number of

01:40:12.924 --> 01:40:16.624
ways. So it acquired a certain
number of forms that were capable

01:40:16.764 --> 01:40:20.284
of appealing to different constituencies.

01:40:20.384 --> 01:40:25.284
In other words, there was
an intellectual side to it,

01:40:26.104 --> 01:40:28.964
The sort of theology, the almost

01:40:29.224 --> 01:40:33.104
quasi-philosophical or engagement
with philosophical schools that could

01:40:33.184 --> 01:40:37.224
draw in, let's say,
intellectuals. There is a,

01:40:38.064 --> 01:40:42.044
a public ceremony and ritual
aspect where you can organize

01:40:42.124 --> 01:40:45.824
communities and cities
to have processions or,

01:40:45.864 --> 01:40:49.764
like, have ho- all these festivals
that take the place of the ancient

01:40:49.804 --> 01:40:54.064
ones. You have a kind of

01:40:54.984 --> 01:40:58.764
not, it's not secretive, but it's
kind of this initiatory aspect

01:40:59.184 --> 01:41:02.924
where there's this baptism and
you learn a sort of creed,

01:41:03.124 --> 01:41:06.814
and you're initiated into the
religion with the prospect of a

01:41:06.864 --> 01:41:10.744
personal afterlife, right? And
that appeals to other kinds

01:41:10.764 --> 01:41:14.744
of people. There's also ways in which it

01:41:15.084 --> 01:41:18.384
it integrated itself into the
court and the language of power.

01:41:19.084 --> 01:41:22.844
Also in the army, right? Soldiers
now swear an oath to the

01:41:22.904 --> 01:41:26.544
Trinity, right? So it takes all
of these different forms that

01:41:26.604 --> 01:41:30.204
enable it to position itself, you know,

01:41:30.344 --> 01:41:34.084
here and there and, you know, in the
streets, in the court, in the armies,

01:41:34.624 --> 01:41:38.604
in the churches, in
texts, in books. And so

01:41:38.644 --> 01:41:43.964
it has this kind of manifold diversity,
right, that makes it very adaptable.

01:41:44.564 --> 01:41:46.314
- So one of the things you mentioned that

01:41:47.484 --> 01:41:51.144
Constantine did not anticipate,
did not realize that Christianity

01:41:51.224 --> 01:41:53.264
creates divisions between various groups.

01:41:53.424 --> 01:41:57.224
- So in part, this happens when you have,

01:41:57.644 --> 01:42:01.964
Religions that make exclusive claims,
right? Like, my beliefs are true-

01:42:02.024 --> 01:42:07.444
... and yours are by definition false.
Not, not just wrong, but false and

01:42:07.544 --> 01:42:10.874
even kinda evil. Like maybe- ...
Satan put them in your mind to-

01:42:10.874 --> 01:42:15.084
... lead you astray, right? And this
is inherently divisive. Like, it is.

01:42:15.944 --> 01:42:18.364
So there's this paradox where

01:42:19.504 --> 01:42:23.224
Christianity, in contrast to, say,
the ancient religions, is both

01:42:23.424 --> 01:42:30.244
far more polarizing but also far
more powerful as a unifying force

01:42:30.304 --> 01:42:34.104
at the same time, right? So
ancient religions tended not to

01:42:34.124 --> 01:42:38.064
produce this kind of conflict
or identities, right,

01:42:38.184 --> 01:42:41.804
or, or wars or these kinds of
things. And they could under certain

01:42:41.824 --> 01:42:44.924
circumstances, but for the
most part, they were not

01:42:45.544 --> 01:42:49.464
drivers of history in this kind of way.
But when you have exclusive claims, then

01:42:49.584 --> 01:42:52.704
suddenly these very communities
of, that are sort of

01:42:52.744 --> 01:42:57.074
consolidated and have this
very strong identity,

01:42:57.904 --> 01:43:02.314
But you also alienate other groups- ...
that you then are in conflict with.

01:43:03.144 --> 01:43:06.994
So this is why I for one
can't come down on whether,

01:43:07.364 --> 01:43:11.144
you know, Christianity is more of a
unifying force or a divisive force in the

01:43:11.184 --> 01:43:13.564
history of the Eastern Empire,
because it's, it's both.

01:43:14.364 --> 01:43:18.353
- And also trying to figure out
whether the unifying or the divisive

01:43:19.044 --> 01:43:21.464
aspects are a feature or a bug.

01:43:21.524 --> 01:43:25.124
Maybe some of the divisive
elements is a way for society

01:43:25.164 --> 01:43:30.744
internally to try to, much like the
civil wars, to try to figure itself out.

01:43:31.564 --> 01:43:31.574
- Yes.

01:43:31.604 --> 01:43:35.484
- So sometimes tension and conflict is a
good mechanism for figuring out what

01:43:35.524 --> 01:43:36.864
do the people want.

01:43:36.984 --> 01:43:38.814
- Or what's the truth, right?

01:43:38.853 --> 01:43:39.384
- Or what's the truth.

01:43:39.504 --> 01:43:43.414
- Yeah. So the story that it
likes to tell itself is that

01:43:43.424 --> 01:43:46.844
there's this, like, this
one original truth, and the

01:43:46.924 --> 01:43:50.923
hardcore of true believers is defending
that truth at every moment against

01:43:50.964 --> 01:43:52.874
all of these evil heretics
who are coming in-

01:43:52.874 --> 01:43:56.704
... and trying to corrupt it. In reality,
what happens is that this truth is

01:43:56.744 --> 01:44:00.744
something that's evolving in the
course of the controversies.

01:44:01.784 --> 01:44:05.444
And, like, often they don't
know that they believed

01:44:05.504 --> 01:44:09.284
that until in retrospect, once
they've had the fight and the winner

01:44:09.344 --> 01:44:13.284
has this position, oh, now that turns
out to have been the position we

01:44:13.344 --> 01:44:17.304
always held, right? And this happens again
and again and again. You know, a lot

01:44:17.364 --> 01:44:19.224
of the time, these Christian theologians

01:44:20.064 --> 01:44:23.664
who get into so much trouble and get branded
as heretics and sometimes get sent into

01:44:23.704 --> 01:44:26.504
exile, they didn't mean any harm.

01:44:27.374 --> 01:44:31.144
They often just were stating what
they thought everybody believed.

01:44:31.284 --> 01:44:34.794
And then when they blurt it out, someone is
like, off in Alexandria, is like, "What?

01:44:34.844 --> 01:44:38.764
That's heresy." And then now you're, now you're in
trouble. Now you're getting into this fight, and you

01:44:38.784 --> 01:44:42.580
might win, you might lose. But, like,
a lot of them were kind of sort of

01:44:42.620 --> 01:44:46.500
well-intentioned in that way, or they had
no intention of starting a fight. But

01:44:46.540 --> 01:44:48.260
there's always someone who
wants to start a fight.

01:44:49.760 --> 01:44:53.440
- Yeah, I mean, sometimes the
fights are extremely intense

01:44:53.560 --> 01:44:57.080
over things that I could see
on the surface or, like,

01:44:57.220 --> 01:45:00.880
iconography. It's like, it
seems like a very subtle-

01:45:00.980 --> 01:45:04.380
...debate, like almost academic. And then

01:45:04.840 --> 01:45:08.520
a large number of people don't
see it as academic. They,

01:45:09.060 --> 01:45:11.970
they do see it like the devil
put ideas in your head that are-

01:45:12.000 --> 01:45:16.900
...completely wrong, and it's, it's fascinating
how that kind of division can emerge.

01:45:17.000 --> 01:45:17.560
Uh, I mean, I—

01:45:18.380 --> 01:45:21.960
The impossible question, and I
apologize for asking it, but maybe just

01:45:22.100 --> 01:45:27.560
worthwhile to try to think about
it is, on the grand scale of

01:45:27.640 --> 01:45:30.960
centuries of the East
Roman Empire, is religion

01:45:32.240 --> 01:45:35.720
a constructive or a destructive force

01:45:36.260 --> 01:45:40.180
for the empire? Did it help it
flourish, or did it hold it back?

01:45:41.240 --> 01:45:44.940
- This society identified
itself increasingly

01:45:44.950 --> 01:45:49.430
with what it saw as orthodoxy. Orthodoxy
just means correct belief. I mean—

01:45:49.430 --> 01:45:52.470
...like every religion ultimately
thinks it's orthodox, right? That's—

01:45:53.400 --> 01:45:57.240
But that's the conventional name, right?
Orthodoxy today might be called Greek Orthodoxy.

01:45:57.340 --> 01:46:03.000
Um, and I mean, it's such an
essential part of the culture.

01:46:03.680 --> 01:46:07.630
It really is. I can't think of
the two of them inde... I mean,

01:46:07.700 --> 01:46:11.620
I try to because, as a historian,
I have to test the models,

01:46:11.820 --> 01:46:14.360
you know, and try to see these
things as independent of each other.

01:46:15.160 --> 01:46:18.720
But ultimately, it's very difficult to

01:46:18.740 --> 01:46:22.610
disentangle them, and I would
say that to the degree that

01:46:22.660 --> 01:46:25.160
this is a successful society historically,

01:46:26.040 --> 01:46:29.860
that its religion definitely contributed
to that and played a role in it.

01:46:29.960 --> 01:46:33.820
Not without cost, right?
There are, it mattered to

01:46:33.860 --> 01:46:38.560
them. They valued it, but things
that matter to you have a cost.

01:46:38.640 --> 01:46:42.740
And they paid that price. They were
willing to pay that price for it.

01:46:43.540 --> 01:46:49.080
For example, at the very end, they had to
choose between Catholicism, Western rule,

01:46:49.880 --> 01:46:53.520
where they essentially have to
compromise on their faith, or

01:46:54.000 --> 01:46:58.640
rule by Muslims, the Turks, where they
would not have to compromise their faith.

01:46:59.640 --> 01:47:03.040
And some of them were explicit that
they were preferring option B,

01:47:03.780 --> 01:47:09.659
because the Turks will at least respect
our identity. Like, that's a cost.

01:47:09.940 --> 01:47:12.920
- Yeah. But there's other
layers, like taxation and-

01:47:13.780 --> 01:47:15.400
...the, the functions of government—

01:47:15.560 --> 01:47:19.510
... that are connected to religion
to the degree it interacts with the

01:47:19.600 --> 01:47:23.240
tax system. But it feels
like that's the engine

01:47:23.700 --> 01:47:27.080
of the society and religion is
more like the cultural layer.

01:47:27.320 --> 01:47:31.040
- Yeah. So this is why I said that I try

01:47:31.440 --> 01:47:35.200
in thinking of the models
that we use to understand the

01:47:35.220 --> 01:47:38.540
society, not to assume that religion is

01:47:38.620 --> 01:47:42.380
everywhere and for everything.
Now, I have colleagues who do

01:47:42.400 --> 01:47:46.300
that, and I would disagree with them about
this, but you're exactly right. There are

01:47:46.380 --> 01:47:50.680
elements of this society that I
like to see as their own thing.

01:47:50.700 --> 01:47:55.240
Like the Roman identity, for example.
It's not the same as Orthodoxy.

01:47:56.040 --> 01:47:59.940
But also the operations
of the state. Those are

01:47:59.960 --> 01:48:03.480
very pragmatic things, and you see them

01:48:03.540 --> 01:48:06.800
intersect with religion
in, largely in areas of

01:48:06.840 --> 01:48:10.540
terminology or the vocabulary that
they use or, you know, like at the

01:48:10.600 --> 01:48:13.200
top, but not at their actual functioning.

01:48:14.060 --> 01:48:17.980
So in my field, I'm a
historian who's tried

01:48:18.060 --> 01:48:22.040
to promote other aspects
of the culture as having

01:48:22.080 --> 01:48:27.240
a kind of integrity of their own and not
to subsume them all within Orthodoxy.

01:48:28.020 --> 01:48:31.870
- So, I mean, again, an
impossible way of asking the

01:48:31.960 --> 01:48:37.000
same question. If you asked a
Roman, a million Romans across

01:48:38.220 --> 01:48:44.010
a thousand years, "Are you
a Roman or a Christian?"

01:48:44.770 --> 01:48:45.790
What would be the answer for that?

01:48:45.810 --> 01:48:47.620
- Oh, both. Oh, absolutely.

01:48:47.720 --> 01:48:49.720
- No, you don't get to say both.
You're not allowed to do that.

01:48:49.760 --> 01:48:50.240
- Why not? It's the-

01:48:50.280 --> 01:48:50.530
- Well, you're-

01:48:50.560 --> 01:48:51.520
- It's the true answer.

01:48:52.220 --> 01:48:55.020
- Okay. So you're saying
they're really tied together.

01:48:55.840 --> 01:48:59.319
- Well, they overlap. But if you were to...

01:48:59.800 --> 01:49:03.790
And this might be a somewhat more
subtle conversation than most of

01:49:03.800 --> 01:49:07.740
them would want to have, but if you were
to say, "Is Roman and Christian the

01:49:07.800 --> 01:49:11.430
same thing to you?" If they thought
about it for a little while,

01:49:11.500 --> 01:49:18.160
they'd quickly be able to say no. Because
there were, I mean, just logically, there

01:49:18.180 --> 01:49:20.080
were Christians who were not Romans.

01:49:20.660 --> 01:49:24.480
The Bulgarians or the Rus
or, you know, whoever.

01:49:24.660 --> 01:49:28.370
There were lots of Christians who were not
Roman, and they did not regard them as

01:49:28.400 --> 01:49:32.060
Roman just because they were Christian.
Conversely, they knew perfectly well

01:49:32.660 --> 01:49:36.220
that there had been Romans who were not
Christians, and they knew this how? Because in the

01:49:36.260 --> 01:49:39.680
churches like almost every
week, they celebrated

01:49:39.760 --> 01:49:43.000
martyrs who had been killed by
the Roman emperors in the past.

01:49:43.550 --> 01:49:47.340
And so it was, like, the
performance of violence by

01:49:47.360 --> 01:49:51.180
Roman emperors against Christians was
something they remember. They knew perfectly

01:49:51.220 --> 01:49:55.300
well. So those two things
did not overlap perfectly.

01:49:55.820 --> 01:49:59.660
And there were some contexts in which
you would be more Roman, and there were

01:49:59.700 --> 01:50:01.560
some contexts in which you
would be more Christian.

01:50:02.480 --> 01:50:06.330
And you find characters who, and I love
to do this. I find characters who,

01:50:07.540 --> 01:50:11.230
As some sources say we didn't pay
too much attention to Christian

01:50:11.300 --> 01:50:15.220
things. Like, they were just politicians.
They were just doing their work. And then

01:50:15.260 --> 01:50:19.000
you find characters who, like,
devote themselves. They go all

01:50:19.120 --> 01:50:23.030
in on Orthodoxy and, like, monasticism
and they just don't care about

01:50:23.060 --> 01:50:25.050
the Roman stuff at all.

01:50:25.050 --> 01:50:28.870
And that is, in fact, part of the reason
why I like this society, is because

01:50:28.920 --> 01:50:32.910
it has these kinds of options for people to choose.
And there's another one. There's the Greek stuff,

01:50:33.000 --> 01:50:36.980
too, because their language is Greek, their
literature is Greek, and so there are people in

01:50:37.000 --> 01:50:40.108
the society who go all in
on the Greek stuff. Right?

01:50:40.698 --> 01:50:44.488
And I see this society as
this kind of laboratory of

01:50:44.548 --> 01:50:47.928
these three elements coexisting
in these fascinating

01:50:47.988 --> 01:50:51.608
combinations. Usually it's
combinations, right? But

01:50:51.648 --> 01:50:55.628
sometimes you'll find people who are like,
kinda try to be purists in one way or

01:50:55.688 --> 01:50:59.658
another. And it's the only
society in history in

01:50:59.688 --> 01:51:03.768
which you can do this, 'cause it's the only
society that's Roman and Christian and Greek.

01:51:04.248 --> 01:51:05.388
But in different ways, right?

01:51:06.288 --> 01:51:10.048
- Yeah, unfortunately, I think it's tempting,
but it's probably impossible to say

01:51:10.448 --> 01:51:13.808
if we remove the taxation system,
would the, would Roman Empire

01:51:13.908 --> 01:51:17.848
be more or less successful? If we
removed religion, would it be more or

01:51:17.888 --> 01:51:18.628
less successful?

01:51:18.668 --> 01:51:18.778
- Right.

01:51:18.778 --> 01:51:23.128
- If we removed, uh,

01:51:24.088 --> 01:51:28.028
Greek and kept it Latin all the way through,
would it be more or less successful?

01:51:28.408 --> 01:51:32.028
It's probably impossible to do this
kind of analysis 'cause they're all so

01:51:32.748 --> 01:51:33.648
deeply integrated.

01:51:33.828 --> 01:51:38.748
- And fundamentally, it also wouldn't be what
it was. It would be something different.

01:51:39.168 --> 01:51:43.078
- But there is a big temptation, and this
is at the core of your work, and to

01:51:43.128 --> 01:51:47.808
understand why did the East Roman
Empire last as long as it did.

01:51:48.168 --> 01:51:51.068
And why did the broader Roman
Empire last as long as it did?

01:51:51.308 --> 01:51:51.388
- Yeah.

01:51:51.408 --> 01:51:57.368
- 'Cause it's, it is one of, if not
the most successful empires in terms

01:51:57.408 --> 01:52:02.068
of duration and stability in a
very dense part of the world.

01:52:02.248 --> 01:52:05.708
- That's actually like my next project.
I'm starting to write a book

01:52:06.308 --> 01:52:11.208
trying to explain just kind of
from an analytical standpoint why.

01:52:11.728 --> 01:52:12.988
- How did it last so long?

01:52:13.248 --> 01:52:13.408
- Yeah.

01:52:13.448 --> 01:52:15.227
- A lot of your work kinda hints at it.

01:52:15.548 --> 01:52:15.608
- Yeah.

01:52:15.618 --> 01:52:16.548
- It's here and there.

01:52:16.568 --> 01:52:21.248
But you're trying to do more, more
systematic. So, and we'll keep hinting at it.

01:52:21.388 --> 01:52:21.568
- Yes.

01:52:22.008 --> 01:52:25.828
- But to put a bow tie on
Constantinople, it went from a

01:52:25.968 --> 01:52:29.708
very low population of maybe 25,000 people

01:52:30.248 --> 01:52:37.128
to 500,000 people in just two centuries.
So can you explain how that happened?

01:52:37.908 --> 01:52:41.868
- Well, it didn't happen through
just demographic growth

01:52:41.888 --> 01:52:45.288
and reproduction in the city
itself. That rate of growth is

01:52:45.368 --> 01:52:49.368
impossible for an ancient city. So
when I say 20,000, 25,000, that's

01:52:50.227 --> 01:52:53.778
possibly what the ancient
city of Byzantium had-

01:52:53.988 --> 01:52:57.828
... when Constantine decided to found
Constantinople, and it grew to a city of a half a

01:52:57.868 --> 01:53:01.218
million in two centuries. That can
only have been done in one way,

01:53:02.228 --> 01:53:07.808
and that is immigration from the provinces.
So people must have been moving there,

01:53:08.768 --> 01:53:10.828
In large numbers,

01:53:12.868 --> 01:53:16.838
Which is a movement that we can't
see very clearly in the sources, but

01:53:16.868 --> 01:53:20.288
we have to infer it and
then try to explain it. So,

01:53:21.128 --> 01:53:24.797
Also there's another factor,
which is that ancient cities

01:53:25.068 --> 01:53:27.788
we now know or suspect are

01:53:28.808 --> 01:53:32.688
what some historians call death
traps. In other words, the density

01:53:32.728 --> 01:53:38.288
of disease is such that ancient cities
probably are losing something like

01:53:38.708 --> 01:53:42.368
1, 2, possibly 3% of their
population per year.

01:53:43.608 --> 01:53:49.017
So just in order to stay with a stable
population, they have to import people.

01:53:49.188 --> 01:53:53.628
Right? Now, they're not like 17th
century London. They're not that bad.

01:53:53.768 --> 01:53:56.528
- Do diseases and plagues
seem to be prevalent?

01:53:56.788 --> 01:54:00.638
- Oh, yeah. Now, you know, Roman
cities have some corrections

01:54:00.668 --> 01:54:04.568
for these sorts of things, like the way
they distribute the water through the city.

01:54:04.728 --> 01:54:08.218
Anyway, they, they weren't as
bad as they could've been,

01:54:08.768 --> 01:54:12.708
but there's that. So not only to
keep the population steady, but to

01:54:12.728 --> 01:54:16.568
expand it so dramatically means
that a lot of people are coming in

01:54:16.648 --> 01:54:20.588
from the provinces, mostly the
Greek-speaking provinces. So

01:54:20.648 --> 01:54:24.348
you know, Greece, Asia Minor, and
some of the major cities in the

01:54:24.428 --> 01:54:28.288
East that are Greek speaking.
And I start to wonder

01:54:28.348 --> 01:54:32.668
like, well, how did this happen? Like,
who are these people, for one thing?

01:54:33.548 --> 01:54:37.428
And then I did some simple calculations.
So I mentioned earlier that we

01:54:37.468 --> 01:54:39.857
have something like two and
a half thousand senators-

01:54:40.288 --> 01:54:43.448
... Who are required initially
to reside in Constantinople.

01:54:44.128 --> 01:54:46.648
Well, senators don't
live in bachelor pads.

01:54:47.728 --> 01:54:51.688
Senators have manners. They have
household staff, right? In Rome

01:54:51.708 --> 01:54:55.628
at the time, there's a calculation
that a senatorial household

01:54:55.688 --> 01:55:00.468
was something like 100 people,
right? Just servants, slaves,

01:55:01.647 --> 01:55:04.828
dancing girls, cooks,
barbers, whatever, right?

01:55:05.608 --> 01:55:09.538
So let's assume sort of conservatively
that in Constantinople it's

01:55:09.568 --> 01:55:13.408
only 30 people, which it might be
low, right? So if you do the math,

01:55:13.548 --> 01:55:17.698
you're starting to get something like,
I mean, closer to 100,000 people,

01:55:18.728 --> 01:55:21.968
right? And that's just
by bringing in senators.

01:55:22.348 --> 01:55:27.968
Right? They come with people.
So I think this was the nucleus

01:55:29.008 --> 01:55:32.568
of the population. Now then
Constantine also makes

01:55:32.608 --> 01:55:39.668
provision for possibly up to like 200,000
people to receive the grain dole, the

01:55:39.688 --> 01:55:43.648
bread. So that would've incentivized even

01:55:43.708 --> 01:55:46.818
more people to travel
there because there are-

01:55:46.818 --> 01:55:47.688
- So you get free bread.

01:55:47.888 --> 01:55:51.028
- Yes. And you can't live on that
alone, but it is, it's something.

01:55:51.128 --> 01:55:55.787
- Incentive. Is it true that he diverted
resources from Rome to Constantinople?

01:55:55.828 --> 01:55:59.048
- Absolutely. Oh, yeah. That
grain, that's coming from Egypt.

01:55:59.588 --> 01:56:05.528
So New Rome is literally stealing
food from the mouth of Old Rome.

01:56:05.588 --> 01:56:09.328
Now, Old Rome doesn't starve because
they, they divert other, like from North

01:56:09.428 --> 01:56:11.668
Africa and Sicily, you
can feed Rome, right?

01:56:11.688 --> 01:56:15.148
- But it sends a strong signal to
the people living in Old Rome

01:56:15.388 --> 01:56:17.467
that, long term, we should probably move.

01:56:18.328 --> 01:56:21.268
- Some people do move. So we know of
some senators who move from Rome.

01:56:22.588 --> 01:56:26.448
It sends a signal about the priorities of
the state, like they're investing much

01:56:26.488 --> 01:56:31.028
more in the East. And that the East
would be regarded as an equal parallel

01:56:31.328 --> 01:56:33.528
Roman, you know, world. Yeah.

01:56:33.828 --> 01:56:38.568
- As we talk about diverting
resources, slowly

01:56:39.408 --> 01:56:50.104
the West declines and collapses in 476
AD. So the Visigoths sack Rome in 410 AD,

01:56:51.184 --> 01:56:54.844
and in 476 AD, the last
Western emperor is deposed,

01:56:55.004 --> 01:56:58.784
marking the end of the
Western Roman Empire.

01:56:59.364 --> 01:57:03.164
High-level question: What is
the reason for that decline

01:57:03.324 --> 01:57:06.984
and the collapse of the
Western Roman Empire? So,

01:57:07.044 --> 01:57:10.864
nonstop civil wars, as we've
talked about, weak emperors.

01:57:11.684 --> 01:57:16.684
There's an economic money
crisis, so shrinking tax base,

01:57:17.604 --> 01:57:21.184
rising army costs. There was a loss of key

01:57:21.304 --> 01:57:26.544
provinces, especially in North Africa.
Reliance on contracted barbarian troops

01:57:27.424 --> 01:57:30.604
as they immigrated more and more into—

01:57:30.614 --> 01:57:33.964
...the Western Roman Empire.
Cascading invasions,

01:57:34.104 --> 01:57:42.044
migrations amplified by Hun pressure,
and then the East-West split. The richer

01:57:42.144 --> 01:57:47.564
East survives, the West can't
stabilize under— ...that split.

01:57:48.374 --> 01:57:52.344
- Yeah. The crux of the matter is that
barbarian armies, so armies from

01:57:52.384 --> 01:57:56.284
outside the empire, put
increasing pressure on it during

01:57:56.294 --> 01:57:59.914
the fifth century. And
for whatever reason,

01:57:59.914 --> 01:58:03.884
when the Roman state failed
to sort of suppress one of

01:58:03.924 --> 01:58:07.424
them and, say, settled them here
or allowed them to have here

01:58:07.504 --> 01:58:11.424
or couldn't stop them and they took over
a province, like the Vandals did in

01:58:11.444 --> 01:58:17.004
North Africa— ...this created this kind
of vicious cycle because then the Roman

01:58:17.084 --> 01:58:20.964
state lost access to the resources
from those provinces, that

01:58:21.004 --> 01:58:23.584
is the taxes, and without those
resources, they couldn't,

01:58:24.424 --> 01:58:28.054
you know, maintain, mobilize,
pay for their armies.

01:58:28.384 --> 01:58:32.354
Then they had fewer armies to handle
the next wave of barbarians that

01:58:32.404 --> 01:58:36.304
came in. The previous barbarians who
settled kind of declared their kind

01:58:36.364 --> 01:58:40.184
of independence. They also could not be
put down, and so this created a vicious,

01:58:40.464 --> 01:58:42.204
cycle that just continued in that way.

01:58:43.004 --> 01:58:46.844
It's not rocket science, actually.
I mean, you can see it playing out.

01:58:47.364 --> 01:58:51.204
Yeah. Now, who these groups are,
where they came from, why did they

01:58:51.344 --> 01:58:54.064
cross, that, those are
different questions, right?

01:58:54.984 --> 01:58:58.804
But from the Roman standpoint, that's
how it was experienced. These are

01:58:58.904 --> 01:59:05.984
armies that can defeat a Roman field army-
right, in battle. And sometimes they do.

01:59:07.544 --> 01:59:11.533
And they then settle and take over
territories, and then you lose the revenues,

01:59:11.584 --> 01:59:15.084
and so you can't recruit your own armies.
And so, anyway, that's the kind of

01:59:15.104 --> 01:59:17.484
cycle. The East tried to help.

01:59:18.724 --> 01:59:22.684
Occasionally, they would send forces, but they
were also subject to some of the same pressures.

01:59:23.174 --> 01:59:26.964
Because remember, the Goths
cross the Danube for the first

01:59:27.004 --> 01:59:30.704
time in a major way in 376.
Then you have the Battle of

01:59:30.724 --> 01:59:34.684
Adrianople a couple years later, where,
like, one and a half field armies is just

01:59:34.744 --> 01:59:38.604
annihilated, and the Emperor Valens dies,
and the Goths are just, like, kind of loose

01:59:38.744 --> 01:59:44.454
in the Balkans. And there was then
a long war with them, four years.

01:59:44.564 --> 01:59:48.504
It results in a kind of
truce where neither side

01:59:48.584 --> 01:59:52.144
wins, and the Romans, for the
first time, accept the presence of

01:59:52.204 --> 01:59:56.324
this quasi-independent Gothic army
in the territory of the empire.

01:59:57.204 --> 02:00:01.074
This is unprecedented, as I
said, and it creates a lot of

02:00:01.124 --> 02:00:05.084
tensions and dysfunctions.
Okay, so why does

02:00:05.144 --> 02:00:08.304
the East survive and the
West does not, right?

02:00:08.344 --> 02:00:11.494
There's... And so the-- Lots of reasons
that we can give here, but one of them

02:00:12.664 --> 02:00:15.684
is the geography that we were talking
about earlier. In other words,

02:00:16.604 --> 02:00:20.424
the, without a fleet, which they
don't have, the Goths can't cross

02:00:20.524 --> 02:00:27.164
over from Thrace or the western Balkans
to Asia Minor and go plunder some of the

02:00:27.224 --> 02:00:31.204
more prosperous provinces. So
they're stuck in the Balkans.

02:00:31.244 --> 02:00:35.184
They're gradually pushed kind of in toward the
western Balkans, which is, like, the worst

02:00:35.284 --> 02:00:37.684
part you, you know, at the
time, like, you wanna be in.

02:00:38.604 --> 02:00:42.844
And eventually, they just decide, "Well,
you know, it's kinda nicer in Naples."

02:00:44.124 --> 02:00:45.504
And so they go to Italy, right?

02:00:46.324 --> 02:00:49.364
Just because there's just a lot
more resources there for them.

02:00:50.124 --> 02:00:53.804
And that's one way that the
East just kind of manages to...

02:00:54.384 --> 02:00:56.064
It doesn't do this deliberately, but it,

02:00:56.884 --> 02:01:00.484
the geography kind of pushes
these invaders to the West.

02:01:00.883 --> 02:01:06.004
- So that's one. So geography is, some of
it's sort of the luck of geography and-

02:01:06.684 --> 02:01:09.564
... both of the invaders and
the geography of the empire.

02:01:09.744 --> 02:01:10.184
- Yeah.

02:01:10.344 --> 02:01:15.384
- But, you know, the East had
a lot of invaders since-

02:01:15.804 --> 02:01:19.844
... and was able to still barely at times-

02:01:19.964 --> 02:01:23.884
... survive the invaders, so... And
some of that could be luck. Some of it

02:01:24.124 --> 02:01:27.884
could be about the nature of
the invaders and the, the

02:01:27.924 --> 02:01:30.244
effectiveness of their military,
all that kind of stuff.

02:01:30.824 --> 02:01:34.704
- By the way, it worked in the other direction, too.
So if you have, like, Persians or Arabs coming

02:01:34.744 --> 02:01:36.264
into Asia Minor from the East,

02:01:37.244 --> 02:01:40.064
they usually can't cross over
into your Balkan provinces.

02:01:40.504 --> 02:01:40.614
- Mm-hmm. Right.

02:01:40.644 --> 02:01:44.154
- So you can fall back on one
side or the other side.

02:01:44.164 --> 02:01:48.114
They... If you fortified Constantinople
so that it's an impregnable bunker,

02:01:48.724 --> 02:01:52.454
which it was, right? So you're
holding your command center in

02:01:52.464 --> 02:01:56.404
Constantinople. You can alternate
between your European or your Asian

02:01:56.484 --> 02:02:00.064
provinces, depending on where the trouble is.
You can call in reinforcements from either

02:02:00.104 --> 02:02:04.024
side. So the East does have that kind
of advantage. This is not the reason

02:02:04.094 --> 02:02:07.864
why it survives for as long as it does,
though it is a reason. You know, also,

02:02:08.264 --> 02:02:12.034
they acquire flamethrowers at some
point, which- ... those help, too.

02:02:12.304 --> 02:02:16.264
Um, right? Ultimately, I think it's
the decision made by local communities

02:02:16.304 --> 02:02:19.804
to stick with the Roman state,
like, ultimately. Like, they're

02:02:19.864 --> 02:02:24.064
not going to actively side with invaders.

02:02:25.124 --> 02:02:28.944
And when the trouble passes, they
restore ties with Constantinople

02:02:28.984 --> 02:02:31.804
immediately. Like, this is
their natural political home.

02:02:32.684 --> 02:02:36.484
And, and that's the question that I'm really
trying to answer, like, why does that happen?

02:02:36.964 --> 02:02:40.864
- You know, we should say, just like we've
articulated multiple times, that it, the

02:02:40.904 --> 02:02:42.344
Roman Empire survives-

02:02:43.812 --> 02:02:49.192
So it's not like the Roman Empire collapsed
and another Byzantine Empire was born.

02:02:49.312 --> 02:02:53.132
Really, there is a shift that
happens, and part of that

02:02:53.172 --> 02:02:54.952
shift is because of Constantine,

02:02:55.872 --> 02:02:59.411
right? It's not just about where
the capital is, but I'm sure that

02:02:59.472 --> 02:03:04.692
there's just a general move towards that
direction from the West to the East.

02:03:05.172 --> 02:03:05.402
- Yeah, yeah.

02:03:05.432 --> 02:03:11.822
- And, and that in many ways, you know, weak
emperors and the West, the weak leaders,

02:03:12.892 --> 02:03:16.761
The structure of government, all
these kinds of elements put together-

02:03:16.872 --> 02:03:20.272
... maybe demographic shifts
and declines that have to do

02:03:20.412 --> 02:03:24.092
with the fact that the center
of the empire has moved.

02:03:24.732 --> 02:03:25.132
- That's right.

02:03:25.592 --> 02:03:30.892
- And so ultimately- ... it's not that
the West Roman Empire collapsed, it is

02:03:30.932 --> 02:03:34.792
that the center of the
Roman Empire shifted.

02:03:34.842 --> 02:03:38.112
And because of that, the
historic West collapsed.

02:03:38.432 --> 02:03:46.432
- It's quite striking. So for example, already
by, like in the 430s, Constantinople is

02:03:46.472 --> 02:03:50.392
basically codifying Roman
law for the West. So Roman

02:03:50.472 --> 02:03:54.152
law in Latin is codified in
Constantinople, and then sent

02:03:54.232 --> 02:03:56.192
to the West as, "Oh,
here's your law code."

02:03:57.012 --> 02:04:00.712
And this is in the 430s, so after the
alleged division between the two, which

02:04:00.952 --> 02:04:04.682
like I said, is kind of loose.
It's not hard and fast. In the

02:04:04.812 --> 02:04:10.232
6th century, it is the East that reconquers
part of the West under Justinian.

02:04:10.432 --> 02:04:10.832
- Mm-hmm.

02:04:10.892 --> 02:04:14.732
- And not only that, he also recodifies
Roman law on a much bigger

02:04:14.792 --> 02:04:18.452
scale, and then that law becomes Western

02:04:18.552 --> 02:04:22.432
law. So in a certain sense,
Roman law as we know

02:04:22.492 --> 02:04:26.252
it comes from Constantinople. It
doesn't come from ancient Rome. I mean,

02:04:26.412 --> 02:04:29.851
ultimately it comes from ancient Rome, but
we don't have those versions of it. We have

02:04:30.352 --> 02:04:34.092
the East Roman versions of it. It is East

02:04:34.152 --> 02:04:37.812
Rome that reconquers Rome. This
is a funny inversion, you know,

02:04:37.872 --> 02:04:41.772
because Constantinople is situated in
a province, Thrace, which always was

02:04:41.812 --> 02:04:42.952
sort of considered backwards,

02:04:43.792 --> 02:04:47.672
right? In the time of, like, the early
Caesars, if you were in Rome and you

02:04:47.692 --> 02:04:51.592
thought, you know, Thrace, it was like, "Ugh."
It's like, you know, some sort of, yeah,

02:04:51.812 --> 02:04:55.802
armpit of the Roman Empire or something,
you know? But by Justinian's time,

02:04:55.922 --> 02:04:59.221
it's complete inversion. Like, the capital
of the Roman world, the heart of it

02:04:59.752 --> 02:05:04.972
is there, and Rome is this kind of
backwater provincial city in Italy,

02:05:05.792 --> 02:05:09.732
you know, that you've just liberated from the Goths,
and it's kind of in ruins. There are wolves roaming the

02:05:09.772 --> 02:05:13.712
streets of the Forum. So this
is a complete, you know,

02:05:13.832 --> 02:05:17.472
overhaul of the centers of power.
It's turned inside out almost.

02:05:18.112 --> 02:05:21.092
- And I think it's fair to say
that the reason the East...

02:05:22.392 --> 02:05:26.292
Part of the reason the East lasted as
long as it did is the topic that we've

02:05:26.352 --> 02:05:30.252
mentioned, which is the structure of
government. So can we just zoom out once again

02:05:30.312 --> 02:05:34.441
and explain the key ways the government
functioned in the East Roman Empire,

02:05:35.292 --> 02:05:37.932
and how it evolved over the
lifetime of the empire?

02:05:38.712 --> 02:05:42.102
- Very broadly speaking, there's
civilian and military,

02:05:42.852 --> 02:05:46.752
right? And you might actually add the
church. It's entirely plausible to treat the

02:05:46.792 --> 02:05:50.752
church as a kind of government
institution at this time.

02:05:51.172 --> 02:05:55.092
But let's just stick with
military and civilian.

02:05:55.212 --> 02:05:59.132
the military is pretty straightforward,
would be recognizable to any student

02:05:59.152 --> 02:06:03.492
of military history. This is how
you recruit, organize, equip,

02:06:04.452 --> 02:06:12.152
pay, and lead soldiers. And the
East Roman state tends to have a

02:06:12.372 --> 02:06:14.952
larger military, at least paper strength.

02:06:15.752 --> 02:06:19.561
Active is a different matter. Like, how many soldiers
you take on a campaign is a different matter,

02:06:19.992 --> 02:06:23.952
but how many soldiers you maintain, like,
in the provinces generally, right, is a...

02:06:24.632 --> 02:06:32.432
It tends to be on the large side for a
medieval society, right? So it compares

02:06:32.712 --> 02:06:36.602
favorably to, say, the Caliphate
later on, which is a much

02:06:36.602 --> 02:06:44.392
more massive territorial entity. So the
military is that. It can have anywhere

02:06:44.412 --> 02:06:52.592
between 100,000 at a minimum, at a low
point, up to maybe about 250,000 at a high

02:06:52.652 --> 02:06:56.332
point, depending on the period. It's
a lot of people. It's a lot of men.

02:06:57.372 --> 02:07:00.892
Factor in their families, right?
These are also, like, part of the

02:07:00.932 --> 02:07:05.052
whole, you know, military
economic complex, if you will.

02:07:05.471 --> 02:07:08.272
- And they're career military,
so, like, this is their job.

02:07:08.392 --> 02:07:09.122
- Yep, yes.

02:07:09.172 --> 02:07:13.112
- And is the military for most of
the history of the East Roman

02:07:13.152 --> 02:07:14.832
Empire defensive military?

02:07:16.152 --> 02:07:18.172
- Mostly, but not always.

02:07:18.292 --> 02:07:19.872
- Yeah. And we'll talk about Justinian.

02:07:20.172 --> 02:07:21.152
- Sure.

02:07:21.252 --> 02:07:24.992
Um, and so then you have the civilian administration.
Civilian administration does a number of

02:07:25.012 --> 02:07:29.952
things. Principally, it is to find
the funds to pay for this army,

02:07:30.832 --> 02:07:34.552
which is the single largest
expense on the state budget,

02:07:34.752 --> 02:07:37.932
right? And so in order to
find those funds, it has

02:07:37.992 --> 02:07:41.952
to have census of the assets, and it has

02:07:41.992 --> 02:07:45.972
to be able to tax them, and there are
lots of different ways of doing that. So

02:07:46.172 --> 02:07:50.032
the civilian administration
has a number of tax bureaus,

02:07:51.092 --> 02:07:55.072
records keeping this sort of
thing, also a legal branch for

02:07:55.132 --> 02:07:58.972
resolving disputes with the imperial
fisc. Okay. But the civilian

02:07:59.012 --> 02:08:02.592
administration does a number of other
things, too. For example, the whole legal

02:08:02.632 --> 02:08:08.262
regulation of the, of the empire, the
courts, judges, courts of appeal,

02:08:09.202 --> 02:08:13.152
Or also issuing laws,
keeping records, all,

02:08:13.212 --> 02:08:17.112
all of this. And those
are the main bureaus that

02:08:17.172 --> 02:08:20.772
have to do with the
subjects of the empire.

02:08:21.232 --> 02:08:25.552
The emperors obviously maintain bureaus
that are for things like diplomacy,

02:08:26.392 --> 02:08:28.292
right, or running the palace staff,

02:08:29.252 --> 02:08:32.132
Because the palace is a huge
institution, right, with...

02:08:33.322 --> 02:08:37.252
And then there are a number of
endowments that, you know, major

02:08:37.272 --> 02:08:41.092
churches, Hagia Sophia, for example,
has hundreds of staff, clergy to, you

02:08:41.132 --> 02:08:44.592
know, readers to whatever, and so
they need to be paid, and so you need

02:08:44.632 --> 02:08:48.111
endowments. The imperial household,
it has expenses, so it needs

02:08:48.152 --> 02:08:51.892
endowments, right? So there's
a lot of land that's earmarked

02:08:52.544 --> 02:08:56.264
For these kinds of expenses, that
requires administration. So,

02:08:56.344 --> 02:08:58.764
this multiplies, right? I mean,
go on and on and on and on.

02:08:58.864 --> 02:09:03.784
- And I'm sure the tax code is
not a simple flat tax. It's...

02:09:03.834 --> 02:09:07.664
... probably incredibly complicated. So
it's just like in the United States,

02:09:08.944 --> 02:09:12.884
it feels like the majority of the United
States is basically lawyers and the IRS.

02:09:14.884 --> 02:09:18.504
That's maybe 98%, I think, is lawyers.

02:09:18.604 --> 02:09:18.724
- Lawyers.

02:09:18.764 --> 02:09:20.294
- I'm not sure it's scientifically-

02:09:20.314 --> 02:09:24.184
- I thought they shrunk the IRS down now to a
size that it can't, like, actually do anything.

02:09:24.723 --> 02:09:25.584
- They shrunk it down...

02:09:25.784 --> 02:09:26.384
- I thought it was just...

02:09:26.434 --> 02:09:27.424
- ... to just 90% now.

02:09:27.434 --> 02:09:28.114
- 90, just 90.

02:09:29.524 --> 02:09:33.964
- No. I think there is
something—this is another,

02:09:34.324 --> 02:09:38.004
Conversation about human nature
and about the, the nature of

02:09:38.084 --> 02:09:39.704
governments, but there's something about,

02:09:40.864 --> 02:09:45.744
like I think it's impossible to have an
IRS-type organization that doesn't grow.

02:09:47.184 --> 02:09:53.373
I think maybe with good intentions
because you can't— You have to, like...

02:09:53.584 --> 02:09:57.404
... everybody always comes to you,
"Well, I don't... Here's my special

02:09:57.523 --> 02:09:59.984
case. I want my tax to be lower."

02:10:01.184 --> 02:10:04.454
And they kind of add another
line. "All right, if you have...

02:10:04.454 --> 02:10:06.704
... purple hair, you..."

02:10:06.724 --> 02:10:11.444
... the tax decrease. And so you keep adding,
and then of course, the more you add,

02:10:12.464 --> 02:10:16.204
the more opaque the thing becomes,
therefore corruption seeps in

02:10:16.344 --> 02:10:19.924
or co- you know, maybe not like
official corruption, but...

02:10:20.004 --> 02:10:23.884
... corruption light, and
then that tax code grows, and

02:10:23.924 --> 02:10:26.574
then all of a sudden you have
these big institutions that then-

02:10:26.594 --> 02:10:30.304
... encourage corruption, and then
there's a bureaucracy, and there's a

02:10:30.344 --> 02:10:32.664
momentum, and this is just how humans are.

02:10:32.744 --> 02:10:37.484
- Yes. So this happens in East Roman society
too. I'll give you some examples. So,

02:10:38.964 --> 02:10:42.904
there's not a tax code as such,
but what you-- The way it

02:10:43.004 --> 02:10:45.244
operates is through basically exemptions.

02:10:46.294 --> 02:10:50.244
So you petition for an
exemption. You might be

02:10:50.304 --> 02:10:54.224
a monastery, you might be a wealthy la- You
might be someone well-connected to the court.

02:10:54.284 --> 02:10:58.184
You might be a struggling provincial
village, and you petition the emperor or

02:10:58.304 --> 02:11:02.183
some official, and you say, "Hey, we know we
had a bad season," or, "The barbarians came

02:11:02.244 --> 02:11:05.824
through and they took all of our... We can't
pay the taxes. Could we have an exemption?"

02:11:06.884 --> 02:11:10.744
And emperors often are granting
these exemptions for very

02:11:10.844 --> 02:11:14.404
specific things, like maybe for this
year or for that tax or whatever.

02:11:15.004 --> 02:11:18.904
The problem is that the emperors are discovering
every once in a while that their officials are,

02:11:18.984 --> 02:11:22.913
are granting these exemptions sort of on their
own. So every once in a while, the emperors have

02:11:22.944 --> 02:11:26.204
to, like, clear house
when they have to, like,

02:11:26.584 --> 02:11:30.364
cancel all of these exemptions and
start the whole process again. But,

02:11:30.744 --> 02:11:34.344
later on, when-- once we start to have
documentation, like maybe in the 11th century,

02:11:34.924 --> 02:11:38.794
we see that every little, well, not every,

02:11:38.864 --> 02:11:42.554
but we have all these monasteries, these little
villages, these high officials, and they all have these

02:11:42.564 --> 02:11:46.164
documents that give them exemption from this
or that or the other thing, and it gets

02:11:46.204 --> 02:11:48.624
so complicated and that's how it works.

02:11:49.784 --> 02:11:53.664
- Uh, but it is the engine of society that
makes the whole thing work 'cause you

02:11:53.704 --> 02:11:54.444
have to fund--

02:11:55.284 --> 02:11:59.004
I mean, there's infrastructure projects,
but you have to also fund the army, and the

02:11:59.064 --> 02:12:03.224
army's necessary to defend against
all the military incursions.

02:12:03.664 --> 02:12:07.644
A good fraction of the bureaucracy
seemed to have been eunuchs,

02:12:07.824 --> 02:12:11.344
which are castrated men. Can you
explain why this was a prominent thing?

02:12:11.984 --> 02:12:15.284
- The eunuchs are part of the
household staff of the emperor.

02:12:16.684 --> 02:12:20.664
So that would be like, what would it be? The West
Wing of the White House or something like this.

02:12:21.104 --> 02:12:25.124
So they are the people who
handle the imperial person,

02:12:25.924 --> 02:12:29.224
the bedchamber, the
organization of palace life,

02:12:29.784 --> 02:12:33.924
things like banquets, you know,
these kinds of things, the wardrobe.

02:12:34.724 --> 02:12:38.364
And why are they important? So
for starters, if you're, like,

02:12:38.824 --> 02:12:42.744
physically with the emperor
all day, right? Like,

02:12:42.804 --> 02:12:46.764
you're handling the meetings, you're... Right?
People can come to you and say, "Hey, I need

02:12:46.784 --> 02:12:50.604
you to put in a good word for
whatever," right? So they can

02:12:50.644 --> 02:12:54.564
get things done. So you bribe them,
they get things done. So they're

02:12:54.604 --> 02:12:57.924
very useful in this way. They're
also kind of hated for that reason.

02:12:57.994 --> 02:13:01.884
Right? But they're also kind of there
to be hated. In other words, they

02:13:02.064 --> 02:13:06.044
soak up a lot of the frustration
that people sometimes feel when

02:13:06.064 --> 02:13:10.304
they're not getting, you know,
what they want from the court.

02:13:10.644 --> 02:13:13.904
Okay. That's one thing. Here's the
other thing that's more interesting.

02:13:15.764 --> 02:13:19.704
How do you as an emperor make sure
that your bureaucracy doesn't displace

02:13:19.824 --> 02:13:23.504
you? Like, if the bureaucracy is handling
all the matters of running the empire,

02:13:23.964 --> 02:13:29.604
what do we need you for? Right? Like, the
bureaucracy can develop rules of its own-

02:13:29.664 --> 02:13:33.464
... for solving all the
problems for dealing with

02:13:33.484 --> 02:13:36.724
petitions and exemptions and
whatever. Like, they can do it. So

02:13:37.224 --> 02:13:41.104
where's your power exactly? So what
the emperors did not want is to

02:13:41.144 --> 02:13:44.764
be displaced or overshadowed
by these kinds of more

02:13:44.784 --> 02:13:48.064
impersonal institutions. And so
they would often set up, like,

02:13:48.844 --> 02:13:51.944
So this could be a bit confusing.

02:13:52.984 --> 02:13:56.744
So eunuchs were perfect for
this reason because often

02:13:56.984 --> 02:14:00.784
their origin was from outside the
empire, or they were former slaves. They

02:14:00.824 --> 02:14:03.964
weren't connected to, like,
networks of powerful families.

02:14:04.064 --> 02:14:07.694
So you knew that they would generally
be loyal to you because they

02:14:07.724 --> 02:14:11.694
depended entirely on you, the emperor,
for their position and their power.

02:14:12.324 --> 02:14:16.304
And what you would sometimes do is you'd
say, "Okay, I'm putting you in charge of,

02:14:16.324 --> 02:14:19.654
like, this army." Literally, like
putting you in charge of an army,

02:14:20.364 --> 02:14:23.644
just so that you can
counterbalance the kind of

02:14:24.124 --> 02:14:28.084
networks of established generals,
and you'll have, like, a eunuch

02:14:28.094 --> 02:14:31.954
from my wardrobe. You know, I'm
putting him in charge. And so this

02:14:32.004 --> 02:14:35.944
kind of shook things up a little bit
so that people who were part of a

02:14:35.984 --> 02:14:39.964
system or a network could never fully
count that that could get them all

02:14:39.984 --> 02:14:43.854
the power that they wanted. They now have to answer
to this eunuch from the wardrobe who's, like,

02:14:43.924 --> 02:14:47.324
outside of their system. And sometimes
these eunuchs were extremely

02:14:47.384 --> 02:14:50.984
competent like Narses,
Justinian's general, who

02:14:51.024 --> 02:14:54.684
defeated the Goths in Italy in this
massive battle. Like, this guy was a total

02:14:54.724 --> 02:14:58.644
hardass. And he was this little old man.
He was very old, and he was tiny, and he

02:14:58.684 --> 02:15:04.364
was a eunuch, and the Goths laughed at
him, but he had the last laugh, right?

02:15:04.404 --> 02:15:08.336
- Is there some component to them
being eunuchs, so they can't

02:15:08.376 --> 02:15:09.736
propagate the bloodline?

02:15:09.796 --> 02:15:13.686
- Yeah. They can't have their own family, so
they can't be, like, looking out for their own

02:15:13.776 --> 02:15:20.676
offspring. They're kind of isolated
individuals who depend entirely on your favor.

02:15:21.116 --> 02:15:26.116
- Is it known whether the castration
is almost always by force?

02:15:26.606 --> 02:15:30.436
- There are eunuchs in society generally.
They're often bishops. They're appointed

02:15:30.496 --> 02:15:32.606
Patriarch of Constantinople
sometimes. They're-

02:15:32.676 --> 02:15:36.436
... they're in all kinds of
positions. Many of them are

02:15:36.496 --> 02:15:41.776
children who are enslaved and
castrated against their will.

02:15:41.816 --> 02:15:46.346
Sometimes, however, they are castrated very
much according to the will of their families.

02:15:46.596 --> 02:15:50.226
Um, in some parts of, like in

02:15:50.296 --> 02:15:53.565
Caucasia, there were some regions that
were famous for producing eunuchs,

02:15:54.216 --> 02:15:55.936
also in, in Persia and so forth.

02:15:56.966 --> 02:16:00.336
But also, we are pretty sure that
this happened within the empire,

02:16:00.876 --> 02:16:04.356
because there were some families that, like,
really wanted to place a eunuch at the court.

02:16:04.776 --> 02:16:07.956
Um, so from Paphlagonia, there
were a number of... This is in

02:16:07.976 --> 02:16:15.006
northern Asia Minor. And so they would...
It was almost like a family strategy.

02:16:15.756 --> 02:16:18.336
- I mean, it's fascinating. It's
fascinating that they had so,

02:16:19.436 --> 02:16:24.856
So much representation
in the inner circles-

02:16:24.866 --> 02:16:28.216
... of the emperor, and
therefore had real influence.

02:16:28.336 --> 02:16:32.276
- Oh, yeah. But this was the case always,
even in Rome, like in the Julio-Claudians

02:16:32.336 --> 02:16:33.026
under-

02:16:33.026 --> 02:16:36.836
... you know, the first Caesars. There
are all these powerful eunuchs, and the,

02:16:37.756 --> 02:16:41.316
the senatorial class always hates them. I
mean, it's just the s- it's the same dynamic.

02:16:42.176 --> 02:16:45.716
- Uh, one of the interesting things you've
said as an aside in one of the many

02:16:45.796 --> 02:16:51.196
podcasts that I listened with you is you
said that there were no isolated people,

02:16:52.816 --> 02:16:56.516
You know, people that are
disconnected from the empire,

02:16:57.776 --> 02:17:01.566
Maybe who, for example, don't know
about the taxes or just don't feel

02:17:01.616 --> 02:17:05.306
integrated into the system. I mean,
that's really interesting to me, that

02:17:06.176 --> 02:17:12.196
there's so much connectivity, there's so
much cohesion- ... as an entire peoples.

02:17:12.856 --> 02:17:16.476
- These people do not exist, these
isolated peasants. This is a

02:17:16.555 --> 02:17:20.505
myth that I, one day I'm going
to write a chapter about this

02:17:20.676 --> 02:17:24.386
because it's this idea that you occasionally
encounter, well, actually quite

02:17:24.436 --> 02:17:28.296
often in the scholarship, that there
are these sort of rural communities out

02:17:28.356 --> 02:17:32.106
there somewhere that don't
know what's going on in

02:17:32.196 --> 02:17:36.176
Constantinople. They might not know, even
know who the emperor is. They're cut

02:17:36.256 --> 02:17:40.196
off. Maybe a tax official
will show up every once in a

02:17:40.236 --> 02:17:43.886
while, maybe not, and they just
live their lives on their own,

02:17:43.956 --> 02:17:47.876
unaffected by the, say, state,
because the medieval state,

02:17:48.016 --> 02:17:51.196
we suspect, is you know, always

02:17:51.536 --> 02:17:55.276
powerless and can't, you know,
affect people's lives. There's

02:17:55.356 --> 02:17:59.156
no proof for these communities
at all. At most, you

02:17:59.316 --> 02:18:03.306
might try to find some,
like, actual hermits, like,

02:18:03.416 --> 02:18:08.636
actual Christian ascetic hermits who
try to go out and find this situation,

02:18:09.516 --> 02:18:13.176
and sometimes they're described in the
text as, like, oh, so, so-and-so went so

02:18:13.316 --> 02:18:17.236
far out into the mountains that,
like, not even the tax census people

02:18:17.516 --> 02:18:20.996
showed up there, which tells you how
they think about what it means to be

02:18:21.056 --> 02:18:24.916
isolated, right? So this is not
a... This is a state in which every

02:18:25.036 --> 02:18:28.656
arable, you know, piece of arable
land has been censused for

02:18:28.736 --> 02:18:32.376
centuries. It's not like you
can hide a village, right?

02:18:32.936 --> 02:18:36.896
And the, the taxation process
is not like, what, they visit

02:18:36.936 --> 02:18:40.736
once a year, give us some coin, and we'll
leave. It's actually more like three

02:18:40.776 --> 02:18:44.716
times a year. And the
taxes is not just coin and

02:18:45.096 --> 02:18:48.756
maybe a payment in kind or something, but
it's, it's a whole bunch of things like

02:18:48.816 --> 02:18:52.676
services and recruits and all...
You're right. And once you

02:18:52.776 --> 02:18:56.856
start adding all of these things
up, it creates a very dense,

02:18:57.736 --> 02:19:02.136
Institutional matrix in which
all communities are enmeshed.

02:19:02.176 --> 02:19:06.636
They can't get out of it. Also, they,
they have a church, don't they?

02:19:07.565 --> 02:19:11.336
And if they have a church, they have the calendar.
And of course they have the calendar because...

02:19:11.936 --> 02:19:15.816
So, like, how do they
organize time and space and

02:19:15.956 --> 02:19:19.616
boundaries and all of these things? No, this is all
state institutions. How do they pay for anything?

02:19:19.656 --> 02:19:23.276
They have coins. Coins are
everywhere. So I think

02:19:23.336 --> 02:19:27.096
that these institutions
structured the way that everyone,

02:19:27.356 --> 02:19:31.196
even in village communities, even in
the most isolated ones, supposedly,

02:19:31.756 --> 02:19:35.436
how they thought about things
like time and space and value and

02:19:35.496 --> 02:19:39.476
relations and power and
kinship and so forth.

02:19:39.856 --> 02:19:43.816
- So what you're saying is taxation is the
thing that brings the empire together.

02:19:44.696 --> 02:19:45.876
- It is, principally, yes.

02:19:46.416 --> 02:19:49.716
- I mean, it's- ... it's true, right?
This is, like, this is how you know.

02:19:50.096 --> 02:19:53.476
- Yeah. But on top of that is
layered things like the economy,

02:19:53.736 --> 02:19:55.956
coins, right? But also there's the church.

02:19:56.596 --> 02:19:59.056
- Yeah, and the church is
important, just like you said.

02:19:59.136 --> 02:20:00.936
Yeah. And there's churches
throughout the empire.

02:20:01.076 --> 02:20:04.616
- Yes, and they have sermons,
and they pray for the

02:20:04.676 --> 02:20:08.976
emperor after this service. No,
there are no isolated communities.

02:20:09.496 --> 02:20:13.056
- So one of the things I briefly
mentioned just would be nice to

02:20:13.976 --> 02:20:17.396
elaborate on is this term
of monarchic republic.

02:20:18.636 --> 02:20:24.856
So we've been throwing around words like
kingdom and republic and empire and,

02:20:25.736 --> 02:20:33.326
Monarchy. So what is the actual... What's
a good applicable term to what this

02:20:33.356 --> 02:20:35.316
thing is- ... the East Roman Empire?

02:20:35.656 --> 02:20:39.466
- That's an excellent question,
and I'm glad you flagged that

02:20:40.036 --> 02:20:43.066
because we call it conventionally Byzantine
Empire, and it's neither of those things

02:20:43.096 --> 02:20:46.236
really. We talked about Byzantine.

02:20:46.276 --> 02:20:52.216
Now, empire's a bit of a problem because
first of all, There's no term in Greek,

02:20:53.596 --> 02:20:58.036
In the Greek that they use at this period
that corresponds to our notion of empire.

02:20:59.096 --> 02:21:03.016
It's not part of the official terms. It's
not even... They didn't even have a term

02:21:03.056 --> 02:21:06.436
for it. You could have... There's some
terms that might mean something like state

02:21:07.276 --> 02:21:13.776
Arche maybe or kratos. But for the most
part, it's either basileia, which we might

02:21:13.836 --> 02:21:17.976
translate as monarchy or
politeia, which is polity.

02:21:18.896 --> 02:21:24.276
And politeia in Greek, polity, is a
Greek translation of Latin res publica.

02:21:24.616 --> 02:21:28.156
Res publica doesn't mean republic
the way we mean it for the Romans,

02:21:28.396 --> 02:21:32.206
like a non-monarchical regime, right? That's how
we mean, like, the American Republic or, you

02:21:32.256 --> 02:21:35.796
know. That's a usage that came
in later, like during the

02:21:35.816 --> 02:21:39.675
Enlightenment. In Latin,
a res publica is the

02:21:39.736 --> 02:21:43.456
common affairs, the common
interest of a people who are

02:21:43.496 --> 02:21:47.236
constituted as a political
community, regardless of the type of

02:21:47.246 --> 02:21:50.936
regime that they have. Like even
Cicero could imagine the Roman res

02:21:50.996 --> 02:21:54.356
publica governed by a king
or by a senate or by a

02:21:54.496 --> 02:21:58.325
democracy. And they continue to
use that term. We don't use it

02:21:58.356 --> 02:22:02.286
according to Roman norms. We use it according
to modern norms, the term republic.

02:22:03.456 --> 02:22:07.376
So they continue to call it a res
publica or a polity under the emperors

02:22:07.436 --> 02:22:11.155
as well, right? And it was
understood that the role of the

02:22:11.276 --> 02:22:14.976
emperor, whether he's Caesar or
basileus or whatever, whatever

02:22:15.056 --> 02:22:18.856
language, was to serve the
polity. They keep saying this.

02:22:19.536 --> 02:22:23.556
So the terms that occur in
the sources most commonly are

02:22:24.376 --> 02:22:28.316
basileia of the Romans, polity
of the Romans, or Romania,

02:22:28.496 --> 02:22:33.736
which is the proper name
of this state. Not empire.

02:22:33.896 --> 02:22:39.116
Now, empire. Empire in
modern English commonly,

02:22:39.856 --> 02:22:43.736
an empire is a state that's created
when one group conquers a bunch of

02:22:43.796 --> 02:22:47.696
others and rules them. It could be an ethnic
group. It could be an ethnoreligious group.

02:22:47.736 --> 02:22:51.486
It could be a political group, whatever.
But there's an act of conquest, and

02:22:51.596 --> 02:22:54.276
results in a state where one
group is ruling over others.

02:22:55.196 --> 02:22:59.176
That's not how Romania is actually constituted.
We've talked about this. It's, for

02:22:59.216 --> 02:23:02.956
the most part, all Roman
citizens ruling like Roman

02:23:03.036 --> 02:23:06.376
subjects ruling themselves,
through their own government.

02:23:07.296 --> 02:23:10.976
So it's not an empire strictly
speaking. Now, occasionally,

02:23:11.576 --> 02:23:15.396
they will conquer other people, right? We talked
about the warfare. Sometimes it's not just

02:23:15.416 --> 02:23:17.076
defensive. Sometimes
it's offensive, right?

02:23:17.956 --> 02:23:21.836
In that case, you do
establish a- an imperial

02:23:21.856 --> 02:23:25.736
relationship. Like we, the Romans, are
ruling over this other group. Could

02:23:25.776 --> 02:23:29.676
be Slavs, it could be Bulgarians for
a while, it could be whatever. Or,

02:23:29.776 --> 02:23:34.456
even some Muslims in northern Syria
for a while in the 11th century,

02:23:35.476 --> 02:23:36.736
who-- and you are not Romans.

02:23:37.936 --> 02:23:41.816
And that's an imperial relationship. The question
is, how many of these imperial relationships do

02:23:41.856 --> 02:23:45.736
you need to decide that, well,
we've reached a tipping point, and

02:23:45.776 --> 02:23:49.676
now we're just gonna call the whole
thing an empire? Personally, I don't

02:23:49.736 --> 02:23:53.676
think we ever reach that point.
I mean, all states, even today,

02:23:53.816 --> 02:23:55.116
have like minorities.

02:23:56.016 --> 02:23:59.856
Some of them are part of that state because
they were conquered once upon a time.

02:24:00.716 --> 02:24:05.416
But we don't call those states empires
necessarily. Even though... Like,

02:24:06.796 --> 02:24:10.336
look at the United Kingdom.
Well, Wales was conquered.

02:24:11.236 --> 02:24:14.476
And, you know, the Welsh have their
own identity, their own language.

02:24:15.556 --> 02:24:20.296
I don't know that you would call
that now an imperial relationship.

02:24:21.136 --> 02:24:22.576
Maybe. I don't know.

02:24:22.796 --> 02:24:26.776
- I think there's also a synonymous use
of the word empire that refers to

02:24:26.856 --> 02:24:29.476
the power that the state has-

02:24:29.556 --> 02:24:32.996
... in the global context
geopolitically. So sometimes

02:24:33.116 --> 02:24:39.206
empire is used synonymously with superpower,
meaning it's one of the primary-

02:24:39.206 --> 02:24:43.016
... nations in the world, and it
doesn't necessarily have to do with the

02:24:43.056 --> 02:24:46.416
imperial nature of its history.

02:24:47.076 --> 02:24:47.436
- That's true.

02:24:47.816 --> 02:24:50.676
- Hence the sort of American
empire, US empire.

02:24:50.836 --> 02:24:54.616
- Yes. Though you would never characterize
the American political regime as an

02:24:54.636 --> 02:25:01.016
imperial one insofar as it does not have
an emperor, for example. But anyway,

02:25:02.516 --> 02:25:06.256
yes. The problem is that in my
field, we use the term empire

02:25:06.336 --> 02:25:09.996
conventionally, even when
what you just described is

02:25:10.076 --> 02:25:13.956
clearly not happening, like even
toward the end. It's not a major world

02:25:14.016 --> 02:25:17.956
power. It, like, has a few islands in
the Peloponnese, and, but we call it

02:25:18.036 --> 02:25:21.676
empire and the emperor, and it's like, it's
completely ridiculous. There's not even a

02:25:21.756 --> 02:25:24.936
term in their language
for that sort of thing.

02:25:25.896 --> 02:25:29.676
anyway, we can call things whatever we want,
just so we understand what the reality

02:25:29.756 --> 02:25:33.596
is- ... and what we are
using those terms to mean.

02:25:33.756 --> 02:25:35.276
I think that's the important thing. Yeah.

02:25:35.616 --> 02:25:41.316
- So then let's look at words which are
both fascinating, monarchic republic.

02:25:41.716 --> 02:25:41.856
- Right.

02:25:42.236 --> 02:25:46.246
- Why is that a good term
for the East Roman Empire?

02:25:46.716 --> 02:25:50.696
- Uh, because they understood it very
much to be a polity in the Roman sense

02:25:50.736 --> 02:25:55.116
of a res publica that was governed
by a regime that was monarchical.

02:25:55.496 --> 02:25:59.396
- So those two elements, there's
an emperor dude at the top,

02:26:00.476 --> 02:26:03.976
and it functioned
politically like a republic.

02:26:04.456 --> 02:26:07.916
- Also, the emperor was expected
to be working for the republic.

02:26:08.676 --> 02:26:12.656
Like, they keep saying this. So,
like, this was their conception.

02:26:13.436 --> 02:26:18.336
You don't find it, for example, in
other kinds of dynastic empires,

02:26:19.216 --> 02:26:22.916
The ones that don't emerge from
within the context of an ancient

02:26:22.936 --> 02:26:26.496
republic. So this is another reason
why I find this civilization so

02:26:26.516 --> 02:26:30.176
fascinating, right? I mean, we mentioned the,
the Greek and the Roman and the Christian

02:26:30.276 --> 02:26:34.016
elements that are kind of jostling
together. This is fascinating to me in part

02:26:34.076 --> 02:26:37.776
because it's this weird
combination of monarchical

02:26:37.876 --> 02:26:44.296
power, like in terms of executive
institutions— ... and a republican kind of

02:26:44.776 --> 02:26:48.696
baseline ideology on which it
operates. Yeah, and they, they

02:26:48.776 --> 02:26:50.236
sometimes come to a head.

02:26:50.856 --> 02:26:53.696
- Is there at all a degree to which
it's a military dictatorship?

02:26:54.596 --> 02:26:58.156
Because especially when it's the
general in the emperor's seat,

02:26:58.796 --> 02:27:02.716
yes, there's a republic, yes, there's
political discussion, but the army has

02:27:02.776 --> 02:27:08.156
a lot of power. So to what degree is
it a military dictatorship, as is

02:27:08.216 --> 02:27:11.856
sometimes talked about when you
talk about the Roman Empire?

02:27:12.612 --> 02:27:16.012
- Yeah, so Augustus' position,
for example, and that of his

02:27:16.032 --> 02:27:19.972
successors is, is talked about as a
military dictatorship. In other words, when

02:27:20.012 --> 02:27:24.712
push comes to shove— ... and the
basis of political power is the army,

02:27:25.712 --> 02:27:29.112
then I suppose it's legitimate
for historians to talk

02:27:29.172 --> 02:27:33.072
about a military dictatorship.
But here's why I don't think

02:27:33.572 --> 02:27:37.072
the Eastern Roman Empire is a military
dictatorship. Even though, again,

02:27:37.672 --> 02:27:43.592
the emperors control the armies, and the
armies themselves will often have a say

02:27:44.372 --> 02:27:48.732
in who becomes emperor, like through
the civil wars that we mentioned.

02:27:49.412 --> 02:27:53.252
Okay. The reason why I don't think it's
a military dictatorship is because

02:27:54.212 --> 02:28:01.722
they almost never, very, very, very rarely
use the army as an instrument of social

02:28:01.812 --> 02:28:02.312
control.

02:28:03.252 --> 02:28:07.132
- Is that, isn't that strange to you?
Because you see that being done

02:28:07.912 --> 02:28:12.652
through so much of human history. And
the fact they don't resort to that,

02:28:13.472 --> 02:28:18.112
I mean, they, for 1,000 years,
that's just not a thing.

02:28:18.872 --> 02:28:22.612
- As a way of keeping down the
population, you just don't see it.

02:28:23.152 --> 02:28:26.332
And part of the reason for that is I don't
think the population needs to be kept down.

02:28:26.592 --> 02:28:30.552
Like, this gets back to the consensus that we were
talking about. The understanding is that the army

02:28:30.592 --> 02:28:33.732
is there to protect the Roman people.

02:28:34.202 --> 02:28:41.212
And is often recruited among them. And for
most of the period that I study, is like

02:28:41.292 --> 02:28:44.992
lives among them. So when the emperors have
to call up the army, they're literally

02:28:45.052 --> 02:28:47.932
calling up soldiers from local villages.

02:28:47.972 --> 02:28:50.872
- It's just incredible that this
worked. I guess the civil war thing

02:28:52.032 --> 02:28:55.932
is, as a mechanism, is effective.
'Cause you just, throughout human

02:28:55.952 --> 02:28:59.752
history, I mean, you look at even
recent history, it's just a very

02:28:59.812 --> 02:29:05.052
common thing for a authoritarian figure
to use the army to suppress people.

02:29:05.352 --> 02:29:09.292
- Yeah, but isn't that dangerous, though?
Look at how many modern regimes

02:29:09.332 --> 02:29:14.422
tried to use their own armies against their
people who are in a moment of rising up.

02:29:14.422 --> 02:29:14.952
- It doesn't last.

02:29:15.032 --> 02:29:19.352
- Well, it's a risk. Like the Arab Spring.

02:29:19.752 --> 02:29:24.332
Especially in Egypt. And you could,
you could tell for those three weeks

02:29:25.412 --> 02:29:29.222
that Mubarak was trying to
decide whether he could

02:29:29.312 --> 02:29:33.241
actually count on the army to
suppress the protesters or not,

02:29:33.932 --> 02:29:37.892
because you never know what
they're going to do if you ask

02:29:37.912 --> 02:29:43.932
them to fire on a civilian population.
It can backfire on you badly.

02:29:45.092 --> 02:29:49.032
So I think that is a very
dangerous force to use, and

02:29:49.112 --> 02:29:52.852
even in the context of modern regimes,
can result in a regime change.

02:29:53.492 --> 02:29:57.072
- Absolutely, and there's huge wisdom
behind that, but, you know, leaders are

02:29:57.112 --> 02:29:59.892
not always wise, often not wise.

02:29:59.901 --> 02:30:03.312
And often maybe they start out wise,
but power corrupts them over time,

02:30:03.352 --> 02:30:08.401
and so the fact that this does not happen
just over and over and over and over-

02:30:08.472 --> 02:30:11.992
... in the East Roman Empire is, is,
there's just a signal there that's

02:30:12.092 --> 02:30:16.192
fascinating. And I mean, this goes to
the book that you want to be working on-

02:30:16.632 --> 02:30:18.732
... About why the thing lasts. So.

02:30:19.072 --> 02:30:22.652
- There's one emperor who does
do that, and that's Justinian.

02:30:22.812 --> 02:30:24.312
- Mm-hmm. Yeah, he gets wild.

02:30:24.842 --> 02:30:24.972
- Right. Yeah.

02:30:25.052 --> 02:30:28.282
- So let's talk about Justinian. We have
to. We have to talk about Justinian.

02:30:28.372 --> 02:30:28.532
- Yes.

02:30:29.332 --> 02:30:32.092
- one of the most impactful
Roman emperors in history,

02:30:33.032 --> 02:30:37.432
started as a peasant, and rose
in power to become emperor.

02:30:38.252 --> 02:30:42.232
He fought wars of conquest and was
very consequential and impactful.

02:30:42.392 --> 02:30:42.832
- Yes.

02:30:42.872 --> 02:30:43.612
- So who was he?

02:30:44.172 --> 02:30:47.712
- All right. So Justinian was
the emperor from 527 to

02:30:48.052 --> 02:30:54.392
565, so quite a long reign. He was the
nephew of the previous emperor, Justin I,

02:30:55.672 --> 02:30:59.292
who was an older man, ruled for just
under a decade before Justinian.

02:30:59.912 --> 02:31:03.052
And both of them came from small, poor

02:31:03.752 --> 02:31:05.692
agricultural communities
in the western Balkans.

02:31:06.172 --> 02:31:11.392
- We should say that Justin I ended
up in your worst 10 emperors list.

02:31:11.752 --> 02:31:15.552
- Yeah, for one decision. He's not
the worst of the worst, but he,

02:31:15.692 --> 02:31:19.352
he made a very, very bad call when it
came to church policy, tore the church

02:31:19.392 --> 02:31:20.882
apart. He shouldn't have done that,

02:31:21.752 --> 02:31:25.632
in my view. But by the way, Justinian's
an immensely complicated figure.

02:31:25.772 --> 02:31:29.592
I found it impossible to decide, first of all,
whether to put him on the best emperors or the worst

02:31:29.632 --> 02:31:29.931
emperors.

02:31:30.332 --> 02:31:31.852
- Yeah, you, I mean, you're
being spicy. Yeah.

02:31:31.892 --> 02:31:34.772
- Yeah, yeah. You have to be
provocative about these things.

02:31:35.052 --> 02:31:38.932
And I thought omitting those two would
be that, and it, and it was. So,

02:31:39.052 --> 02:31:39.942
and here we are talking about it.

02:31:39.972 --> 02:31:42.252
- Yeah, yeah, exactly. The controversy.

02:31:42.332 --> 02:31:46.012
- And through all the systems of
social mobility that we've been

02:31:46.022 --> 02:31:49.232
talking about, Justin ended up emperor.

02:31:49.852 --> 02:31:53.632
because of his military background, he just rose through
the ranks. He was in the right place at the right

02:31:53.692 --> 02:31:57.432
time, became emperor, and then he
gradually positioned his nephew,

02:31:57.632 --> 02:32:01.472
Justinian, whose background we do not know.
Literally, we do not know anything that

02:32:01.492 --> 02:32:05.072
Justinian did before the age of something like
38 when he appears on the historical record.

02:32:06.032 --> 02:32:09.812
Same background. We know where he came
from, but we don't know what he was

02:32:09.852 --> 02:32:13.892
doing, although, like, was he an active
soldier for decades? We don't know.

02:32:15.312 --> 02:32:19.131
Probably not. He comes equipped with,

02:32:19.172 --> 02:32:22.672
like, a knowledge of something
like Roman law and some Christian

02:32:22.712 --> 02:32:25.072
theology. That seems to
be, like, what he knew.

02:32:26.032 --> 02:32:29.992
And then Justin positions
him to become his

02:32:30.012 --> 02:32:33.071
successor eventually, kind
of reluctantly, but he does.

02:32:33.752 --> 02:32:37.252
Justinian also marries
Theodora, who's a woman who's a

02:32:37.412 --> 02:32:40.732
former sex worker, which
is a controversial choice.

02:32:41.712 --> 02:32:45.772
By this point, he's a senator and is
holding all of these top generalships,

02:32:46.672 --> 02:32:47.772
and then he becomes emperor.

02:32:47.932 --> 02:32:49.592
- She was also very influential, yes?

02:32:50.032 --> 02:32:50.792
- Very powerful, yes.

02:32:51.012 --> 02:32:51.172
- Very powerful.

02:32:51.212 --> 02:32:56.372
- Under his, yeah, during his reign. So
the interesting thing about Justinian's

02:32:57.412 --> 02:33:01.072
choice of, let's say, associates,
and that includes his wife,

02:33:01.832 --> 02:33:06.422
is that he seems to have just gone for
people he, like, he thought were talented-

02:33:06.692 --> 02:33:10.642
... or that would be good for
him as a ruler, rather than

02:33:10.672 --> 02:33:14.452
their social class or prestige.
And so he accumulates

02:33:14.532 --> 02:33:21.960
around him quite a motley group of
odd, sometimes like these kinds of,

02:33:22.000 --> 02:33:28.540
disreputable people. But they did what he
wanted them to, and they were, they, with

02:33:28.640 --> 02:33:32.520
lasting consequences for world
history. So he has an eye for talent,

02:33:32.940 --> 02:33:36.680
and, and he doesn't hesitate to pick
people that others might look down

02:33:36.780 --> 02:33:39.600
on if he thought they
could get the job done.

02:33:39.660 --> 02:33:43.420
And these are some of the attributes that
enable him to be as successful as he

02:33:43.520 --> 02:33:46.520
was. So that's his background.

02:33:47.920 --> 02:33:50.600
He's a Latin speaker primarily,
but he knows Greek, too.

02:33:51.360 --> 02:33:55.340
- So here he is and he, but he had, so
like I mentioned, the wars of conquests.

02:33:55.440 --> 02:33:57.400
He also overhauled the Roman law.

02:33:58.180 --> 02:33:59.500
- He appoints a committee-

02:33:59.840 --> 02:34:05.840
... As one does- ... To just take the
whole of Roman law and condense it

02:34:05.940 --> 02:34:09.900
into what today we call the Corpus
Juris Civilis, which is the,

02:34:09.940 --> 02:34:14.800
the body of Roman civil law. And this
was a massive work of codification,

02:34:15.720 --> 02:34:19.499
And it is our main source for Roman

02:34:19.560 --> 02:34:23.080
law. Like overwhelmingly,
what we call Roman law

02:34:23.920 --> 02:34:27.640
is what Justinian's committee, and
specifically this character called Tribonian,

02:34:28.080 --> 02:34:31.180
who was a very accomplished
jurist said it was.

02:34:31.480 --> 02:34:34.660
- Mm-hmm. And that, did that persist
through time? Did that last?

02:34:34.770 --> 02:34:38.350
- Yes, still to this day. When you
study Roman law, you're studying

02:34:39.140 --> 02:34:40.040
Tribonian's committee.

02:34:40.960 --> 02:34:45.570
- And so in terms of our modern society,
how much of impact did that have,

02:34:46.640 --> 02:34:51.190
this codification, this stable law
that ran the East Roman Empire?

02:34:51.500 --> 02:34:53.900
- Well, I mean, Roman legal concepts pervade

02:34:54.900 --> 02:34:58.880
everything from philosophy to political
thought to actual Roman, uh, legal

02:34:58.920 --> 02:35:02.580
practice. I mean, depends on what country you're
in. So in many of the countries of Europe,

02:35:03.940 --> 02:35:05.340
it is the,

02:35:06.320 --> 02:35:09.240
you know, current law. And it is to some
degree. I mean, I'm, I'm exaggerating.

02:35:09.300 --> 02:35:13.280
But legal scholars have to
study Roman law. Even, even,

02:35:13.600 --> 02:35:14.880
law students have to do that.

02:35:15.700 --> 02:35:19.560
Not in, so much in countries like the United
States or Britain, which have the so-called

02:35:19.620 --> 02:35:25.140
common law system. But ideas in
Roman law about, for example,

02:35:25.439 --> 02:35:28.980
property, right, ownership,
things like this,

02:35:29.520 --> 02:35:33.220
these were hugely important in formulating
ideas, for example, about sovereignty

02:35:33.480 --> 02:35:36.960
in political thought. Yeah, it's
one of the most important and

02:35:37.000 --> 02:35:40.280
influential acts of committee
work ever done in Constantinople.

02:35:41.700 --> 02:35:45.000
- So, going to Perplexity here and
looking at some aspects of the

02:35:45.060 --> 02:35:48.960
Justinian's laws, they include a
systematic structure of private

02:35:49.040 --> 02:35:52.750
law, persons, things,
actions, strong protection of

02:35:52.780 --> 02:35:56.580
property and contracts,
detailed family and inheritance

02:35:56.700 --> 02:36:00.120
rules, and a hierarchical
status-based view of

02:36:00.240 --> 02:36:04.080
persons. These elements became
the template for later civil

02:36:04.180 --> 02:36:11.140
law systems. And some overall
structures, tripartite schema, law

02:36:11.200 --> 02:36:18.660
organized around personae, legal
subjects, things, and procedural

02:36:18.800 --> 02:36:22.070
actions. Essentially
who, what, and how of—

02:36:22.070 --> 02:36:25.880
...private law. And it goes on. I mean, a
lot of the things I'm reading here really

02:36:25.940 --> 02:36:30.660
sounds like what we think
of as law. Marriage.

02:36:31.000 --> 02:36:33.760
- Look, most of it's about property.

02:36:35.140 --> 02:36:38.620
- Marriage is a legal status.
Lawful matrimony required

02:36:38.680 --> 02:36:42.380
conformity to rules about
age, citizenship, and

02:36:42.560 --> 02:36:46.520
cognatum or prohibited degrees,
incest rules, adoption

02:36:46.540 --> 02:36:49.060
relations, et cetera.
All that kind of stuff.

02:36:49.300 --> 02:36:51.620
- Oh, yes. Who you can marry, who not.

02:36:52.240 --> 02:36:53.960
- What was their view of homosexuality?

02:36:54.480 --> 02:36:57.330
- Well, I mean, Justinian
thought it caused earthquakes.

02:36:58.360 --> 02:36:58.790
- Oh, did it?

02:36:58.920 --> 02:36:59.200
- Yes.

02:36:59.570 --> 02:37:00.060
- Did it?

02:37:00.120 --> 02:37:00.300
- Yes.

02:37:00.360 --> 02:37:01.780
- Wow. That's fascinating.

02:37:01.880 --> 02:37:05.560
- Um, no, for him no, for, for...
So for Christian emperors

02:37:06.640 --> 02:37:10.720
or Christian authorities, this is
a, a reprehensible immoral act.

02:37:11.620 --> 02:37:15.680
Um, depending, it, it could be punished.

02:37:16.140 --> 02:37:20.100
Um, Justinian did try to punish
it pretty brutally. I mean,

02:37:20.420 --> 02:37:27.120
ultimately lethally. Um,
however, this gets really tricky

02:37:27.180 --> 02:37:34.500
here because what counts as a homosexual
act is not clear to everybody, right?

02:37:35.359 --> 02:37:45.420
And in addition to which, there... This
is a society that generally will not go

02:37:45.580 --> 02:37:48.560
after, let's say,

02:37:50.400 --> 02:37:54.340
Scandals or deviance or however you
wanna call it, like systematically.

02:37:54.380 --> 02:37:56.610
This is not like some--
There's no inquisition.

02:37:56.720 --> 02:38:03.810
There's no social police. If there's
some sort of scandal and this comes out,

02:38:04.080 --> 02:38:07.780
then it's a problem. But they're
not actively going to track down,

02:38:07.880 --> 02:38:11.720
hunt down, monitor, survey, interrogate

02:38:11.780 --> 02:38:15.460
people about their sex lives. I
mean, it is in a way, despite

02:38:15.500 --> 02:38:21.300
having views that we, we may
not agree with about sexuality,

02:38:22.140 --> 02:38:27.110
uh, it was, it was, it was generally
humane in the way of just kind of leaving

02:38:27.180 --> 02:38:28.040
people alone.

02:38:28.920 --> 02:38:32.820
- I mean, that said, there's some...
I'm just on Perplexity, looked

02:38:32.880 --> 02:38:40.100
up Justinian Roman law view of sexuality.
They're pretty harsh on, like adultery

02:38:40.140 --> 02:38:43.520
and just getting freaky with it.

02:38:43.660 --> 02:38:48.640
- No, Justinian was more zealous
in this matter, definitely.

02:38:48.700 --> 02:38:52.380
- Even though he married a sex worker.

02:38:53.400 --> 02:38:54.860
- Well, sex work wasn't illegal.

02:38:56.540 --> 02:38:58.380
- Right, but it's a bit spicy.

02:38:58.420 --> 02:39:02.300
- Yes. And in fact, it was
illegal for a senator to marry

02:39:02.500 --> 02:39:05.050
someone from such a
disreputable profession.

02:39:05.400 --> 02:39:10.256
And he got his uncle to pass a law
changing that rule- ... so that he could.

02:39:11.156 --> 02:39:14.316
- Well. Love knows no bounds.

02:39:14.516 --> 02:39:17.056
- Actually, Justinian kind of
says that in one of his laws.

02:39:17.336 --> 02:39:17.796
- Oh, wow.

02:39:18.296 --> 02:39:20.756
- No, he clearly loved her.
There, there's no question.

02:39:20.766 --> 02:39:24.336
- This actual love. I mean, this, you have
to like this guy. Starts as a peasant.

02:39:24.476 --> 02:39:28.336
Surround himself by all kinds
of weirdos just because they

02:39:28.356 --> 02:39:31.276
were good at what they did, and it
doesn't really matter, class or not.

02:39:31.796 --> 02:39:36.576
- Yes, but there's a lot to be said
against him, too. Um, I like so much.

02:39:37.976 --> 02:39:41.636
- Let's get into it. So he did
launch wars of conquest.

02:39:42.556 --> 02:39:46.436
What was his view of war and
conquest, and what maybe what

02:39:46.456 --> 02:39:50.676
are the things we should mention
in terms of expansionary wars?

02:39:50.716 --> 02:39:54.536
- He thought he was authorized by God to
reconquer the lost provinces of the Western

02:39:54.556 --> 02:39:58.396
Roman Empire, and when he did so,
that was proof that God favored him.

02:39:59.616 --> 02:40:03.596
And he was generally opportunistic
about it and for the most part, kind

02:40:03.636 --> 02:40:07.496
of successful in that he
intervened in the most

02:40:07.536 --> 02:40:11.496
critical moments of the histories of these
barbarian, you know, kingdoms in the

02:40:11.516 --> 02:40:15.076
West, and exploited their
weaknesses and took them

02:40:15.156 --> 02:40:18.836
over. Now, in the process, many of
these provinces were ravaged by

02:40:18.876 --> 02:40:25.356
war Italy for decades. He overstretched
his resources, leaving his

02:40:25.376 --> 02:40:31.796
successors with a much more
dangerous situation to defend.

02:40:32.356 --> 02:40:36.256
and he disbanded certain armies that
were meant to protect Constantinople,

02:40:36.636 --> 02:40:40.196
sent them to Italy, for example.
This weakened the home front.

02:40:41.156 --> 02:40:45.076
So he left a very difficult legacy
for his successors in that way.

02:40:45.136 --> 02:40:48.876
Plus, some of the provinces
that he conquered were so like

02:40:48.916 --> 02:40:52.766
Italy, I don't think it could even
pay for itself after a certain point.

02:40:53.016 --> 02:40:56.496
so I'm not sure that some of those
decisions were the best ones. North

02:40:56.596 --> 02:41:02.056
Africa, yeah, probably that paid off.
Italy and southern Spain, not so sure.

02:41:02.276 --> 02:41:06.836
- So that's one of the big criticisms
is even though there was conquest,

02:41:07.756 --> 02:41:12.996
it was overextended, and- ... those
lands were not economically stable.

02:41:13.476 --> 02:41:14.036
- Yeah, and

02:41:14.176 --> 02:41:15.676
- Broke. AKA.

02:41:15.956 --> 02:41:19.396
- Conquest is not just good, you
know, in itself. I mean, this is...

02:41:20.236 --> 02:41:24.096
I know that some rulers in history are called
the Great simply because they conquered

02:41:24.136 --> 02:41:29.156
something. But that's, no, that's not
enough. I mean, I know that rulers do this,

02:41:29.896 --> 02:41:33.616
but if we're to compare them to
each other we should at least

02:41:33.636 --> 02:41:37.616
expect that they have a plan or that
it works out well in the end, let's

02:41:37.656 --> 02:41:39.876
say, and I don't think
that many of these did.

02:41:40.576 --> 02:41:44.056
- I should say that as far as historians go,

02:41:44.656 --> 02:41:48.496
I think you don't give too many
points on the conquest front.

02:41:49.256 --> 02:41:50.776
- Personally, I? No, I don't.

02:41:51.056 --> 02:41:56.756
- Yeah, so your value comes from
is a leader implementing lasting

02:41:58.076 --> 02:42:00.076
change, like a stable-

02:42:00.216 --> 02:42:02.056
- Was he good for his subjects?

02:42:02.116 --> 02:42:05.236
Were they living better
because of him than otherwise?

02:42:05.596 --> 02:42:10.705
- And also, like, longer, like, the
long- term nature of it, not just-

02:42:10.756 --> 02:42:12.996
... not just, like, a temporary thing.

02:42:13.036 --> 02:42:17.956
- Right. Are you strengthening
institutions that benefit your subjects?

02:42:18.576 --> 02:42:22.416
That. And some he did, some
not. So look, in order to send

02:42:22.456 --> 02:42:26.236
those armies west to make the
conquests, he stripped the

02:42:26.316 --> 02:42:29.985
east of armies, so the Persians could
just march in and, like, destroyed

02:42:30.056 --> 02:42:33.476
Antioch. Like, that's a
major strategic failure,

02:42:34.376 --> 02:42:38.416
and I don't think you get a pass for
conquering North Africa by surrendering Syria.

02:42:39.536 --> 02:42:44.756
- He did rebuild Constantinople and
reconstructed the Hagia Sophia.

02:42:44.856 --> 02:42:48.735
- Yes, after he and his soldiers
set fire to it. Yes. I-

02:42:48.836 --> 02:42:52.705
in the Nika insurrection. So this is when the
people of the capital rise up against him,

02:42:53.456 --> 02:42:57.346
and there's, like about 10 days of street
fighting, and he brings in some armies,

02:42:57.396 --> 02:43:00.856
and eventually he orders
his armies to slaughter the

02:43:00.896 --> 02:43:04.676
protesters, leaving more than
30,000 dead. Like, this is an

02:43:04.716 --> 02:43:08.696
enormous number. And a
lot of Constantinople

02:43:08.716 --> 02:43:12.546
burned in the process, and yeah,
he rebuilt it. So his building is

02:43:12.576 --> 02:43:16.476
considered one of his great points. He
built Hagia Sophia, for example, which

02:43:16.536 --> 02:43:19.786
is a magnificent church, like, hands

02:43:19.836 --> 02:43:23.036
down. It's just a fascinating
monument to study,

02:43:23.076 --> 02:43:26.986
too. And yeah, that was, that
was him, too. I'm trying

02:43:26.996 --> 02:43:30.916
to give you a sense here that the good and
the bad are mixed in such equal measure

02:43:31.036 --> 02:43:35.466
that, like Buridan's ass, I can't decide
which- ... which bale of hay to put him on.

02:43:35.496 --> 02:43:37.696
- But there's a grand scale
to the good and the bad.

02:43:37.816 --> 02:43:38.866
- Yes, yes.

02:43:38.876 --> 02:43:41.936
- For many people, that's
what makes for a, uh-

02:43:42.256 --> 02:43:46.116
... top 10 emperor list.
Uh, what about the plague?

02:43:46.796 --> 02:43:48.656
- Well, he wasn't responsible
for that at least.

02:43:49.776 --> 02:43:49.906
- All right.

02:43:49.956 --> 02:43:50.176
- Okay.

02:43:50.696 --> 02:43:56.536
- The plague of Justinian- ... AKA
541 AD. So some historians claim

02:43:56.556 --> 02:43:59.056
that it killed half the
population and ruined the empire.

02:43:59.996 --> 02:44:01.576
You are skeptical on this view.

02:44:02.016 --> 02:44:05.856
- Yes. So this is a bubonic plague.

02:44:06.276 --> 02:44:10.196
Um, which lasts more or
less for two centuries. It

02:44:10.236 --> 02:44:14.076
comes and it goes, and it's kind
of endemic to large parts of the

02:44:14.116 --> 02:44:18.056
world. 541 is when it
starts to break out in

02:44:18.096 --> 02:44:21.896
the empire, in Constantinople and
other cities, and it spreads.

02:44:22.776 --> 02:44:26.716
There's been a lot of debate about
this recently because now we've

02:44:26.776 --> 02:44:30.356
actually isolated the pathogen. It's
Yersinia pestis. Like, we know this.

02:44:31.036 --> 02:44:33.976
Just as of, like, a generation
ago, this was just guesswork.

02:44:34.036 --> 02:44:37.936
But now there's all of this new, like,
laboratory science work that's come in to

02:44:37.976 --> 02:44:40.016
fill in some of the gaps in history.

02:44:40.076 --> 02:44:40.736
- That's so cool.

02:44:40.796 --> 02:44:44.406
- It is. It is. There are lots
of discussions about that. And

02:44:44.436 --> 02:44:50.696
so the study of diseases and virology have
just become much more important lately.

02:44:51.956 --> 02:44:55.816
It still doesn't tell you, however,
like mortality rates and historical

02:44:55.876 --> 02:44:59.576
impact. Like, for that, you still
need standard old-fashioned

02:44:59.656 --> 02:45:01.376
non-laboratory historical work.

02:45:01.796 --> 02:45:05.726
And there's a debate about the impact of this
plague. It's ongoing, I should say that.

02:45:06.656 --> 02:45:10.226
And some scholars argue for a
kind of maximalist position

02:45:10.296 --> 02:45:15.216
of 50%. I think that would have
brought this society to a halt.

02:45:16.152 --> 02:45:22.472
Just logistically speaking. And so I
believe in a much more moderate impact.

02:45:22.872 --> 02:45:25.612
- And the real impact is
what? The tax base shrinks?

02:45:25.832 --> 02:45:29.452
- Oh. Oh, yeah. The tax base
would shrink instantly.

02:45:29.892 --> 02:45:33.812
You wouldn't be able to recruit armies.
You know, there would be massive social

02:45:33.872 --> 02:45:37.732
dislocation. Like what
happens in the, in the Black

02:45:37.812 --> 02:45:41.742
Death in Europe in the 14th century.
Like, we have very good records

02:45:41.772 --> 02:45:45.732
for what happened to those societies, and basically
everything that they were doing stopped for a few

02:45:45.792 --> 02:45:49.712
years until they sort of tried to
put things back together again. This

02:45:49.752 --> 02:45:51.252
does not happen in the 6th century.

02:45:52.072 --> 02:45:56.052
In fact, Justinian is at that
time waging war on something like

02:45:56.112 --> 02:45:57.632
four or five different fronts.

02:45:58.812 --> 02:46:02.602
If you read the narratives of those
wars, there's no pause. There's

02:46:02.752 --> 02:46:06.532
no, there's no impact
from the plague on the

02:46:06.592 --> 02:46:08.882
conduct of those wars.
They just continue on.

02:46:09.252 --> 02:46:13.162
Taxation continues. The courts continue.
Like, you just don't see it in

02:46:13.192 --> 02:46:16.952
the narrative, and so I think
that there's a much less

02:46:17.032 --> 02:46:19.532
impact than, certainly than 50%, yeah.

02:46:19.872 --> 02:46:24.752
- So this sets the stage for
a tumultuous 7th century.

02:46:25.392 --> 02:46:27.492
- Yeah, you could call it that. Yes.

02:46:27.912 --> 02:46:35.052
- So what is the legacy of Justinian,
in terms of how he left the empire

02:46:35.612 --> 02:46:37.792
leading into the 7th century?

02:46:38.492 --> 02:46:42.472
- Well, he left it overextended,
so his successors

02:46:42.512 --> 02:46:46.182
had to deal with many more
problems along many more fronts,

02:46:46.992 --> 02:46:50.972
With fewer military forces
concentrated in what we might call the

02:46:51.012 --> 02:46:52.752
homeland of the Eastern Roman Empire.

02:46:53.892 --> 02:46:57.792
And so that made the, the center
vulnerable too, and so you start

02:46:57.832 --> 02:47:04.372
to get raids into the Balkans and, you
know, it enters a kind of vicious cycle

02:47:05.012 --> 02:47:06.032
again.

02:47:07.112 --> 02:47:10.672
now, not all of this was Justinian's fault.
I mean, the plague definitely had some

02:47:10.732 --> 02:47:16.582
impact. But I wouldn't
blame everything on his

02:47:16.592 --> 02:47:20.542
successors, as is sometimes done,
like they mishandled the situation.

02:47:21.432 --> 02:47:26.591
He... Yeah, he left them a very
difficult situation to deal with.

02:47:27.132 --> 02:47:29.632
- So speaking of which, let's
talk about Heraclius.

02:47:30.612 --> 02:47:34.432
He didn't make, he didn't make your
list either, which is a shocker

02:47:35.112 --> 02:47:38.452
for a lot of people. Perhaps you can
describe the nuance of that, but

02:47:38.532 --> 02:47:41.672
he took over the Roman
Empire on the verge of

02:47:41.712 --> 02:47:49.392
extinction. Persians at the gates,
treasury empty. So maybe first tell the

02:47:49.452 --> 02:47:53.432
full saga of the Roman-Persian War that
threatened the empire's existence.

02:47:53.632 --> 02:47:56.652
- Sure. Well, he wasn't entirely, you know,

02:47:57.392 --> 02:48:01.072
free of blame for the
situation that he inherited.

02:48:01.112 --> 02:48:05.441
He was in part responsible for it.
So he doesn't get a pass on that.

02:48:05.472 --> 02:48:10.272
So Heraclius is basically
a rebel and a usurper. So

02:48:11.612 --> 02:48:18.672
for various reasons Rome and Persia
are at war starting around 602.

02:48:18.992 --> 02:48:22.712
and the, the Persian shah
at this time, Khosrow II,

02:48:23.272 --> 02:48:26.872
has basically decided on
a policy of conquest,

02:48:27.012 --> 02:48:30.001
not just raiding. Like, I'm gonna
go in and take your people,

02:48:31.092 --> 02:48:34.412
some cattle, and some statues, and
take them to, you know, Mesopotamia.

02:48:35.212 --> 02:48:39.001
He starts what... I mean, I think there's
some evolution in his thinking and his

02:48:39.032 --> 02:48:42.292
planning about this, but
pretty soon during the

02:48:42.472 --> 02:48:46.142
600 and the aughts, he
realizes that there's

02:48:46.172 --> 02:48:50.032
potential for actual permanent territorial
gain here, and his armies start moving

02:48:50.112 --> 02:48:54.052
in. And the Roman Emperor is this guy
called Phocas, who is himself a usurper,

02:48:54.812 --> 02:48:58.592
a military background, and
he now faces a rebellion

02:48:58.672 --> 02:49:02.992
by Heraclius, who, whose base is in North
Africa at this time, like around Carthage.

02:49:04.152 --> 02:49:09.692
And they have a civil war
for three years, 608 to 610.

02:49:10.202 --> 02:49:13.592
That civil war that Heraclius initiates

02:49:14.472 --> 02:49:18.292
causes a diversion of Roman
armies to the civil war away

02:49:18.312 --> 02:49:22.072
from the Persian front. So it's
a massive gift to the Persians.

02:49:22.732 --> 02:49:26.412
Plus, a lot of the fighting takes
place in Egypt, and Egypt was a

02:49:26.452 --> 02:49:31.722
province that had up until that point not
really been harmed by war. Now it is,

02:49:32.531 --> 02:49:36.402
right? So Heraclius's forces, he's
not in Egypt, but his backers,

02:49:37.392 --> 02:49:41.072
are fighting a civil war in
Egypt, so that province is

02:49:41.112 --> 02:49:45.072
now, you know, ravaged in part. The

02:49:45.112 --> 02:49:49.092
Persians make tremendous gains in the
east. Heraclius heads straight for

02:49:49.172 --> 02:49:53.112
Constantinople during all of this, and
to make a long story short, he manages

02:49:53.172 --> 02:49:56.762
to take Constantinople, execute
Phocas, and become emperor,

02:49:57.212 --> 02:50:01.072
right? But now he's facing a problem
that's much worse than it was

02:50:01.132 --> 02:50:06.832
when, before he started the rebellion.
The reason why Heraclius is sort of

02:50:06.932 --> 02:50:10.832
lionized in some... Well, actually,
there's a very long tradition of doing

02:50:10.892 --> 02:50:14.572
this, which goes back to the Middle Ages. In the
Western Middle Ages, Heraclius was sometimes

02:50:14.592 --> 02:50:16.092
considered, like, the first crusader.

02:50:16.672 --> 02:50:17.512
- Oh, interesting.

02:50:17.912 --> 02:50:21.412
- Yeah, yeah. So there's all this medieval
literature about Heraclius as being a

02:50:21.452 --> 02:50:23.512
a proto-crusader type and all that,

02:50:24.352 --> 02:50:28.202
For reconquering, like,
Jerusalem from the Persians and

02:50:28.232 --> 02:50:32.192
restoring the True Cross and all
that. So he had this kind of

02:50:32.292 --> 02:50:34.921
aura, and I think his modern

02:50:35.352 --> 02:50:39.302
admirers are basically just continuing...
I mean, they might not know it,

02:50:39.532 --> 02:50:43.382
but they're kind of continuing this very,
very long tradition of treating Heraclius as

02:50:43.412 --> 02:50:48.612
this heroic holy warrior.
Anyway, from my standpoint,

02:50:49.672 --> 02:50:53.292
it's a complete wash.
In other words, yes, he

02:50:53.432 --> 02:50:57.392
does beat the Persians and he gets, like,

02:50:57.452 --> 02:51:01.252
in my view, full credit for that,
though he did it with, I think, the

02:51:01.312 --> 02:51:05.052
help of some Turkish allies from
Central Asia. These were, I think,

02:51:05.632 --> 02:51:09.272
the major component of his
success at the very end. But no,

02:51:09.292 --> 02:51:13.402
no. So he held the Persians off
and ultimately defeated them, yes.

02:51:14.212 --> 02:51:16.032
And then he loses everything to the Arabs.

02:51:16.372 --> 02:51:23.812
- So the Arab conquests are 630s and 640s,
but the Persian War is 602 to 628.

02:51:23.892 --> 02:51:24.172
- Yes.

02:51:24.552 --> 02:51:31.356
- So what can be said about this what
seems to be a pretty costly war, I guess

02:51:31.536 --> 02:51:32.036
Persians

02:51:32.556 --> 02:51:37.596
- So the war was costly
initially only for the Romans.

02:51:38.656 --> 02:51:42.296
the eastern provinces were conquered
by Persia. That means Syria,

02:51:42.336 --> 02:51:44.996
Palestine, Egypt. So that's a loss.

02:51:45.116 --> 02:51:48.506
You lose all that revenue, and then
they start raiding into Asia Minor.

02:51:48.796 --> 02:51:49.196
- Yes.

02:51:49.216 --> 02:51:53.086
- By the way, this is exactly what the Arabs
would do, you know, just a couple decades

02:51:53.176 --> 02:51:56.796
later. They would conquer Syria, Palestine, Egypt,
and they would start raiding into Asia Minor.

02:51:57.616 --> 02:52:01.266
So almost like this phase of
East Roman history begins

02:52:01.316 --> 02:52:05.276
already during the Persian invasion. It's
just a kind of a prelude. It was, in

02:52:05.316 --> 02:52:07.816
fact, the Arabs that would do
that for the next few centuries.

02:52:08.716 --> 02:52:13.296
So Heraclius, it takes him a
very long time to get organized,

02:52:14.116 --> 02:52:17.936
In fact, something like
15 years, and it's not

02:52:17.956 --> 02:52:21.756
entirely clear, like, what
he's doing all this time. Um,

02:52:22.356 --> 02:52:29.736
but he ultimately manages to defeat
the Persians by waging these really

02:52:29.816 --> 02:52:33.636
spectacular, weird
campaigns in the East. He

02:52:33.676 --> 02:52:37.616
decides to strike into
the Persian heartland,

02:52:37.696 --> 02:52:41.116
as it were. Well, first in the
Caucasus region, and then he goes into

02:52:41.136 --> 02:52:44.646
Mesopotamia. So not to try
to defeat their armies that

02:52:44.676 --> 02:52:48.396
are rampaging around Asia Minor
or even besieging his capital

02:52:48.736 --> 02:52:52.716
in 626. The Persians and the
Avars, this people from... This

02:52:52.756 --> 02:52:56.656
nomadic warrior group that
settled in roughly modern

02:52:56.716 --> 02:53:00.016
Hungary, they're besieging Constantinople.
Heraclius doesn't even go.

02:53:01.036 --> 02:53:04.746
And he's just kind of preparing his
armies in the East, and he strikes the

02:53:04.776 --> 02:53:08.296
Persians right where it
hurts, and this now begins to

02:53:08.336 --> 02:53:12.156
degrade the Persian heartland
and their infrastructure

02:53:12.776 --> 02:53:16.586
because remember, both of these empires are going
to be in shambles by the time the Arabs come

02:53:16.596 --> 02:53:20.036
along, and this is what enables the Arabs
to conquer them so quickly. I mean, they've

02:53:20.056 --> 02:53:21.116
destroyed each other

02:53:22.036 --> 02:53:25.916
in these wars. And eventually Heraclius
calls in his Turkish allies, and they

02:53:25.976 --> 02:53:29.936
go on a field trip
through Mesopotamia, and

02:53:29.956 --> 02:53:33.436
this causes a coup in, in
Persia, and Khosrow is killed.

02:53:34.056 --> 02:53:37.796
- Is there something to be said,
a little bit of texture to the

02:53:37.836 --> 02:53:41.686
motivations of the different empires and
the different groups involved? So the

02:53:41.736 --> 02:53:45.136
East Roman Empire, the Persian
Empire, and the Islamic

02:53:45.176 --> 02:53:48.796
Caliphates, were they after
conquering? Were they

02:53:48.956 --> 02:53:52.736
after expansion? Were they
after more like raiding

02:53:52.796 --> 02:53:55.836
for financial benefits?
What was the motivation?

02:53:56.156 --> 02:54:00.026
- So in the past, the Persian Shahs
basically were interested in raiding, and

02:54:00.056 --> 02:54:03.976
they also had an interest in manpower.
So all of those Mesopotamian

02:54:04.056 --> 02:54:07.696
agricultural estates won't till
themselves. So they were kind of

02:54:07.716 --> 02:54:11.696
insatiable for agricultural workforces and
specialized craftsmen and people like that.

02:54:11.756 --> 02:54:14.276
so they would go into
the empire and get them.

02:54:15.416 --> 02:54:18.876
But in this phase, it seems that Khosrow

02:54:19.036 --> 02:54:22.796
II is taking really to heart
the idea that the Persian

02:54:22.836 --> 02:54:24.916
Empire should really extend
to the Mediterranean

02:54:25.816 --> 02:54:29.676
as it did in, like, Achaemenid times,
right, in, in ancient history, the empire

02:54:29.686 --> 02:54:33.656
that Alexander conquered. So it
seems that the, the Sassanians,

02:54:33.716 --> 02:54:37.416
this is this dynasty, this Iranian
dynasty that's ruling the Persian

02:54:37.476 --> 02:54:41.436
Empire, of course, they were aware of
the Achaemenids, but sometimes they

02:54:41.476 --> 02:54:46.296
would have these claims to reviving the
former greatness of the Iranian Empire.

02:54:46.796 --> 02:54:50.616
So, you know, bathing in the
Mediterranean Sea is something

02:54:50.676 --> 02:54:54.636
that many Near Eastern monarchs, you know,

02:54:54.676 --> 02:54:59.896
they did this as a sign of success. Anyway,
for the Romans, it was sheer survival,

02:55:00.976 --> 02:55:04.956
Just desperate survival 'cause
they knew that this was a war

02:55:04.996 --> 02:55:06.456
that could end the Roman state.

02:55:06.516 --> 02:55:10.716
- I mean, they're already on
the verge of being ended.

02:55:10.856 --> 02:55:15.496
And here, their defensive
wars of survival.

02:55:15.816 --> 02:55:24.036
- Yeah. So it's pretty clear that initially
the goal of Arab Muslim warfare is to

02:55:24.116 --> 02:55:27.976
unify Arabia. That is,
that all Arabs should be

02:55:28.236 --> 02:55:35.376
Muslim and should be unified into this
religious kind of state, whatever, that

02:55:35.776 --> 02:55:40.496
the prophet and his successors had created.
Now, then they start striking out,

02:55:41.516 --> 02:55:47.896
Into Rome and into Iran. It's not
entirely clear, like, why. Now,

02:55:49.056 --> 02:55:52.536
there are obvious reasons. Like, I
mean, we don't-- It's not, like, a

02:55:52.656 --> 02:55:55.996
huge historical mystery
why a, you know, recently

02:55:56.006 --> 02:56:01.096
formed successful army will decide
to take on two very weak opponents-

02:56:01.176 --> 02:56:04.956
... who are on their doorstep. Like-
... this is not, you know, complicated.

02:56:04.976 --> 02:56:08.456
- Yeah, they're pretty effective
at military- ... conquest.

02:56:08.576 --> 02:56:12.256
- Yeah. But they're striking both
empires from a direction that those

02:56:12.296 --> 02:56:16.016
empires had never prepared to
defend from. Arabia was just

02:56:16.076 --> 02:56:19.996
not, "Oh, you might get some occasional
raiders, but you're never gonna get an

02:56:20.176 --> 02:56:24.136
army that's coming out that can
potentially conquer you." So

02:56:24.196 --> 02:56:26.976
the defensive orientations are all wrong.

02:56:27.456 --> 02:56:30.256
And these two empires have
gone through this massive war,

02:56:31.136 --> 02:56:34.916
that has destabilized them. They're,
they're low on manpower, low on

02:56:34.956 --> 02:56:38.896
resources. The outcome is almost kind
of inevitable. I don't think there's a

02:56:38.916 --> 02:56:39.676
great mystery.

02:56:40.516 --> 02:56:44.956
- And the effect of that is they
stripped away the richest provinces

02:56:45.776 --> 02:56:47.116
of the Roman Empire.

02:56:47.936 --> 02:56:50.466
- Yes, Egypt in particular.

02:56:50.536 --> 02:56:54.516
That's, that means now you can't feed Constantinople.
Like we talked about the grain from Egypt,

02:56:54.556 --> 02:56:56.996
right, that came to Constantinople.
You don't have that now.

02:56:57.796 --> 02:57:01.016
And so that means that the population
of Constantinople will decline

02:57:01.076 --> 02:57:03.456
dramatically over the next few decades.

02:57:03.816 --> 02:57:06.086
- So how, how does the
empire rebuild itself,

02:57:07.616 --> 02:57:11.586
you know, restabilize? Because it's
not, it doesn't collapse there, right?

02:57:11.936 --> 02:57:12.456
- Yes.

02:57:12.516 --> 02:57:16.096
- It stays, it survives.
There's interesting low

02:57:16.216 --> 02:57:18.676
points for the empire
where it still survives.

02:57:18.816 --> 02:57:19.495
- This is one of them.

02:57:20.316 --> 02:57:22.856
- And that is as interesting
as the survival at the top,

02:57:23.956 --> 02:57:27.436
and the flourishing survival
at the bottom is also super

02:57:27.476 --> 02:57:31.696
interesting. So how do-- What
happens? How does it kinda stabilize?

02:57:32.236 --> 02:57:39.312
- Very slowly. This is a painful process, and
it takes them centuries, you could say.

02:57:39.392 --> 02:57:43.391
First you gotta stop the bleeding,
just try to hold the line.

02:57:43.512 --> 02:57:46.842
It takes them decades to just
to hold a line. Like, they get

02:57:46.892 --> 02:57:53.372
pummeled by the Arabs for decades in the
seventh century until finally by, 6-

02:57:54.112 --> 02:57:58.272
660s, 670, they finally
begin to beat them.

02:57:59.352 --> 02:58:05.112
Beat them on land and hold
the line, on the sea.

02:58:06.012 --> 02:58:09.632
And so we now have an
investment in fleets.

02:58:10.472 --> 02:58:13.932
Eventually, you get the Greek
fire, which is the flamethrowers.

02:58:14.792 --> 02:58:18.392
And when the Arabs try to
take Constantinople, these

02:58:18.452 --> 02:58:22.322
attempts are defeated,
like, twice, and that

02:58:22.372 --> 02:58:26.952
ensures the survival of this, of
the Roman state in some form.

02:58:27.712 --> 02:58:29.632
- How were the flamethrowers used?

02:58:29.932 --> 02:58:32.972
- Ah, yes. This is an interesting question.
We're still kind of debating that.

02:58:33.372 --> 02:58:34.572
- Oh, it's not fully understood.

02:58:34.672 --> 02:58:35.732
- Well, it's a state secret.

02:58:37.322 --> 02:58:41.222
They didn't want this getting out, so
they kept it pretty well. The fact

02:58:41.252 --> 02:58:44.752
that we're debating it will tell you that
they were pretty good at keeping secrets.

02:58:44.892 --> 02:58:53.792
So possibly through a pressure valve.
Right? So you have this flammable compound

02:58:55.392 --> 02:58:58.352
whose preparation and components
is also a state secret.

02:58:59.292 --> 02:59:03.212
So there's specialized-- There's a corps
of engineers that prepares this and

02:59:03.252 --> 02:59:04.112
deploys it.

02:59:04.932 --> 02:59:12.152
Um, and it's possibly through a heated
pressurized container with a spigot,

02:59:12.232 --> 02:59:18.992
let's say, that unleashes this thing
through a nozzle, and it's lit and

02:59:20.032 --> 02:59:23.612
basically spews flaming napalm

02:59:24.992 --> 02:59:29.772
on other ships, and it will continue
to burn even when it's on the water.

02:59:29.812 --> 02:59:33.802
Right? On the top. So, like, you can't,
like, swim away or anything. So it's

02:59:33.812 --> 02:59:37.512
this very, very destructive
weapon. Terrifying. They used it

02:59:37.552 --> 02:59:41.412
against Vikings too. This is much
later. So once the Vikings show up-

02:59:41.691 --> 02:59:44.992
... Like, when they would raid attacked

02:59:45.032 --> 02:59:49.062
Constantinople in the 940s,
then again in the 1040s-

02:59:50.272 --> 02:59:54.372
... Yeah, the Romans used Greek fire
fleets to just incinerate the...

02:59:55.412 --> 02:59:57.452
And that'll teach Vikings.

02:59:59.272 --> 03:00:03.152
Yes. If you're in that situation,
you'd rather serve under

03:00:03.192 --> 03:00:05.872
the emperors than attack them.

03:00:06.872 --> 03:00:10.552
- And so this is a kind of nuclear
weapon level state secret.

03:00:10.752 --> 03:00:12.292
- They even had it in hand grenade form.

03:00:14.452 --> 03:00:15.252
- This is a real thing?

03:00:15.612 --> 03:00:15.932
- Oh, yes.

03:00:16.792 --> 03:00:17.572
- Hand grenade form.

03:00:17.682 --> 03:00:19.732
- Yes. So it's a, it's
like a clay container,

03:00:20.652 --> 03:00:24.292
with the compound, and it
has, like, some sort of

03:00:24.352 --> 03:00:27.282
fuse that you light on the
outside and you throw it. Now,

03:00:28.252 --> 03:00:31.692
you throw it... You can throw it against
people, but it's not gonna be that effective.

03:00:31.732 --> 03:00:35.072
Maybe you burn a person, whatever. You just
wasted a hand grenade for, you know, one

03:00:35.112 --> 03:00:40.232
person. It's most effective against
things like, uh, siege engines.

03:00:40.852 --> 03:00:45.092
Uh, so you, you throw that on a
wooden frame and, you know, yeah.

03:00:45.332 --> 03:00:48.592
- This is incredible. So this is one of
the things that's finally stabilized,

03:00:49.632 --> 03:00:52.632
Stopped the bleeding from
a military perspective.

03:00:52.772 --> 03:00:56.342
- Yeah, eventually. Now, now remember, they've
pulled the armies back into Asia Minor,

03:00:56.832 --> 03:01:00.552
so they're, they're beginning
to defend and fortify Asia

03:01:00.672 --> 03:01:04.302
Minor. Now you have to find ways to pay and
support and feed all of these soldiers, and

03:01:04.332 --> 03:01:07.612
this is a whole administrative-
it's a wrenching

03:01:07.672 --> 03:01:11.132
administrative readjustment. But they go
through it. It takes them a long time.

03:01:11.572 --> 03:01:15.232
Eventually, they emerge with a different
kind of strategic logistical system.

03:01:15.652 --> 03:01:20.072
- Just a smaller, harder- ...
core- ... of the empire.

03:01:20.252 --> 03:01:21.852
- That's right. Very militarized.

03:01:22.612 --> 03:01:27.852
- Very militarized. And then in the eighth
century, the, the second Arab siege

03:01:27.892 --> 03:01:30.592
of Constantinople, that somehow fails.

03:01:31.072 --> 03:01:33.892
- In the early eighth century,
yes, that was the second siege.

03:01:34.332 --> 03:01:38.192
- Yeah, the early eighth century.
So why, why did it fail? Can you

03:01:38.232 --> 03:01:43.592
tell the story of that siege? That was
really the empire hanging by, by a thread.

03:01:43.672 --> 03:01:47.442
- Yes, but it happened to have a very
competent man in charge. This is,

03:01:47.532 --> 03:01:51.461
uh, Leo III, and he's an emperor
who has- he's a usurper. He's just

03:01:51.492 --> 03:01:55.472
seized power. They knew that
this massive Arab attack was

03:01:55.532 --> 03:01:58.992
coming, and so it's quite
possible that the Roman

03:01:59.052 --> 03:02:02.472
elites, you know, preferred to put someone

03:02:02.532 --> 03:02:06.372
capable in, in power at that moment.
The city was very well prepared.

03:02:07.092 --> 03:02:10.792
I encourage people in the audience to, to go and
read the, the sources that we have for that.

03:02:10.812 --> 03:02:14.572
You, you can find many accounts of it
online. It, it was just very, very

03:02:14.612 --> 03:02:18.592
well done. He also had Bulgar allies.

03:02:18.972 --> 03:02:22.732
So these are the, the Bulgars who had just,
you know, crossed the Danube just, like, just

03:02:22.792 --> 03:02:26.742
a few years earlier actually and
settled south of the Danube, you

03:02:26.772 --> 03:02:30.742
know, where eventually, you know, Bulgaria
emerged. So he had Bulgar allies,

03:02:31.232 --> 03:02:35.032
and he used the, the Greek fire very,
very strategically. He used his

03:02:35.072 --> 03:02:38.772
own fleet. He contained the Arabs to
certain places where they kind of

03:02:38.852 --> 03:02:42.492
starved and wore them down.
Yeah, it's just very well done.

03:02:42.912 --> 03:02:44.132
- From a military perspective.

03:02:44.162 --> 03:02:45.332
- From a military perspective.

03:02:45.852 --> 03:02:52.232
- Well, was there, was it the, the
walls, the navy, the weather, the

03:02:52.272 --> 03:02:57.972
diplomacy, just good luck that
helped Constantinople hold?

03:02:58.172 --> 03:03:01.962
- I don't see much role for good luck there. I
mean, I think he had it all pretty planned out.

03:03:01.972 --> 03:03:05.852
It was all of the elements that you mentioned.
And yeah, he, he just deployed them very,

03:03:05.872 --> 03:03:09.592
very astutely and went on to rule

03:03:09.672 --> 03:03:13.401
after that for another 20-some
years, and his son continued. Um,

03:03:13.992 --> 03:03:17.832
they, they formed a dynasty. It was-- We call it
the Isaurian dynasty, though they were not from

03:03:17.892 --> 03:03:18.332
Isauria.

03:03:19.192 --> 03:03:22.952
- And then from that, the fascinating
thing that we mentioned about religion,

03:03:23.442 --> 03:03:27.392
there was a whole stretch
of time marked by intense

03:03:27.532 --> 03:03:31.072
internal religious
conflicts over iconoclasm.

03:03:32.092 --> 03:03:35.842
Maybe you can clarify this, but so
iconoclasm, of course, is whether

03:03:35.892 --> 03:03:39.542
sacred images, icons, should
be venerated or destroyed.

03:03:40.332 --> 03:03:44.076
This had major political
and theological stakes. The

03:03:44.096 --> 03:03:47.936
seemingly smallest things can
have the biggest of conflicts.

03:03:48.176 --> 03:03:50.956
- Yeah. You've been in an Orthodox church.

03:03:51.216 --> 03:03:54.356
Have you seen all the icons and
the just painting everywhere?

03:03:54.916 --> 03:03:58.776
Every space that you can imagine
is covered in either icons or

03:03:58.876 --> 03:04:02.476
images or iconography of saints.
All right. That's a result of this.

03:04:03.516 --> 03:04:07.376
No, that's not what Christian churches used
to be like, at least not in Constantinople.

03:04:08.216 --> 03:04:13.856
But his dynasty basically tried to limit,

03:04:14.756 --> 03:04:18.666
Or remove images from
churches, and ultimately that

03:04:18.696 --> 03:04:22.026
policy failed. And the other side that

03:04:22.516 --> 03:04:26.496
wanted images or liked images, or let me
put it differently, thought that images

03:04:26.536 --> 03:04:29.836
were not only appropriate but
helpful in the context of Christian

03:04:29.876 --> 03:04:33.756
worship prevailed. And so
gradually the churches began

03:04:33.796 --> 03:04:41.176
to fill up with icons, lots of icons.
They're almost like, you know, like a

03:04:41.216 --> 03:04:45.056
catchword for Orthodox,
you know, devotion. Um,

03:04:45.256 --> 03:04:49.175
I have icons at home. You have a little corner
in the house and you have little iconography.

03:04:49.656 --> 03:04:53.496
Um, anyway, I mean, as a secular Orthodox
person, but I... even I can't get away

03:04:53.576 --> 03:04:54.086
from them.

03:04:55.406 --> 03:04:57.226
- But that has serious
consequences. I mean, that was-

03:04:57.266 --> 03:05:00.856
... serious. It was an extremely
serious internal religious conflict.

03:05:01.056 --> 03:05:09.076
- Well, okay, so one asterisk on that.
In my research, I did not find a

03:05:09.136 --> 03:05:11.776
popular interest in this matter. Like-

03:05:12.176 --> 03:05:12.666
- Oh, interesting

03:05:12.676 --> 03:05:13.776
- ... yeah, I don't-

03:05:14.216 --> 03:05:15.476
- So this is an overblown-

03:05:15.636 --> 03:05:18.476
- Yes. Yes, socially completely overblown.

03:05:18.556 --> 03:05:22.476
- Oh, this is one of those things
where religious folks will write the

03:05:22.616 --> 03:05:23.556
story of history.

03:05:23.576 --> 03:05:24.316
- That's it. Got it.

03:05:24.776 --> 03:05:25.236
- Ah.

03:05:25.276 --> 03:05:25.656
- You got it.

03:05:26.556 --> 03:05:30.456
I could not find... There were, like, a
few emperors, and there's some bishops

03:05:30.496 --> 03:05:34.216
and abbots and monks. Like,
I don't know, maybe 100, 200

03:05:34.256 --> 03:05:37.536
people are, like, seriously invested
in this, and they're going at it.

03:05:38.316 --> 03:05:40.756
But these are the people
who write the texts.

03:05:41.576 --> 03:05:44.956
But they never mention, for example,
that, oh, you know, the people of

03:05:44.996 --> 03:05:48.936
Constantinople, they rose up, and
they demanded icons or not icons or

03:05:48.976 --> 03:05:50.136
anything like that.

03:05:50.156 --> 03:05:55.576
Nah, never. So in my view, this is
one of those controversies that's

03:05:56.576 --> 03:06:00.306
only a few people really, really cared-

03:06:00.306 --> 03:06:04.255
... about it, and unfortunately,
they're the ones who wrote the sources.

03:06:04.816 --> 03:06:05.896
- So you always have to,

03:06:07.836 --> 03:06:11.696
Be very careful to consider the
sources when you're reading about

03:06:11.756 --> 03:06:14.416
anything involving religious events.

03:06:14.596 --> 03:06:15.656
- Or any kind of events.

03:06:15.896 --> 03:06:21.556
- But certain things are more intensely,
People are more intensely passionate about-

03:06:21.586 --> 03:06:24.216
... and therefore they're
going, that bias is going to-

03:06:24.256 --> 03:06:24.516
- Yeah, yeah

03:06:24.576 --> 03:06:28.456
- ... bleed into the way
you report the history.

03:06:28.466 --> 03:06:31.246
- Yeah. And not only that, when
emperors changed their policy,

03:06:33.076 --> 03:06:36.996
almost everyone fell into
line. They switched positions.

03:06:37.616 --> 03:06:41.296
It's like, "No, yeah, whatever. Put the
images, take the images," like, whatever.

03:06:41.376 --> 03:06:44.966
I mean, like this isn't, they did not
see this as central. Some people did,

03:06:45.576 --> 03:06:46.976
and they got very worked up about it.

03:06:48.276 --> 03:06:52.016
Anyway, but in the end,
the pro-icon position won,

03:06:52.856 --> 03:06:56.096
and their view just began
to fill up the space.

03:06:56.176 --> 03:07:02.096
Like, like it literally was filling
up the churches, and it still does.

03:07:02.136 --> 03:07:09.536
- The thing is, we somehow took on the
impossible task of talking about a thousand-

03:07:10.176 --> 03:07:12.216
- It'll defeat you, man. It'll
defeat you every time.

03:07:12.736 --> 03:07:16.596
- I mean, there's a reason why you
really wanna do a thousand-hour

03:07:16.696 --> 03:07:18.276
podcast on this, right?

03:07:18.296 --> 03:07:22.286
As, as, as you do, as there's so many
incredible conversations about every

03:07:22.416 --> 03:07:26.336
single emperor, every single nuanced
detail of the emperors. It really is a, is

03:07:26.376 --> 03:07:31.856
a thriving civilization. It's
a thriving empire which in it

03:07:31.916 --> 03:07:35.796
contains so many lessons for even
the modern times. But anyway,

03:07:35.896 --> 03:07:39.756
you have written one of the books
is Streams of Gold, Rivers of

03:07:39.776 --> 03:07:46.625
Blood: The Rise and Fall of Byzantium,
955 AD to the First Crusade. So this

03:07:46.656 --> 03:07:50.396
period has... We talked
about survival and some low

03:07:50.476 --> 03:07:54.456
points. This is a period where, once
again, there's some flourishing.

03:07:55.516 --> 03:08:00.276
So by the 10th century in the
Macedonian era, the empire is back.

03:08:01.356 --> 03:08:07.076
It's wealthy, it's culturally confident,
and under emperors like Basil II,

03:08:08.056 --> 03:08:11.116
Who I think is in your top 10 list.

03:08:11.896 --> 03:08:15.806
it is expanding again, and
this is a period that you

03:08:15.956 --> 03:08:19.936
describe in part in your book, Streams
of Gold, Rivers of Blood. So how did

03:08:19.956 --> 03:08:23.036
Byzantium go from surviving
to expanding again?

03:08:23.796 --> 03:08:29.936
- So I wrote that book in part in
order to test myself and see if I

03:08:29.956 --> 03:08:31.496
could write narrative.

03:08:31.756 --> 03:08:35.716
So I hadn't written a history narrative
book up until that point. Everything

03:08:35.776 --> 03:08:37.676
I wrote was sort of analytical, right?

03:08:38.816 --> 03:08:42.636
And it was successful enough that a
few years later, my editor asked me to

03:08:42.656 --> 03:08:44.856
write the big history,
the new Roman Empire-

03:08:44.976 --> 03:08:45.356
- Yeah

03:08:45.366 --> 03:08:46.046
- ... the thousand page-

03:08:46.076 --> 03:08:46.686
- Of the whole thing

03:08:46.856 --> 03:08:50.716
- ... of the whole thing. And
so I set for myself the

03:08:50.796 --> 03:08:54.516
task of explaining in this book,
Streams of Gold, Rivers of Blood,

03:08:55.556 --> 03:08:58.976
a very particular period
that was marked by a

03:08:59.096 --> 03:09:06.646
sudden turn to conquest again after a long
period of more or less defensive war. 955,

03:09:06.816 --> 03:09:10.356
there's a new military
leadership is appointed, and

03:09:10.876 --> 03:09:14.716
the Romans go conquering
again, especially in Cilicia,

03:09:14.956 --> 03:09:20.216
northern Syria, and Cyprus, and the
Caucasus, and then eventually also Bulgaria.

03:09:22.316 --> 03:09:26.196
And then right afterwards,
they have this generation plus

03:09:26.416 --> 03:09:30.316
period of stability and prosperity, and

03:09:30.356 --> 03:09:33.896
then they're hit by a triple
whammy. These are three new

03:09:33.956 --> 03:09:37.816
attackers. So it's primarily the
Seljuk Turks coming in from the

03:09:37.876 --> 03:09:41.576
east, some Pechenegs coming down
from the north over the Danube,

03:09:42.476 --> 03:09:46.576
And the Normans in southern Italy.

03:09:47.136 --> 03:09:52.060
And under the pressure of
this three-part attack, the,

03:09:52.980 --> 03:09:58.620
you know, this expansionist what had
become more imperial state buckles.

03:09:58.940 --> 03:10:02.460
And enters another one of these
crises, just like the one we

03:10:02.500 --> 03:10:09.090
described for the seventh century. You
know, survives it by the skin of its teeth.

03:10:09.320 --> 03:10:13.230
And goes on again to rebuild and become
prosperous, wealthy, and powerful

03:10:13.300 --> 03:10:15.740
again, as it does throughout its history.

03:10:15.780 --> 03:10:21.320
It's these cycles. So I just wanted
to describe that iteration of that-

03:10:21.330 --> 03:10:24.660
... that process, and that's
what I do in that book.

03:10:25.020 --> 03:10:32.120
- So I think the traditional view, In
this perfect storm of the 11th century

03:10:33.740 --> 03:10:38.360
is that it was more to do with the
internal sort of moral decay and,

03:10:39.500 --> 03:10:42.940
Civilian emperors neglecting
the army, this internal stuff.

03:10:43.580 --> 03:10:46.940
And you make the case that
it's the external stuff, the

03:10:47.060 --> 03:10:49.800
three-prong attack, like you
said, Normans in the west,

03:10:50.700 --> 03:10:58.200
the Turkic steppe people in the north, and
in Central Asia, the Turks in the east.

03:10:58.680 --> 03:11:02.550
Can you describe that, the three
forces in the case that that was the

03:11:02.600 --> 03:11:05.300
main reason why it hit a low?

03:11:05.800 --> 03:11:09.780
- Well, this is also a methodological problem,
right? In other words, when you're looking

03:11:09.800 --> 03:11:13.500
at a society that suddenly faces a bunch
of problems, and you could, you know,

03:11:13.760 --> 03:11:18.860
reasonably make the case for a kind of
decline or a crisis, is your instinct,

03:11:19.720 --> 03:11:23.380
it's your first instinct to suppose that
there must be something wrong in the

03:11:23.420 --> 03:11:27.300
internal mechanisms of that society
that, you know, led it to fail,

03:11:28.720 --> 03:11:31.730
which is what my field
has done traditionally.

03:11:31.730 --> 03:11:35.250
Uh, in part because of the decline
and fall model, right, of this

03:11:35.300 --> 03:11:39.850
society, we're kind of primed to think
that there was something wrong with it.

03:11:40.000 --> 03:11:47.380
It's a long story. Or is it
reasonable to say that a society

03:11:47.440 --> 03:11:53.160
that does not seem to have any, like,
particularly serious structural flaws

03:11:54.360 --> 03:11:58.200
is hit by external, you
know, challenges that it

03:11:58.480 --> 03:12:02.400
couldn't realistically have foreseen
or prepared for such that, you

03:12:02.440 --> 03:12:05.489
know, it, it couldn't cope with
them and, as I said, buckled.

03:12:06.480 --> 03:12:10.000
And I think that's what
happened. I think that's the,

03:12:10.120 --> 03:12:14.840
main narrative. Not that there
weren't problems. There were. But

03:12:16.220 --> 03:12:21.220
no state can, I mean, medieval or
ancient, can realistically survive

03:12:22.080 --> 03:12:25.739
the simultaneous attack of
three very different kinds of

03:12:25.800 --> 03:12:29.680
enemies, the Normans or,
like, these knights...

03:12:29.840 --> 03:12:33.480
Like a new type of Western warfare
that is just all about, you know,

03:12:33.620 --> 03:12:37.180
grinding the enemy to
bits. But who are also

03:12:37.240 --> 03:12:39.900
terrorists. Like, they're
straight up terrorists.

03:12:40.200 --> 03:12:41.800
- Normans are fascinating
because, I mean, there's...

03:12:41.810 --> 03:12:43.100
... there's a Viking component too-

03:12:43.240 --> 03:12:43.369
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.

03:12:43.369 --> 03:12:44.020
- ... with the Normans.

03:12:44.200 --> 03:12:44.620
- Yeah, yeah.

03:12:44.649 --> 03:12:49.880
- That's a whole... So they have, they
have three different kinds of enemies.

03:12:50.080 --> 03:12:53.700
- Yes. The Pechenegs, who's, you know, a, a

03:12:53.760 --> 03:12:57.980
totally different type of, you know,
probably mostly nomadic horsemen.

03:12:58.960 --> 03:13:02.840
And then the Seljuk Turks who are

03:13:03.220 --> 03:13:07.000
also mostly nomadic horsemen, but
who are coming in from Central Asia

03:13:07.020 --> 03:13:10.820
with vast reserves of manpower
behind them. In fact,

03:13:10.880 --> 03:13:18.400
either intending to or, as it happens,
effecting a demographic change in not just

03:13:18.420 --> 03:13:22.240
demographic, but ecological too,
because they basically, when they

03:13:22.280 --> 03:13:25.660
move into Asia Minor, they're
transforming or terraforming,

03:13:26.260 --> 03:13:29.380
Agricultural land into pasturage.

03:13:29.760 --> 03:13:32.780
And, and they're just backed
by reserves of manpower

03:13:32.880 --> 03:13:38.200
that no other enemy of
the empire has had yet.

03:13:38.460 --> 03:13:42.280
Uh, so yeah, how do you, how do you cope with
these situations? I mean, they're, it's very,

03:13:42.340 --> 03:13:46.200
very difficult, and it's a wonder that they
survived it at all. Now, they also have

03:13:46.240 --> 03:13:50.100
internal problems, and I'm not gonna sort
of try to sweep these under the rug,

03:13:50.180 --> 03:13:54.560
right? In particular, we're
seeing the end of the Macedonian

03:13:54.620 --> 03:14:00.060
dynasty. This is a dynasty that had
lasted for about two centuries, and

03:14:01.280 --> 03:14:05.180
this has a kind of politically
destabilizing effect. New

03:14:05.260 --> 03:14:08.420
emperors, and there are a lot of, like,
childless old men in this period,

03:14:09.100 --> 03:14:13.040
are relatively insecure. They don't have
this sort of a dynastic glitz behind

03:14:13.100 --> 03:14:16.760
them, and so they're tending to,
to buy a lot of political support,

03:14:17.180 --> 03:14:21.120
like hand out these exemptions,
give cash, you know, titles to

03:14:21.160 --> 03:14:25.000
anyone who will support them, and this, of
course, causes a budget problem. Like, they

03:14:25.040 --> 03:14:29.000
don't have enough money after a while. And then they have
to start raising all of these armies to deal with all of

03:14:29.040 --> 03:14:32.920
these problems, and that just increases
the pressure on the budget, and

03:14:32.980 --> 03:14:35.220
so there is an internal
problem as well, yeah.

03:14:36.120 --> 03:14:42.540
- So you mentioned this loop of
thriving and then having to survive,

03:14:42.660 --> 03:14:47.080
surviving, that happens a few times- ...
throughout the history of the Roman Empire.

03:14:48.020 --> 03:14:50.970
It seems that societies in
general oscillate in that way.

03:14:52.260 --> 03:14:56.050
Is there something particular you
could say about the oscillations,

03:14:56.280 --> 03:14:58.240
the loops that the Roman
Empire goes through?

03:14:59.460 --> 03:15:03.320
- Yes. Now, I don't think this is an oscillation.
At least that's not how I think of it in my own

03:15:03.360 --> 03:15:09.980
mind. Um, so as I explained,
the crises that this, this

03:15:10.220 --> 03:15:12.700
polity, this state, this
society that it undergoes

03:15:13.580 --> 03:15:17.440
are dis- there are a discrete
number of them. I can tell

03:15:17.500 --> 03:15:21.470
you what they are, and we've
talked about most of them so far.

03:15:21.480 --> 03:15:28.400
They don't last very long, and they
are all sudden challenges that appear

03:15:28.440 --> 03:15:31.290
from the outside. In other
words, they're exogenous shocks,

03:15:32.400 --> 03:15:35.520
that they can't really have prepared for.

03:15:36.560 --> 03:15:40.320
These shocks cause
massive territorial loss,

03:15:41.040 --> 03:15:44.920
which requires adjustment,
right? But they don't last

03:15:44.940 --> 03:15:48.620
that long. In other words, the
Romans almost always, at some point,

03:15:48.940 --> 03:15:54.040
figure out how to hold a line, how to
consolidate their position, regroup-

03:15:54.876 --> 03:16:00.456
and put their economy and their society
back on a trajectory of revival, regrowth,

03:16:01.416 --> 03:16:08.496
and eventual reconquest. Always. Every
single time, except the last time, right?

03:16:09.216 --> 03:16:14.656
And for me, this poses the
following kind of dilemma,

03:16:15.786 --> 03:16:19.406
which I can answer. And the
dilemma is, should we define the

03:16:19.476 --> 03:16:23.036
society by these brief
crises of exogenous shocks,

03:16:23.596 --> 03:16:27.336
or should we define it by the
centuries-long, sometimes,

03:16:27.496 --> 03:16:36.396
periods of regrowth, consolidation, and
stabilization, which are endogenous.

03:16:36.496 --> 03:16:39.196
Nobody came from the outside
to help them rebuild.

03:16:39.796 --> 03:16:43.636
Uh, and my answer is
unequivocally the latter. So

03:16:43.836 --> 03:16:51.266
I see this as a society whose internal
organization primes it to stabilize

03:16:51.796 --> 03:16:57.156
and embark on steady growth.
Slow and gradual, but steady.

03:16:58.196 --> 03:17:02.096
And that's what I would like my
field to explain more, and I'm

03:17:02.116 --> 03:17:05.716
gonna try to do so in the book
I mentioned that I'm writing

03:17:05.776 --> 03:17:09.666
on, like, the longevity or the
resilience of this society.

03:17:10.036 --> 03:17:13.566
And not try to center the crises,

03:17:13.936 --> 03:17:16.276
which I see as being from the
outside. Like, these aren't...

03:17:17.116 --> 03:17:20.046
Of course, they're part of its story,
but they're not coming from it.

03:17:20.276 --> 03:17:24.096
What's coming from it is the
stability, and I think that's the more

03:17:24.156 --> 03:17:25.576
interesting part of this society.

03:17:26.756 --> 03:17:30.846
- Yeah, so the, you know, these
peak-to-peak histories,

03:17:31.696 --> 03:17:35.406
as you can think of them, they miss the
machinery in the valleys. Institutions,

03:17:35.456 --> 03:17:39.196
incentives, daily life, all of these
things. The politics, the religion.

03:17:40.556 --> 03:17:44.206
You have a bunch of revisionist
history ideas in your work. You're

03:17:44.296 --> 03:17:45.316
challenging the field.

03:17:45.516 --> 03:17:46.946
- Yes. You could say that.

03:17:47.476 --> 03:17:51.436
- In the best possible way. So
just to linger on it, what

03:17:51.456 --> 03:17:55.376
are, what are some of the things that
historians miss? So this is a big one, right,

03:17:55.496 --> 03:17:59.456
that you're speaking to, which
is, like, focusing too much

03:17:59.496 --> 03:18:05.696
on specific moments versus on the
broad structural underpinnings

03:18:06.116 --> 03:18:07.876
of, of an empire, of a society.

03:18:08.396 --> 03:18:11.796
- Right. So what you alluded
to there is a critique

03:18:11.896 --> 03:18:15.816
of what we might call short histories
of Byzantium, which is a kind

03:18:15.856 --> 03:18:21.176
of genre of a book. Right? This isn't
necessarily, like, what my other

03:18:21.236 --> 03:18:24.996
revisionist ideas are about. The
more important ones are things

03:18:25.076 --> 03:18:28.846
like the monarchical republic that we
talked about. In other words, that there's

03:18:28.956 --> 03:18:32.366
actually a broader spectrum
of political participation.

03:18:32.656 --> 03:18:36.436
Um, that emperors are having to look over
their shoulders all the time. That there is a

03:18:36.496 --> 03:18:40.296
deeper matrix of Roman Republican
thought there. Like, that's one

03:18:40.336 --> 03:18:44.086
revisionist idea. Another
one is about Roman identity,

03:18:44.216 --> 03:18:45.516
just like who are these people?

03:18:45.576 --> 03:18:49.436
And no, they are Romans, and in fact,
it's kind of an ethnic identity after a

03:18:49.476 --> 03:18:52.255
certain point. Like, those kinds of ideas.

03:18:53.106 --> 03:18:56.636
The criticism of the peak
to peak kinds of books.

03:18:57.176 --> 03:19:01.116
So if you're trying to condense
1,200 years into 120 pages

03:19:01.196 --> 03:19:03.516
or even, you know, even 200 pages,

03:19:04.636 --> 03:19:08.496
there's no way to do so realistically
and give a sense of the whole

03:19:08.616 --> 03:19:12.296
terrain. In other words, what these
books do is they go, they jump from,

03:19:13.096 --> 03:19:16.976
from highlight to highlight, and these
highlights are sometimes things like,

03:19:17.156 --> 03:19:22.736
you know, everything Justinian did because
it's so extravagant, to the crises.

03:19:22.836 --> 03:19:26.196
The crises are, of course, dramatic
moments that you can't skip.

03:19:27.156 --> 03:19:31.126
And you can't get a sense
from these books as to

03:19:31.196 --> 03:19:34.936
how all of this is interconnected
in the valleys, right?

03:19:34.996 --> 03:19:38.726
In the crags, down there. Like,
what are the mechanisms that are

03:19:38.736 --> 03:19:42.596
connecting these peaks together?
And that's how I tried to write

03:19:42.606 --> 03:19:46.216
the big history, The New Roman
Empire, is to tell the story by

03:19:46.276 --> 03:19:50.236
casting light in those darker
places. That is, to show how

03:19:50.296 --> 03:19:54.036
especially institutions
and ideologies sort of

03:19:54.116 --> 03:19:58.106
tie, you know, people's
lives together. That

03:19:58.136 --> 03:20:01.426
is, tie people to institutions and to
the broader history that surrounds

03:20:01.476 --> 03:20:05.296
them. So that the reader
can get a sense when

03:20:05.336 --> 03:20:09.536
I'm, when I'm recounting specific
events or either of, you know,

03:20:10.876 --> 03:20:15.616
greatness or of a success or a
failure, that they can understand

03:20:16.576 --> 03:20:20.296
roughly why these things are happening,
right? Look, there's no perfect

03:20:20.376 --> 03:20:23.996
answer. A short book will just not
tell you these things. A long book,

03:20:24.396 --> 03:20:25.856
well, is a long book.

03:20:26.016 --> 03:20:29.976
- Well, in some sense, I mean, this, in this, even
in this very conversation, I think we did a pretty

03:20:30.036 --> 03:20:34.076
good job of looking at the valleys, at
the structure, at the institutions.

03:20:34.086 --> 03:20:36.816
And that gives you a sense
of the whole underpinnings.

03:20:36.876 --> 03:20:40.316
And so it's, it's beautiful. It's a
beautiful way to see history, especially for

03:20:40.396 --> 03:20:44.816
societies that have lasted as long as-
... as the, as the East Roman Empire has.

03:20:44.936 --> 03:20:46.235
- But it did take us a few hours.

03:20:46.676 --> 03:20:46.876
- Yes.

03:20:46.936 --> 03:20:52.056
- Yes. You're right. But it requires
that you actually spend some

03:20:52.096 --> 03:20:53.605
time to look in there, yeah.

03:20:53.736 --> 03:20:55.456
- What's, what's a few hours among friends?

03:20:55.516 --> 03:20:57.256
- No, no, no, that's... I agree.

03:20:58.916 --> 03:21:02.136
- Uh, so zooming out and asking once again,

03:21:03.216 --> 03:21:06.996
the old we're getting a little
close to last call at a bar,

03:21:07.256 --> 03:21:10.516
I'm gonna ask you the big question.
We asked it before about the

03:21:10.596 --> 03:21:15.136
collapse of the West Roman Empire.

03:21:15.956 --> 03:21:25.516
When did the decline of the East Roman
Empire begin for you? Throughout this loops,

03:21:26.416 --> 03:21:32.896
when, if you were to predict, Would you be
able to say where this is gonna be over?

03:21:33.896 --> 03:21:37.776
And what led to that decline and the

03:21:37.836 --> 03:21:44.256
collapse? So of course, the
collapse is finally in 1453 AD.

03:21:44.596 --> 03:21:49.016
- Right. That's actually a very good
question. In other words, um,

03:21:50.176 --> 03:21:53.776
not looking at all of the previous
crises that caused loss of territory,

03:21:54.316 --> 03:21:58.056
like, you know, you lose Egypt, you lose
Syria, you lose Palestine, you lose

03:21:58.116 --> 03:22:01.900
Eastern Asia Minor, you lo- right?
But at what point could you

03:22:01.920 --> 03:22:04.440
say there's no coming back from this?

03:22:04.560 --> 03:22:10.390
Right? I would say early 14th century.
Somewhere between 1300 and 1350,

03:22:11.280 --> 03:22:18.020
the sources of resilience begin to
dry up, and you have a number of

03:22:18.080 --> 03:22:23.720
setbacks. They lose Asia Minor
to the Turks by 1300, roughly,

03:22:24.560 --> 03:22:28.520
which means that you can
now no longer draw upon the

03:22:28.640 --> 03:22:32.590
two wings, as it were,
the European side and

03:22:32.620 --> 03:22:35.970
the Asian side, which they could
always do. They're confined to Europe.

03:22:36.740 --> 03:22:40.680
And then you have a series of
civil wars, you have the Serbian

03:22:40.700 --> 03:22:48.020
expansion and you have the Black Death,
and they never recover from that.

03:22:48.900 --> 03:22:52.520
In 1300, you think of this, you
look at it and you think, "That's a

03:22:52.600 --> 03:22:54.400
tiny little Balkan state."

03:22:54.780 --> 03:22:58.690
Okay, it goes from Constantinople
to the Adriatic in this

03:22:58.740 --> 03:23:02.730
just sort of ribbon, right, this,
this corridor that just stretches

03:23:03.140 --> 03:23:07.820
across the Balkans. And yet, it's
not that much smaller than England

03:23:09.040 --> 03:23:12.940
and has about as much, if not more,
revenue, because they're still able

03:23:13.000 --> 03:23:14.860
to raise cash, because taxes.

03:23:15.710 --> 03:23:19.740
Right? So the emperor's still able
to pull in a lot of gold. Um,

03:23:20.920 --> 03:23:24.480
and his territory is not, you
know, completely insignificant.

03:23:24.520 --> 03:23:28.490
It's not what it, you know, the Roman Empire
used to be. But I don't think that it's

03:23:28.520 --> 03:23:32.260
completely lost. Then they
have some civil wars. Then one

03:23:32.320 --> 03:23:35.920
emperor- um, a rebel makes a deal
with the Serbs, surrenders half that

03:23:35.960 --> 03:23:38.310
territory. Okay, after that, game over.

03:23:39.420 --> 03:23:44.340
What's surprising is it takes the Turks
that long. 1453, that's another century.

03:23:44.460 --> 03:23:48.320
Right? It didn't need to be.
It looks like they might have

03:23:48.360 --> 03:23:53.100
had it wrapped up like 50 years
after- uh, you know, like by 1400.

03:23:54.000 --> 03:23:58.700
But then accidental events happened.
This is Timur, Tamerlane comes-

03:23:58.710 --> 03:24:02.660
... from Central Asia, trounces the
Turks, breaks up their empire. So they go

03:24:02.720 --> 03:24:06.260
into a cycle of, you know, rebuilding,
and so that's why it takes

03:24:06.340 --> 03:24:11.819
another 50 years. Anyway, but
I'd say by the 1340s, game over.

03:24:12.600 --> 03:24:19.260
- And so why did it collapse? What are the
things in the ground, when you zoom out,

03:24:20.500 --> 03:24:25.840
the thing that ate away at the, I like
this term, sources of resilience?

03:24:26.320 --> 03:24:28.840
- Oh, foreign invasions. There's
no question. It's just-

03:24:28.850 --> 03:24:29.449
- It's just invasions

03:24:29.460 --> 03:24:33.420
- ...it's foreign invasions,
those which they could

03:24:33.460 --> 03:24:36.040
not cope with. They
coped with lots of them.

03:24:37.140 --> 03:24:40.900
But, you know, it, all it
takes is to lose to one,

03:24:41.100 --> 03:24:44.400
and you lose some part of your territory.
And if you keep losing enough,

03:24:45.780 --> 03:24:48.940
you won't have anything to fall
back on, and that's what happens.

03:24:49.620 --> 03:24:55.240
- So really, you know, if there's no
significant external invasions,

03:24:56.320 --> 03:25:01.840
the East Roman Empire, the
fundamentals, the taxation system,

03:25:03.340 --> 03:25:07.260
the way the, the policies were developed,
the way the politics was done, the way

03:25:07.300 --> 03:25:10.740
the representation was done, all of
that, this empire could have lasted

03:25:12.100 --> 03:25:14.000
for another thousand years.

03:25:14.080 --> 03:25:18.800
- Absolutely. I'm absolutely
convinced of this because

03:25:20.680 --> 03:25:24.120
you never see movements to split away.

03:25:24.940 --> 03:25:28.729
That is, there's no separatist
movements, at least not on the part of

03:25:28.760 --> 03:25:32.740
any Roman provincials. There's one
separatist movement, which is Bulgaria.

03:25:32.780 --> 03:25:36.700
We mentioned Bulgaria was
conquered, right, in 1018. There's

03:25:36.740 --> 03:25:39.940
a couple of independentist
movements rebellions. Um,

03:25:40.320 --> 03:25:43.880
eventually one succeeds in 1185,
so just under two centuries.

03:25:44.260 --> 03:25:46.720
So Bulgaria is the only
part of this empire that

03:25:47.560 --> 03:25:49.860
actively seeks to break away and does so.

03:25:50.840 --> 03:25:54.720
But for the rest of the 1,200 years,
you don't find provincials wanting

03:25:54.729 --> 03:25:57.870
to leave this system. However much
they complain about the taxes,

03:25:58.780 --> 03:26:02.680
they don't want to leave, and they make
no move to do so. You also never have

03:26:02.780 --> 03:26:09.640
a moment when the center loses its
ability to tax its territories,

03:26:10.300 --> 03:26:14.200
right? You don't have, like,
widespread peasant uprisings or

03:26:14.260 --> 03:26:17.630
provinc- or, right, agricultural
rebellions or these kinds of things,

03:26:18.400 --> 03:26:22.359
Which happens in every other one of
these empires. They also never decide

03:26:22.400 --> 03:26:25.960
to partition it. The Franks partition
theirs, right, like after Charlemagne.

03:26:26.760 --> 03:26:29.940
No. There are no, like, Roman

03:26:30.080 --> 03:26:33.640
warlords that try to carve out
a piece of the territory for

03:26:33.680 --> 03:26:37.640
themselves and rule it independent.
Nope, that doesn't happen either. So

03:26:37.740 --> 03:26:41.680
if you're looking at the kinds of
factors that cause states to fail,

03:26:41.860 --> 03:26:46.460
fragment, you know, become
ungovernable, these never happen.

03:26:47.000 --> 03:26:50.560
- This is so incredible.
This is truly incredible.

03:26:51.520 --> 03:26:55.460
In the history of human civilization,
just an incredible study of

03:26:55.480 --> 03:26:59.190
what human societies can
form. So, so what, what,

03:26:59.840 --> 03:27:04.340
what, what are the whys? Why?
Why? Why was it so stable?

03:27:04.420 --> 03:27:06.810
- Well, now look, there are other
stable... Like, for example,

03:27:08.420 --> 03:27:11.640
The, the British monarchy. That's
been around for quite a while.

03:27:11.770 --> 03:27:11.890
- Yeah, that's true.

03:27:12.040 --> 03:27:17.220
- Right? States like Portugal, Japan,
they have one thing in common.

03:27:18.450 --> 03:27:19.880
They're all tucked away at the edges.

03:27:20.940 --> 03:27:23.560
Like, they're off, they're little islands
or whatever. They're not like, right?

03:27:24.320 --> 03:27:27.410
We're talking about a society
that was right in the-

03:27:27.410 --> 03:27:28.320
- In the, yeah

03:27:28.420 --> 03:27:31.980
- ... middle of one of the main corridors
of empire building and new religions

03:27:32.540 --> 03:27:36.480
in the world. This is the most
dangerous neighborhood, right,

03:27:36.540 --> 03:27:38.570
that you can possibly live in.

03:27:38.660 --> 03:27:42.540
So no wonder it didn't
survive. Like it would've been

03:27:42.580 --> 03:27:46.400
extraordinary if it had.
But absent those forces,

03:27:47.580 --> 03:27:51.280
I don't see any forces of internal

03:27:51.400 --> 03:27:56.420
decomposition that would have
imperiled it, you know, significantly.

03:27:56.480 --> 03:28:00.180
- So what, I mean we've talked about a
lot of it, but what, just to, like,

03:28:00.260 --> 03:28:04.860
return to it, why was there no internal

03:28:05.992 --> 03:28:09.732
sources of decomposition. Like
why, why did it work so well?

03:28:09.892 --> 03:28:13.252
Why did the people feel represented?
Yes, they— By the way, you talked about

03:28:14.032 --> 03:28:17.672
how they complain about the taxes, which is
one of the signs of a healthy society, that

03:28:17.712 --> 03:28:21.632
we... It's like complaining about the weather.
The fact that you complain about the taxes

03:28:21.712 --> 03:28:25.692
actually means that you're happy with the taxes,
kind of counterintuitively, or it's not too

03:28:25.752 --> 03:28:28.472
bad. You're just complaining
as part of the system.

03:28:28.492 --> 03:28:33.092
Anyway, but why? Why, why did it work
so well? Why did everybody get along—

03:28:33.392 --> 03:28:33.522
- Oh, no, they—

03:28:33.522 --> 03:28:38.041
- ... feel represented? No, not get
along. Not in a, in a silly way.

03:28:38.072 --> 03:28:41.972
I mean, sufficiently to where they
wouldn't... Warlords wouldn't

03:28:42.032 --> 03:28:44.032
rise and break apart the system and—

03:28:44.212 --> 03:28:48.272
... or if there was those kinds of
forces, they would come back together.

03:28:48.332 --> 03:28:50.842
Like, why is this such a
great self-healing system?

03:28:51.272 --> 03:28:55.132
- So you're exactly right. So sufficient is the
key word. We don't want to idealize this,

03:28:55.252 --> 03:28:59.112
right? These aren't, like, they're not just
dancing in the streets, holding hands and then

03:28:59.152 --> 03:29:02.412
direct... It's so— Even when
it comes to the tax system,

03:29:02.632 --> 03:29:06.612
they are complaining all the time. Of
course, they're doing so because they know

03:29:06.632 --> 03:29:08.812
that complaining gets you things.

03:29:08.952 --> 03:29:12.812
There's no disincentive to complaining. You might
not get what you want, or you might get it,

03:29:12.892 --> 03:29:16.752
but you know, no harm will come to
you. So they're complaining all the

03:29:16.852 --> 03:29:20.792
time. They have all of these civil
wars. They're like, "Okay." Um,

03:29:21.592 --> 03:29:25.372
so I think I would give
you a two-part answer, so

03:29:25.972 --> 03:29:28.812
really quickly, as to why
this held together so well.

03:29:30.052 --> 03:29:33.672
First is that an extraordinary effort was

03:29:33.752 --> 03:29:37.632
made by the authorities to persuade
their subjects that they were

03:29:37.672 --> 03:29:41.572
ruling on their behalf, and
I think, for the most part,

03:29:41.692 --> 03:29:45.472
actually tended to do so.
And the second is that it

03:29:45.552 --> 03:29:49.452
had a very tightly unified identity

03:29:49.552 --> 03:29:53.272
as Roman and as Orthodox. In
other words, for the most,

03:29:53.792 --> 03:29:58.812
most time, they knew that they were surrounded
by enemies who were not those things.

03:29:58.822 --> 03:30:02.612
And they did not want to live
under the power of non-Romans and

03:30:02.632 --> 03:30:07.952
non-Christian people. And so those two
factors combined, I think, gave everybody

03:30:08.752 --> 03:30:12.552
reason to hold it together.
The alternatives were worse.

03:30:13.312 --> 03:30:17.292
- Yeah. I mean, that's a really brilliant
summary, and I think we should mention

03:30:17.302 --> 03:30:20.682
that both the rhetoric and the
action are important. I think you've

03:30:20.732 --> 03:30:27.052
articulated that rhetoric is really powerful,
like stating over and over and over-

03:30:27.061 --> 03:30:30.772
... that you represent the people, that
you're acting on behalf of the people and

03:30:30.872 --> 03:30:34.712
doing the action. But it's not enough to actually
do the action. You would think that's all

03:30:34.752 --> 03:30:37.412
Machiavelli says that's the only
thing that matters. But no.

03:30:37.592 --> 03:30:42.432
It's the rhetoric actually has a lot of
power- ... because it is a uniting idea-

03:30:42.452 --> 03:30:46.412
... an ideal that propagates through
time, and it pacifies you. It

03:30:46.552 --> 03:30:49.752
makes you, it puts you at
peace. Rhetoric is important.

03:30:50.032 --> 03:30:54.612
- I'll give you an example. As an
academic administrator, right?

03:30:54.932 --> 03:30:57.221
I mean, I was chair of a
department for years and years.

03:30:58.352 --> 03:31:07.292
There's a difference between a dean who
says, "Sorry, bad budget situation. We're

03:31:07.372 --> 03:31:12.392
just going to have to cut your programs,"
on the one hand, and a dean who says,

03:31:13.852 --> 03:31:17.692
"I am fully on board with what
you're trying to accomplish with

03:31:17.712 --> 03:31:22.672
these programs. I am a defender
of the humanities. Unfortunately,

03:31:23.552 --> 03:31:27.212
we have this budget situation, and we're going
to have to cut some of the programs. But

03:31:27.612 --> 03:31:31.962
I assure you, the moment I'm
in this with you together-

03:31:32.012 --> 03:31:34.372
... the moment we find the
funds, we will restore them."

03:31:35.672 --> 03:31:41.192
Those two just rhetorical strategies, they're
aiming at the same practical outcome,

03:31:42.092 --> 03:31:46.612
will produce very different levels of
compliance- ... right, and consensus.

03:31:47.112 --> 03:31:48.732
- And I should say that
there's subtlety there.

03:31:49.602 --> 03:31:54.712
The best rhetoric in that context,
and maybe in the East Roman Empire,

03:31:55.572 --> 03:31:56.932
is you also have to believe it.

03:31:57.492 --> 03:32:00.512
- Yes. It has to be credible. You can't
just say it and then not do it.

03:32:00.712 --> 03:32:04.572
- But one of the things I've learned about
humans, just having, doing this little podcast,

03:32:05.172 --> 03:32:09.112
is that people could-- Like,
the best way to say a thing,

03:32:09.952 --> 03:32:12.682
a powerful thing, is to really believe it.

03:32:12.732 --> 03:32:16.212
And so, like, this is clearly
one of the things that made

03:32:16.992 --> 03:32:23.372
the Roman Empire work, is doing the
action is the best way to make the

03:32:23.532 --> 03:32:26.212
rhetoric powerful and effective.

03:32:26.352 --> 03:32:29.952
- Yeah. This is sort of what
Aristotle says about tyrants.

03:32:30.792 --> 03:32:34.732
In The Politics, Aristotle's giving essentially
advice to tyrants on how to protect

03:32:34.772 --> 03:32:38.492
themselves because tyrants are usually
hated and are killed in coups,

03:32:38.572 --> 03:32:42.552
right? And he says, "Well, how-- You
know, essentially, how do you manage

03:32:42.572 --> 03:32:47.932
to secure yourself when you're a
tyrant?" Well, you know, you can start

03:32:48.982 --> 03:32:52.912
by maybe, you know, obeying the laws
or making sure that your subjects obey

03:32:52.972 --> 03:32:56.832
the laws and, you know, maybe work for
the interests of yourself. Essentially,

03:32:56.872 --> 03:32:59.772
he's telling them to kind
of become benevolent kings.

03:33:00.572 --> 03:33:04.522
And the best way to persuade your subjects
that you're legitimate, benevolent

03:33:04.522 --> 03:33:07.632
kings is to be that.

03:33:08.732 --> 03:33:14.092
- So what, from all of this, from this
2,200-year history of the Roman Empire,

03:33:14.952 --> 03:33:20.652
what lessons can we draw for modern
times? Now we're sitting in America, this

03:33:21.692 --> 03:33:25.832
young empire. I know we're not
calling it an empire, but, you know.

03:33:26.032 --> 03:33:29.532
- Lots of people are calling it an empire. I
thought it was sort of taboo. Yeah, in the 20th

03:33:29.572 --> 03:33:33.422
century, it was like, "Is America
an empire now?" But like, I

03:33:33.472 --> 03:33:41.412
think since the Iraq War, like since 2003,
I've seen at least very casual uses of

03:33:41.492 --> 03:33:45.392
America and empire in the same, you
know, sentence without any kind of

03:33:45.452 --> 03:33:45.992
hand-wringing.

03:33:46.272 --> 03:33:48.652
- Is it ever called that
in a academic setting?

03:33:49.032 --> 03:33:49.072
- Yes.

03:33:49.092 --> 03:33:50.932
- I mean, it's technically,
I guess you could say-

03:33:50.992 --> 03:33:51.192
- Oh, yeah

03:33:51.352 --> 03:33:55.582
- ... given, given the expanse
of the military bases and,

03:33:56.652 --> 03:34:00.492
and the military might and
and the way that represents

03:34:00.512 --> 03:34:02.392
itself in the geopolitical context.

03:34:02.512 --> 03:34:04.992
- There are books published all
the time that unironically

03:34:06.072 --> 03:34:09.572
Discuss America as an empire
in various ways. Yeah, no.

03:34:09.652 --> 03:34:11.191
- By the way, both positive and negative.

03:34:11.232 --> 03:34:15.202
So when you're saying a positive thing about America,
calling it an empire, and when you're saying it

03:34:15.572 --> 03:34:18.512
to criticize America, you call it
an empire. Yeah, you're right.

03:34:18.572 --> 03:34:22.152
- Yeah. I mean, most academic books aren't trying to
do, like, either. They're just trying to analyze a

03:34:22.172 --> 03:34:24.302
situation.

03:34:24.332 --> 03:34:31.072
- What lessons about, about representing
the people, about flourishing,

03:34:32.312 --> 03:34:33.992
about stability can we draw?

03:34:34.332 --> 03:34:39.632
- I will say that, just drawing on what
we were talking about a moment ago,

03:34:40.512 --> 03:34:45.612
that investing in institutions that
work for the majority of your subjects,

03:34:46.492 --> 03:34:50.332
even if indirectly, like they have to pay a
cost for them, but you have to explain to them

03:34:50.472 --> 03:34:56.692
why they're paying that cost, is to the
benefit of the ruling classes as well.

03:34:57.712 --> 03:35:00.832
Because you're-- ideally,
you're thinking about

03:35:01.272 --> 03:35:04.632
long-term success and not just your own

03:35:04.752 --> 03:35:08.542
short-term, you know, gain. And
I think that's what this society

03:35:08.812 --> 03:35:12.712
tends to do well. You know, the Romans generally,
you know how they built roads for the,

03:35:12.932 --> 03:35:16.832
the centuries and the millennia. They
built institutions too. You know,

03:35:16.892 --> 03:35:19.292
one of the institutions they built
was, like, the Christian Church.

03:35:20.092 --> 03:35:22.352
Like, they build things to last.

03:35:22.612 --> 03:35:26.292
Um, and I think that's a, that's a good
lesson beyond even the roads. I think

03:35:26.832 --> 03:35:32.012
institutions that explain, you
know, to people why they exist,

03:35:32.892 --> 03:35:37.412
is... Yeah, I think we could
we could use some of that.

03:35:37.432 --> 03:35:41.322
- And also the first point you made
about the East Roman Empire. I think

03:35:41.352 --> 03:35:45.272
you've said that US foreign
policy sometimes has a, quite a

03:35:45.372 --> 03:35:50.292
large gap between the rhetoric and the in
modern times, the rhetoric and the action.

03:35:50.592 --> 03:35:51.062
- Oh, yeah. Yeah.

03:35:51.062 --> 03:35:54.592
- And so that's to the Machiavelli's
point that we want to

03:35:54.672 --> 03:35:59.052
maybe narrow that gap for a successful
empire, for a successful nation.

03:35:59.892 --> 03:36:01.832
The rhetoric has to match the action.

03:36:03.032 --> 03:36:03.192
- Yes.

03:36:03.222 --> 03:36:09.892
- And it doesn't quite for some of the
foreign policy engagements in the world.

03:36:10.212 --> 03:36:14.192
- So in the context of the society
I study, let's say the army

03:36:14.212 --> 03:36:17.672
is the single largest expense,
is doing pretty much what

03:36:18.532 --> 03:36:21.852
the emperors say that it's doing,
which is protecting its subjects.

03:36:21.912 --> 03:36:25.632
That's actually what it's doing most
of the time. Not all the time. So, for

03:36:25.692 --> 03:36:29.512
example, emperors will sometimes
take the armies out on a

03:36:29.572 --> 03:36:33.472
raid or an expedition, you know,
crack some skulls, gather some

03:36:33.512 --> 03:36:37.462
plunder, come back, and this is done to glorify
the emperor. Like, yeah. Yeah, yeah, this,

03:36:37.592 --> 03:36:42.852
this does happen. But for the most part,
they're doing that, not much else.

03:36:43.332 --> 03:36:46.852
And actually, in pre-modern
context, it's very difficult to

03:36:46.992 --> 03:36:50.832
operate like, you know, shadow
foreign policies and things like

03:36:50.892 --> 03:36:53.092
this. Like, it's just not part of the-

03:36:53.212 --> 03:37:00.632
... It's not in the cards. But
America in particular has such

03:37:00.712 --> 03:37:04.552
a history of proclaiming
the loftiest goals.

03:37:05.852 --> 03:37:10.692
It just, sometimes just, you
know, breathtakingly implausible.

03:37:11.392 --> 03:37:15.092
- Plus the incredible engineering behind
the military industrial complex, so

03:37:15.132 --> 03:37:18.812
America's very good at creating-
... to the flamethrowers.

03:37:19.832 --> 03:37:20.072
- Yes.

03:37:20.452 --> 03:37:25.612
- The technologies— ... of war, and
so the lofty goals combined with

03:37:25.712 --> 03:37:27.932
just a lot of profit
that could be made on-

03:37:27.972 --> 03:37:31.962
... the technologies of war creates a very
difficult situation to navigate, where

03:37:32.012 --> 03:37:33.792
the gap naturally widens.

03:37:34.522 --> 03:37:38.362
- Yeah. I don't think most of the
world even believes, you know, what

03:37:38.652 --> 03:37:42.792
American leaders say their goals are,
especially when it comes to, like, war.

03:37:43.832 --> 03:37:45.612
Like spreading democracy? No, really?

03:37:46.672 --> 03:37:50.112
I remember when they were
trying to convince me,

03:37:51.312 --> 03:37:56.192
us, that the invasion of
Afghanistan was a feminist war.

03:37:57.152 --> 03:37:58.012
- Oh, that was a thing, huh?

03:37:58.432 --> 03:38:02.212
- Oh, yes. They were to liberate the women
from the burqas or whatever, and, like,

03:38:02.492 --> 03:38:06.232
the news was just flooded with, like, how
terrible women have it in Afghanistan.

03:38:06.272 --> 03:38:09.852
It's like, you're really trying to
persuade me that that's why you're

03:38:09.912 --> 03:38:13.572
sending armed forces— like... Anyway.

03:38:13.632 --> 03:38:17.592
- I think there's a lot, a lot of wake-up calls about
the war in Afghanistan and Iraq, where people

03:38:17.632 --> 03:38:21.842
realized that there is that gap
between the rhetoric and the action.

03:38:21.852 --> 03:38:26.401
And I mean, that's how, because of
a lot of people waking up to that,

03:38:27.362 --> 03:38:32.032
they create pressure on the government
to close that gap, and that's—

03:38:32.042 --> 03:38:34.022
... how we kind of navigate this—

03:38:34.022 --> 03:38:37.412
... complicated world, but it's a
costly one. I mean, these, these were

03:38:37.492 --> 03:38:41.652
extremely costly wars— ... on
every front, on every measure.

03:38:42.392 --> 03:38:45.142
- Yep, but the same lesson was
learned in, like, the Vietnam War,

03:38:46.172 --> 03:38:48.702
and that was such a disaster that

03:38:49.932 --> 03:38:53.542
essentially they had to switch to--
abandon the conscript army, switch to a

03:38:53.552 --> 03:38:57.452
professional army. And,
like, it took them so long

03:38:57.692 --> 03:39:01.432
to be able to, like, wage, you
know, these empire wars again

03:39:02.192 --> 03:39:05.952
because of the sheer damage that the
Vietnam War did to the credibility

03:39:06.032 --> 03:39:09.772
of the military leadership
in the country, right? This

03:39:09.812 --> 03:39:13.772
never happens in, like, this
doesn't happen in Constantinople.

03:39:14.392 --> 03:39:18.162
I can lose a w-- You can be criticized for
losing a war. That's, that's one thing,

03:39:18.272 --> 03:39:22.992
right? But that you're using the army
to do some, like... You know. No.

03:39:23.432 --> 03:39:27.272
- Some of this does have to do
with the, the functioning of

03:39:28.492 --> 03:39:31.972
of how democracy works, the,
the temporary nature of the

03:39:32.052 --> 03:39:34.062
leaderships, and that they're very-

03:39:34.812 --> 03:39:39.712
... short-sighted because of the nature
of the elected position or the executive.

03:39:40.752 --> 03:39:44.622
I mean, that's what we're trying to figure out as
a human civilization, how to do this for, in this

03:39:44.632 --> 03:39:47.192
particular case, the democracy thing.

03:39:47.212 --> 03:39:51.092
- There's no right answer, and by the way, I don't
wanna be ruled by kings or monarchs or emperors

03:39:51.152 --> 03:39:55.092
either. So it's like I wouldn't
necessarily support that. I'm not

03:39:55.632 --> 03:39:59.032
advocating here for anything. I'm just
trying to explain. But you're exactly

03:39:59.072 --> 03:40:05.252
right. You know, we, we want democracy.
We want leaders whom we can eject

03:40:05.292 --> 03:40:06.812
every four or five years-

03:40:07.032 --> 03:40:10.632
... which includes sometimes their, their,
you know, teams of experts and policy

03:40:10.792 --> 03:40:13.632
designers and whatever, and
that comes at a cost too.

03:40:14.192 --> 03:40:17.900
- So you, you said that. You know, the
Roman Empire, maybe ancient Greece,

03:40:18.040 --> 03:40:24.100
maybe the societies before that, and
now societies after that, the society

03:40:24.200 --> 03:40:29.020
we live in are very different. And
so applying the lessons of history,

03:40:29.840 --> 03:40:34.720
you have to be careful doing so. But
are there things that are the same

03:40:35.920 --> 03:40:37.140
with us humans?

03:40:37.990 --> 03:40:41.710
So of everything you've studied across
hundreds of years and centuries,

03:40:42.200 --> 03:40:45.320
are there aspects of human
nature that kind of persist?

03:40:46.080 --> 03:40:49.270
- So look, intellectually,
I have gone through,

03:40:50.100 --> 03:40:53.440
periods when, like when
I was a grad student,

03:40:54.320 --> 03:40:58.250
it was, you know, this was kind
of when postmodernism, what

03:40:58.260 --> 03:41:02.160
we might call loosely, was kind
of alive and well and not-

03:41:02.220 --> 03:41:04.920
... had not yet been kicked in the pants.

03:41:05.020 --> 03:41:08.940
Um, it was very common
to find colleagues who

03:41:09.200 --> 03:41:13.120
did not believe that there was such a thing
as, let's say, human nature. In other

03:41:13.140 --> 03:41:16.180
words, that, let's say, the
parameters of human psychology

03:41:16.740 --> 03:41:20.560
are, you know, yes, there's considerable
variation, but they're within a certain set

03:41:20.640 --> 03:41:24.300
of, you know, norms. Like it's not--

03:41:25.380 --> 03:41:28.020
We're, we're not gonna behave
like different species.

03:41:29.020 --> 03:41:32.900
And, and that they did
not believe that there

03:41:32.940 --> 03:41:36.330
was such a thing. In other words, that
all of human history is essentially

03:41:36.880 --> 03:41:40.520
a series of incommensurate
slices of difference,

03:41:41.200 --> 03:41:45.160
right? That you just couldn't go from
one to the next. And I think it's a

03:41:45.220 --> 03:41:49.180
very problematic view for all kinds of reasons,
like how, how small do you slice these

03:41:49.240 --> 03:41:53.900
slices? I mean, it... And no,
I'm with Thucydides on this one-

03:41:53.980 --> 03:41:57.860
... Who says that, you know, more or less
human beings are gonna, more or less,

03:41:57.880 --> 03:42:01.520
they're, they're going to be act-- Right?
They love, and they hate, and they have

03:42:01.600 --> 03:42:05.580
ambitions, and they're incompetent,
and, you know, you find the whole

03:42:05.800 --> 03:42:08.540
range of, you know, the
whole gamut of diversity-

03:42:08.720 --> 03:42:12.640
... Pretty much in every, in any group of,
of about 20 or 30 people, you're gonna

03:42:12.720 --> 03:42:16.700
find the same kinds of types.
Now, culture then comes in and,

03:42:16.740 --> 03:42:20.720
you know, tweaks things in all kinds of weird
ways, and that's, as a historian, what I like

03:42:20.760 --> 03:42:27.540
to study. I like just how the culture
will modify, will set the dials, right?

03:42:27.810 --> 03:42:30.300
But that the dials go from
one to 10 most people-

03:42:30.349 --> 03:42:31.659
... it's like, yeah,
yeah, yeah, I think so.

03:42:31.880 --> 03:42:33.760
- But every once in a
while, there'll be a few,

03:42:35.300 --> 03:42:39.160
A few folks who come along, whether
it's Steve Jobs with a turtleneck

03:42:39.220 --> 03:42:43.160
or some guy with a weird mustache or

03:42:43.880 --> 03:42:47.560
with a funny hat, and those
can turn the tides of history.

03:42:47.700 --> 03:42:49.260
- I think so. Occasionally, yes.

03:42:49.440 --> 03:42:54.480
- But they're just ultra skilled at the
right time- ... at the right moment.

03:42:54.860 --> 03:42:58.800
- Oh, I believe that too. Oh, yeah. In
other words, I don't-- I also don't

03:42:58.840 --> 03:43:02.060
think that, that cultural
systems or ideologies are so

03:43:02.820 --> 03:43:06.600
effectively totalitarian that they sort
of colonize the mind of every person.

03:43:06.650 --> 03:43:10.320
And so everyone in a culture
is just like a clone. No, you

03:43:10.360 --> 03:43:13.060
encounter this sometimes in,
in historical scholarship.

03:43:13.500 --> 03:43:17.320
And, no, I think people can sometimes just think
for themselves, or they can think outside the

03:43:17.400 --> 03:43:20.980
box, and they can do all kinds of
things. And, and I always wanna keep my

03:43:21.520 --> 03:43:26.200
mind open to that possibility when I'm
encountering historical agents. Yeah.

03:43:26.240 --> 03:43:28.680
- So just because you've
seen this grand history,

03:43:29.560 --> 03:43:34.920
I apologize for the ridiculous question,
but if we look at the entirety of Earth,

03:43:35.840 --> 03:43:38.480
and we fast-forward a
million years from now-

03:43:39.360 --> 03:43:39.640
- Oof

03:43:40.720 --> 03:43:43.980
- ... and the, and the history
of life on Earth is written,

03:43:44.740 --> 03:43:48.840
do you think we're at the very
beginning of human history?

03:43:50.320 --> 03:43:53.880
Or is, are we in the middle,
or are we close to the end?

03:43:54.860 --> 03:44:01.010
- A million years from now. Um, I mean, I
can't project or predict anything like a

03:44:01.120 --> 03:44:01.760
year from now.

03:44:02.640 --> 03:44:06.620
And I've become actually increasingly
skeptical that I can do so at least.

03:44:07.320 --> 03:44:13.420
However, so I don't know about
beginning, middle, and end. Um, I--

03:44:14.240 --> 03:44:18.260
It's easier to think in terms
of like, like numbered phases.

03:44:18.340 --> 03:44:20.800
Like significantly different
phases of human history.

03:44:20.840 --> 03:44:24.530
And I would say we're probably in the third.
I think there've only been three phases.

03:44:25.220 --> 03:44:28.280
The first one being sort of
hunter-gatherer period, which--

03:44:28.880 --> 03:44:31.620
...that lasted for the majority
of human history so far.

03:44:31.880 --> 03:44:35.780
Right? Then there's the agricultural
revolution, basically. And

03:44:35.840 --> 03:44:39.960
this is when you start to produce surpluses
that create more complex societies.

03:44:40.940 --> 03:44:46.860
And we're now living through a technological--
first industrial, now, you know--

03:44:47.060 --> 03:44:48.460
- Yeah. You can throw it
all in the same bucket.

03:44:48.480 --> 03:44:48.590
- ...all kinds of tech--

03:44:48.620 --> 03:44:49.660
- Industrial, technological.

03:44:49.670 --> 03:44:53.660
- Yeah. Industrial, technological. Which
is modifying the parameters of what it

03:44:53.720 --> 03:44:56.420
is that human beings
can do and possibly be.

03:44:56.880 --> 03:45:00.920
And who knows where this will go.
But I see these as very distinct,

03:45:01.780 --> 03:45:04.430
In many ways. It's all human beings--

03:45:04.500 --> 03:45:05.510
- Yeah, it's all humans--

03:45:05.520 --> 03:45:06.100
- ...but very different contexts.

03:45:06.120 --> 03:45:11.340
- But they're almost modifying themselves.
So the question is, is there a fourth?

03:45:12.680 --> 03:45:13.150
Is there going to be a--

03:45:13.150 --> 03:45:14.120
- Yeah, I'm pretty sure there will be.

03:45:14.840 --> 03:45:18.800
- And what does that look like? And is
it-- When they look back at the third,

03:45:20.100 --> 03:45:22.640
would they still see us as the same

03:45:23.900 --> 03:45:27.160
as them, or would it be
something completely different?

03:45:28.360 --> 03:45:32.340
- Oh, no. I mean, we look back at the,
you know, Romans or the Greeks or,

03:45:32.500 --> 03:45:36.300
like, any period in history, and we're like,
"Yeah, no, I see what you're doing there.

03:45:36.380 --> 03:45:40.320
You're doing it with the, you know, the
technological capabilities that you had

03:45:40.360 --> 03:45:44.180
at that time. You're doing it with the materials
that you had. But I see what you're doing.

03:45:44.840 --> 03:45:48.580
Yeah. You've got, you've got families, and
you've got armies, and you've got, you know, you

03:45:48.660 --> 03:45:50.060
bury your dead, and you, you know."

03:45:50.240 --> 03:45:54.080
- Mm-hmm. But now we're
increasingly actually having the

03:45:54.120 --> 03:45:55.940
tools and technology to modify,

03:45:57.060 --> 03:46:00.840
to, like, deeply modify what it means
to be human. Genetic engineering,

03:46:01.480 --> 03:46:05.140
brain-computer interfaces. As we
understand the brain more, we can

03:46:05.200 --> 03:46:11.890
modify things, expand completely. Plus
artificial intelligence can expand the

03:46:12.760 --> 03:46:16.520
knowledge base and the intelligence
of the human mind. Unless

03:46:17.320 --> 03:46:21.180
we figure out the human mind is
actually incredibly special to the

03:46:21.220 --> 03:46:26.772
degree where it's-- At least with the
tools we have this century, we cannot

03:46:26.832 --> 03:46:30.412
accomplish, we cannot achieve the level--

03:46:30.472 --> 03:46:33.992
...of intelligence that-- general
intelligence that humans have.

03:46:34.492 --> 03:46:37.752
Or one of the things we might
figure out in stage four of

03:46:37.812 --> 03:46:41.652
this long history is that
the thing that makes humans

03:46:41.752 --> 03:46:45.632
special is not intelligence. It's
not any of the things we kind of

03:46:45.692 --> 03:46:48.192
value each other by. It's
actually consciousness,

03:46:49.252 --> 03:46:53.622
and consciousness is the thing that
is very difficult to engineer.

03:46:53.642 --> 03:46:56.492
And so that's the common thing
from the hunter-gatherers,

03:46:57.452 --> 03:47:01.372
to before the Industrial Revolution
and after, is we're still the same.

03:47:02.132 --> 03:47:05.432
We still feel like something to be alive,

03:47:06.032 --> 03:47:09.802
and that's maybe an important component
of what makes us fall in love with each

03:47:09.892 --> 03:47:13.672
other or fear each other or suffer and all

03:47:13.772 --> 03:47:16.952
the full range of the human
condition, the human experience.

03:47:16.992 --> 03:47:20.892
Maybe even technology cannot,
cannot replicate that, cannot

03:47:20.932 --> 03:47:23.712
modify that. Maybe
that's what we learn. Or

03:47:25.472 --> 03:47:28.492
very possibly we destroy this whole thing.

03:47:29.282 --> 03:47:32.152
'Cause now for the first time in
human history, we have the tools-

03:47:32.322 --> 03:47:32.342
- Yeah, yeah, we have

03:47:32.342 --> 03:47:34.772
- ... unfortunately, to destroy everything.

03:47:35.852 --> 03:47:37.282
- This is all very eloquent.

03:47:37.292 --> 03:47:41.132
I mean, after so many hours of my
rambling about the medieval Roman

03:47:41.172 --> 03:47:44.372
Empire, you're, you're--
Yeah. I'm impressed.

03:47:44.972 --> 03:47:47.512
- Okay. What gives you hope
about this whole thing,

03:47:48.532 --> 03:47:50.602
about the future of human civilization?

03:47:51.552 --> 03:47:55.502
- Look, there are a lot of
challenges, right, that we, that

03:47:55.532 --> 03:48:02.752
we face and we talk about them a lot. As
a historian, I see other periods that

03:48:02.792 --> 03:48:06.132
were far, far more difficult

03:48:06.832 --> 03:48:12.052
when people could have far more easily
have given up hope, and sometimes did. Um,

03:48:13.192 --> 03:48:17.022
but I don't think we're in one
of those... Like, there, there's

03:48:17.032 --> 03:48:20.782
some major issues like the uncertain
future of technologies, what they might

03:48:20.812 --> 03:48:22.652
do, exactly what you were talking about.

03:48:23.712 --> 03:48:26.912
I think they're solvable problems to
a certain degree. Like, if we can

03:48:27.632 --> 03:48:33.352
rein in some elites, a lot of these problems
can be fixed, and that's not like a

03:48:33.572 --> 03:48:36.822
super difficult... I mean, it's difficult,
but it's not, like, impossible.

03:48:37.392 --> 03:48:41.322
Look, so I grew up
during the Cold War. Uh,

03:48:41.372 --> 03:48:45.212
let's just take the '80s, for example.
And in the '80s, like, there was a

03:48:45.272 --> 03:48:49.052
pervasive sense that nuclear war
could happen at any time and just

03:48:49.072 --> 03:48:52.992
annihilate everything, and we lived under
that. If you look at the popular culture of

03:48:53.052 --> 03:48:56.962
the '80s, it's, like, all, like,
upbeat and cheerful and naive and-

03:48:57.212 --> 03:49:01.112
... like, there was just no correlation.
And then you move into the '90s, and the

03:49:01.172 --> 03:49:05.012
Cold War is over, and everyone's
all depressed. The music gets

03:49:05.072 --> 03:49:08.772
all, like, whiny, and it's
like, "What happened?"

03:49:08.932 --> 03:49:12.872
There's just no correlation. Anyway,
I just think that the, the, it's

03:49:12.932 --> 03:49:16.372
a pervasive sense of
hopelessness or, you know-

03:49:16.382 --> 03:49:20.132
... Despair doesn't always match with,

03:49:20.612 --> 03:49:24.412
like, if you look at the situation
objectively. I mean, yeah, it's, it, it

03:49:24.532 --> 03:49:30.572
can be pretty bad. I-- But there's so
much that's happening that is good-

03:49:30.812 --> 03:49:32.312
... All the time, so.

03:49:32.372 --> 03:49:36.302
- I think this period of human history
will be-- 'cause we've talked

03:49:36.352 --> 03:49:39.392
about the ups and downs of
the Roman Empire. I think

03:49:39.452 --> 03:49:43.252
unquestionably, this period
in history, the 20th,

03:49:44.412 --> 03:49:48.232
the, the late 20th century
and the 21st century will be

03:49:48.372 --> 03:49:52.972
seen as the flourishing of humans.
So if we actually just wake up-

03:49:53.112 --> 03:49:59.372
... it's like what everything around us,
by most measures of human flourishing-

03:49:59.382 --> 03:50:00.612
... we're doing pretty good.

03:50:01.012 --> 03:50:07.192
- The amount of, like, sheer misery is
probably objectively decreasing every year.

03:50:07.552 --> 03:50:11.192
Now, you know, we're also creating
problems, yes, that will cause

